<FIRST>r a AM-TahoeDrownings 1stLd-Writethru a0402 08-24 0191</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tahoe Drownings, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0402,0191</SECOND>
<HEAD>Family of Four Drowns When Sailboat Capsizes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with identities of family; no pickup;
Catlin in 2nd graf is CQ.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GLENBROOK, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A family of four drowned in Lake Tahoe
after their 12-foot sailboat capsized Wednesday in high winds and
rough water, authorities said.
   The dead were identified as Robert Calder, 39; his 30-year-old
wife, Pamela; and the couple's 8-year-old daughter, Jasmine, and
6-year-old son, Catlin, all of Sacramento, Calif., said Douglas
County sheriff's deputies.
   The bodies were found floating nearly in the center of the lake
which turned choppy after a fast-moving cold front pushed winds to
more than 35 mph and temperatures dropped to about 60 degrees.
   Sheriff's Sgt. Larry Coy said the victims wore life belts, but
not the type that will keep a person's head above water. He also
theorized the victims suffered hypothermia due to the high winds and
chilly water.
   Coy said the family had been camping with friends at Bliss State
Park on the California shore and had gone sailing early in the day
before winds picked up and temperatures dropped.
</TEXT>
