<FIRST>r a PM-ValentinoRemembered     08-24 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Valentino Remembered,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fans Pay Tribute to Valentino</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 200 fans and celebrities paid tribute to
actor Rudolph Valentino on the 63rd anniversary of the romantic
idol's death.
   ``Mr. Valentino looked to motion pictures as an art,'' 1985 Emmy
winner Dennis Williams said during a memorial service Wednesday at
the Old Hollywood Cemetery, where Valentino's remains are kept in a
modest crypt.
   In keeping with tradition, the Lady in Black _ her identity
unknown to other mourners _ placed roses, gladiolas and carnations
and a picture of the star next to the crypt.
   Actress Mady Maguire, a prominent film star of the 1920s and
1930s, remembered Valentino as an actor ``with style and
individualism'' whose success, she said, stemmed from his love and
respect for women.
   Born in 1895, the Italian-American leading man achieved fame in
such films as ``The Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse,'' ``The Sheik''
and ``Blood nd Sand.'' He appeared in 33 films.
   Valentino's sudden death on Aug. 23, 1926, of peritonitus
prompted several suicides. His funeral was a national event.
</TEXT>
