<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 0156EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Baltics-History     08-24 0601</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baltics-History,0616</SECOND>
<HEAD>Independence an Exception in Stormy Baltic History</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The independence that many in the Baltic republics
are striving for is a rarity in their long history at the crossroads
of some of Europe's mightiest armies.
   Napoleon, Hitler, Stalin, Russian czars and Swedish kings have
marched their forces across the flat land at the eastern end of the
Baltic Sea.
   Although Lithuanians, Latvians and Estonians are among the oldest
peoples of Europe, they have enjoyed relatively rare moments of
independence, and more often have been fought over by their larger
and more powerful neighbors.
   ``We are slaves,'' Lithuanian philosopher Vitautus Kazlauskas
told an independence rally in the republic's capital of Vilnius on
Wednesday. ``We have been sold so many times.''
   At the beginning of the century the Baltic republics formed part
of the Russian Empire's window on the West, a rich ethnic melting
pot that included Germans, Poles, Jews, Russians and Ukrainians.
   In contrast to the Slavs who dominated the empire, they used the
Latin alphabet and were primarily Roman Catholics and Lutherans
instead of Orthodox Christians.
   Their land guarded the southern approach to the czar's capital of
St. Petersburg at the end of the Gulf of Finland. Finland, across a
narrow gulf, guarded the northern approach.
   But capping a rising tide of nationalism at the end of the 19th
century, the Baltics in 1918 declared their independence after the
czar's empire crumbled under the weight of war and revolution.
   Much of Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania watched Lenin's Bolsheviks
seize power in St. Petersburg from behind German lines. As a bloody
civil war and famine enveloped revolutionary Russia, the Baltics
became a vital listening post for foreign diplomats and journalists
to whom the Russian borders were closed.
   While some were eager to join the ranks of the Red Army's
``internationalist brigades'' and fight for the Bolsheviks in the
bloody civil war that followed the revolution, other Lithuanians,
Latvians and Estonians started building independent countries that
Lenin recognized in a treaty signed in 1920.
   Those small independent lands set up parliamentary governments
and took their place in international affairs, establishing
embassies in the United States as well as many other countries.
   Bu as World War II approached, they found themselves caught
between two of the main adversaries _ Germany and Russia _ just as
they had during World War I.
   And Josef Stalin, eager to regain the territories lost during the
revolution, brought Lithuania, Latvia, and Estonia into the Soviet
sphere of influence in a secret agreement with Hitler signed Aug.
23, 1939, eight days before Germany attacked Poland.
   Less than a year later, Soviet tanks and soldiers entered the
region, which was forcibly annexed to the Soviet Union. Stalin had
thousands of opponents shot or exiled to Siberia, and carried out a
second wave of repression after the Soviet Union reclaimed the
Baltics from Germany at the end of the war.
   For decades the Soviet Union insisted that the republics joined
voluntarily and denied that there had been any secret deal with
Hitler. The United States and other Western countries never
recognized the absorption of the Baltic republics, and almost 50
years later the embassies of the once-independent countries still
function in Washington.
   ``The Soviet Union has done everything to remove the republics of
Estonia, Latvia, and Lithuania from the memory and the map of
Europe, from your libraries and textbooks, your sense of justice,
your grief and your minds,'' Baltic activists said in a declaration
Tuesday on the eve of the Hitler-Stalin agreement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
