<FIRST>d s PM-BRF--Bird-Fire     08-24 0109</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Bird-Fire,0114</SECOND>
<HEAD>Firefighters Say Bird Started Blaze</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JEANNETTE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Don't birds know they shouldn't smoke in
nests?
   Authorities are blaming a bird with a cigarette for starting a
fire that caused $2,500 damage to a home in western Pennsylvania on
Wednesday.
   The bird carried a lighted cigarette butt into its nest on the
house, starting a fire that damaged the porch and some siding,
firefighters said.
   No injuries were reported.
   ``The bird definitely started the fire. That's the only thing it
could be,'' firefighter Robert Carter said.
   Parts of the cigarette were found next to the nest, and the porch
had no electrical fixtures, Carter said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890824-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 0117EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     08-24 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DEMING, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man they call Mister Duck is ducking out
on the Deming Duck Race this year.
   Robert Duck, a seven-time winner, said he's afraid his
participation again this year could cause competitors to quack in
their boots. Instead he plans to rent 60 of his waddlers to others
this weekend for $5 apiece, with proceeds going to charity.
   ``We've won seven of the last nine years, and last year we made a
clean sweep of all three places,'' Duck said. ``People get reluctant
to participate if they don't think they have a chance to win.''
   Duck, an Albuquerque businessman, puts his charges through six
weeks of intensive training before each race and pays close heed to
bloodlines.
   ``I stick to registered ducks,'' Duck said. ``Mine are all in the
American Quarter-Duck Association.''
   Race officials expect 400 ducks to join in two days of racing.
   ``Everyone who's been trying to beat Duck all these years has
added to their flocks and seems determined to win,'' said George
Hoskins of the Deming Chamber of Commerce.
   The world's richest duck race began in 1980 and has grown into a
three-day festival, including a beauty contest for people dressed as
ducks, an outhouse race and a tortilla toss for which the record is
322 feet.
   The ducks race on the lawn of the Luna County Courthouse, along
16-foot, straight-line tracks.
   The fastest fowl wins $2,000. In all, $7,500 in prize money will
be distributed.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If any of the contestants who have been
smooching for 12 days in pursuit of a $10,000 prize plan to give up
anytime soon, they aren't saying. Their lips are sealed.
   Of 15 couples who entered The Great American Kiss-Off Aug. 12
under a tent in the parking lot of a furniture store, six continued
kissing Wednesday.
   Bob Cross, general manager of KWNZ, the radio station
co-sponsoring the contest with the store, said the competitors are
making themselves comfortable by watching television and reading
books while lips remain engaged.
   ``We thought it would go a maximum of two weeks, but it doesn't
look like that now,'' he said.
   ``Once you start and go on this long, you don't want to quit,''
contestant Karen Gonzales explained. ``If it lasts longer, we'll
just do it until we win.''
   Cross said the radio station plans to keep the contest going
until there's a winner. Couples must kiss from 9 a.m. to 9 p.m.,
with five minutes of break time for every hour.
</TEXT>
