<FIRST>r a AM-DisillusionedWalker     08-24 0233</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Disillusioned Walker,0239</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disillusioned Walker for Homeless Gives Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who attempted to dramatize the plight
of the homeless by walking 790 miles to Washington, D.C., has given
up her trek after raising only $1.12 in 130 miles, saying she is
disillusioned with humanity.
   Maria Rogers Johnson, 31, said donations were poor because
publicity about her hike also revealed her criminal convictions on
charges of felony arson, retail theft, and fleeing and eluding
police.
   Ms. Johnson, who attributed her record to a drug and alcohol
abuse problem, said the news in turn prompted her employer to fire
her from her job as house-mother at a home for unwed pregnant women.
   ``I came back a changed person,'' she said. ``I always believed
in the goodness of people. I really don't believe that anymore.''
   Ms. Johnson said her attitude was reinforced by people she met
who refused to donate to her cause, display her brochure or even
give her a place to stay overnight or feed her.
   ``There were a lot of good people out there but, at the same
time, there was a lot of meanness. The bad outnumbered the good,''
she said.
   She said her impressions changed only slightly Wednesday when she
received a letter from an aide to President Bush commending her
``heroism in wanting to spotlight the plight of the homeless through
your own sacrifice.''
</TEXT>
