<FIRST>r a PM-NoseArrest     08-24 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nose Arrest,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Attorney Refuses to File Charges in Clown Nose Arrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A professional clown won't have to pay
through the nose for leaving on a comic disguise at a recent
sheriff's roadblock.
   Although the state attorney's office refused to dismiss it as a
laughing matter, a spokesman said Tuesday that Nancy Cherrington
should not be prosecuted under a law that prohibits wearing a mask
or hood in public.
   She was accused of wearing a plastic nose in public and
disobeying a deputy and faced up to 18 months in jail and up to
$1,500 in fines.
   The 45-year-old Geneva homemaker and professional clown, was
arrested during a roadblock at an apartment complex, where
authorities suspected the drug trade was growing.
   Cherrington had been visiting friends when she was stopped. And
because she often wears a clown nose out in public, she thought she
would try it out on Orange County deputies. But deputies were not
amused when she refused to remove her nose, which was attached to
yellow sunglasses.
   ``I feel better,'' she said after the charges were dropped. ``I
was a little worried.''
   The law would apply to Cherrington only if she had been trying to
conceal her identity, the state attorney's statement said.
``Traditional holiday costumes'' also are exempt from the law.
   Cherrington had planned to wear one of her many clown noses in
court.
   ``I pop on my nose for everybody _ I'm not prejudiced,'' she
said. ``I love the reaction when I put my nose on.''
</TEXT>
