<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 0212EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lutherans     08-24 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lutherans,0471</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consolidated Church Sees Bright Future But Temporary Pains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROSEMONT, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the newly merged Evangelical
Lutheran Church in America said they were loaded with confidence for
the future despite some pressing financial constraints.
   Representatives of the 5.3-million member denomination heard
reports that revenues were running short for budgeted churchwide
programs.
   ``The short-range picture for this church is one of painful
adjustment, and in some cases, severe retrenchment,'' presiding
Bishop Herbert W. Chilstrom said.
   Nevertheless, the ``long-range story is a good one,'' he said.
   ``Our future is secure and bright once we get beyond these
difficult start-up years,'' Chilstrom said Wednesday night at the
opening business session of the church's first national assembly.
   Formed of three previous Lutheran bodies, the denomination is the
nation's fourth largest Protestant church after Southern Baptists,
United Methodists and the mainly black National Baptist Convention.
   The sober discussion of budgetary problems contrasted with a
stirring worship service that opened the eight-day meeting earlier
Wednesday.
   Amid prayers, Scripture readings and antiphonally sung hymns
bounced back and forth between men, women and a black children's
choir, about 2,000 people partook of the consecrated wine and bread
at O'Hare Exposition Center.
   A huge white panel over the podium proclaimed the theme of the
meeting _ ``Many Voices, One Song.''
   Chilstrom expressed hope that the initial legislative work would
produce a sense of cohesiveness and identity and ``set the pattern''
for the future.
   ``We are like a ship setting out into the deep,'' he said. ``If
we set the wrong course _ even by a few degrees _ it will mean that
future assemblies will have to make major corrections.''
   Launched at the start of 1988, the church had a shortfall of
$15.8 million its first 14 months, when expenditures totaled $104.3
million. Continuing revenue shortages forced a cut in 1989
expenditures from $99.3 million to $92.3 million.
   Chilstrom said congregational support for missionaries, campus
ministry, parochial schools, seminaries and various urban and rural
programs ``is not what it should be.''
   Members in 1988 contributed a total of $1.3 billion, up 4.6
percent from the year before and slightly outpacing a 4.4 percent
inflation rate, but the $118 million channeled on to synod and
national programs was down.
   The Rev. Lowell G. Almen, church secretary, reported the number
of Asian, black and Hispanic members rose by 11 percent last year,
now amounting to 1.8 percent of the predominantly white church. The
church has set a goal of raising minority membership to at least 10
percent by the end of its first decade.
   Overall membership, however, sagged slightly, Almen said. ``The
back door of our congregations seems larger than our front door.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
