<FIRST>r w PM-UndergroundExplosions     08-24 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Underground Explosions,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Agency to Decide Soon on Proposed Texas Blast Site</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal officials say they'll decide soon
whether to give in to residents of a small west Texas city who
oppose a proposal to conduct a series of high-powered underground
explosions nearby.
   Officials of the Defense Nuclear Agency met Wednesday with Texas
congressional aides, who said they were told a decision will be made
within 10 days on whether to drop consideration of the Buck King
Ranch 25 miles north of Del Rio, Texas, as a possible site for the
explosions.
   The proposed non-nuclear explosions are intended to simulate the
impact of nuclear blasts on subterranean missile silos and evaluate
the sturdiness of U.S. and Soviet deep-underground command and
control facilities.
   Residents of the arid Texas city say they're concerned the blasts
might endanger their only source of drinking water, the San Felipe
Springs.
   Defense spokeswoman Cheri Abdelnour said the Pentagon agency is
awaiting the results of tests on core samples drilled at the site to
assess the geology.
   ``We're pushing hard for a decision and we expect to have
something in two weeks,'' she said.
   Del Rio officials want the agency to immediately abandon
consideration of the Buck King Ranch. Last week, Mayor Alfred
Gutierrez and City Manager Jeffrey Pomeranz presented top Defense
Nuclear Agency officials with petitions signed by 12,000 of the
city's 40,000 residents opposed to the explosions.
   Sen. Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, whose staff met Wednesday with DNA
officials, said the agency has told him that data from the area is
still being evaluated and a final determination will be made within
a week to 10 days.
   Larry Neal, a spokesman for Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, said the
officials indicated they were concerned ``about the level of
opposition that has developed in Del Rio and that it will be a
factor in their decision.''
   The graduated series of explosions would start with a 1,000-pound
charge in 1990, increasing to 470-ton charge, an equivalent of 300
tons of TNT, in November 1992.
   The DNA said the explosions were designed to have no significant
environmental impact, and they would not affect archeological sites
near the Buck King Ranch.
</TEXT>
