<FIRST>r w PM-MaltLiquor     08-24 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Malt Liquor,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brewers at Odds with Coalition Over Ads Aimed at Minorities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A public interest coalition says brewers should
halt glitzy malt liquor ads that target blacks and Hispanics, but an
industry group says there's nothing ``sinister'' about the ad
campaign.
   ``We make no apologies for marketing a malt liquor, or for the
fact that this particular product is especially popular in the black
and Hispanic markets,'' said Stephen J. Burrows, a vice president of
St. Louis-based Anheuser-Busch, which makes ``King Cobra'' malt
liquor.
   Industry representatives say malt liquor is advertised more
heavily in the black and Hispanic communities because it is popular
there. They also point to various reports, including one from the
Federal Trade Commission, discounting any link between alcohol
advertising and alcohol abuse.
   However, the coalition of 22 health and community groups formed
around the Washington-based Center for Science in the Public
Interest wants government to limit the alcohol content of malt
liquor to 5 percent and pressure brewers into stopping ads targeted
at the two minority groups.
   ``As physicians who encounter all too many alcohol-related
problems in our offices and emergency rooms, we know that malt
liquor is a faster way to get drunk or destroy your liver,'' said
Dr. Walter L. Faggett, a District of Columbia physician speaking for
the black National Medical Association.
   ``Not only are malt liquor products harmful themselves, but like
wine coolers and other alcohol beverages they are `gateway' drugs
that pave the way to crack cocaine, heroin and polysubstance
addiction,'' he said.
   The Beer Institute, an industry group, defended the ads.
   ``There is nothing at all unusual or sinister about marketers
tailoring their marketing campaigns to particular market segments.''
   Peter Bell, executive director of the Minneapolis-based Institute
on Black Chemical Abuse, said at a Wednesday news conference that
blacks, who make up 10 percent of the U.S. population, consume
one-third of all malt liquor.
   ``The central question we must focus on is the fragile nature of
the black community today,'' Bell said. ``Can we afford to have
aggressive marketing campaigns targeted toward it? There's not one
issue on the black agenda _ housing, health care, crime, education _
that is not negatively impacted by alcohol and drug abuse.''
   Carlos Molina, president of the Latino Caucus of the American
Public Health Association, criticized the ads for exploiting and
perpetuating ``another Latino stereotype: `super macho.'''
   The coalition is asking Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady to
restrict the alcohol content of malt liquor to 5 percent.
   Beer generally has a 4.6 percent alcohol content, while malt
liquor begins at 5.6 percent and one brand contains 10.9 percent,
although most are under 7 percent.
   CSPI, a non-profit advocacy group that normally concerns itself
with general health issues, has been criticizing the advertising
practices of the nation's breweries, saying they target young men as
well.
   The issue has been in the forefront since then-Surgeon General C.
Everett Koop said in a May report on drunk driving that
youth-oriented advertising and other promotional practices appealing
to youth should be restricted.
   The industry, through the Beer Institute and individual
corporations, maintains it's putting money back into the community
through contributions to education and other activities.
   Burrows said Anheuser-Busch has contributed $65 million over the
last 10 years to the United Negro College Fund and the Hispanic
Scholarship Foundation.
</TEXT>
