<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 0319EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Extradition     08-24 0680</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Extradition,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Extradition of Drug Suspects Easier Said than Done</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. efforts to extradite suspected criminals
hiding in other countries frequently fail, in large part because the
suspects can't be found or other nations are reluctant to arrest
them, officials say.
   Federal officials last year requested the return of 253 citizens
and foreigners wanted in the United States for crimes ranging from
drug trafficking to money laundering, according to the State
Department.
   Only 73 were forced back.
   ``It takes time to get these people,'' a State Department
official said Wednesday. ``Also, when we ask for someone to be
arrested, that doesn't mean they can always be found.''
   The Justice Department issued a most-wanted list Tuesday for a
dozen Colombian men charged with drug-related crimes in the United
States. But bringing such suspects to American soil for trial is
rare.
   ``In most cases the fugitives can't be found. That certainly is
the case in Colombia,'' said the State Department official who,
following department rules, spoke on the condition of not being
further identified.
   The situation in Colombia is further complicated by the
reluctance of judges and magistrates there to anger the nation's
powerful drug cartels, which have assassinated hundreds of jurists
and politicians who dared to oppose them.
   The latest such incident occurred last week with the murder of
presidential candidate Luis Carlos Galan, who had promised a
government crackdown on drug traffickers.
   The only notable extradition from Colombia came in 1987, when
cocaine smuggling kingpin Carlos Lehder was arrested in Colombia and
brought to the United States within hours. Lehder, charged with
conspiring to import 3.3 tons of cocaine into the United States, was
sentenced to life imprisonment here.
   Another Colombian, Juan Ramon Matta, was nabbed in Honduras by
U.S. officials in 1988 and whisked out of the country to the United
States. But that action prompted violent anti-American
demonstrations because Honduras did not have an extradition treaty
with the United States.
   Matta is jailed on drug charges in connection with the 1985
torture-murder in Mexico of U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration
agent Enrique Camarena Salazar.
   Despite those successes, the State Department official said,
extradition remains ``a complex and expensive procedure.''
   The process starts with formal charges against a person who is
overseas. The case then goes to the Justice Department, which asks
the State Department to request that the host country arrest the
suspect.
   Local authorities normally must decide whether to make the arrest
and whether to permit the person to be deported.
   The State Department official said there is no master list
breaking down the types of crimes those on the U.S. extradition list
face in the United States.
   ``It's not like a 10-most-wanted list,'' said Justice Department
spokesman Joe Krovisky. ``We go after them as the requests come in.''
   Krovisky said the Justice Department normally will not identify
the people it seeks abroad, saying: ``That information is not
released until the person is returned to the United States or the
case is made public in the other country.''
   A spokeswoman for the State Department's Bureau of International
Narcotics Matters confirmed that the United States is seeking the
extradition of ``four or five people from Pakistan for drugs,'' but
she had no other information on the cases or other countries.
   Pakistan is one of the world's main suppliers of high-grade
heroin. The State Department says Pakistani opium production last
year was more than 200 tons.
   Neither the State nor Justice departments would release
information about traffickers operating in the remote ``Golden
Triangle,'' the heroin-rich region where Burma, Thailand and Laos
share a border.
   In some cases, most notably in Panama, the United States has
virtually no chance of having someone extradited to America soil.
Panama and the United States don't have an extradition treaty.
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, the de facto leader of Panama, was
indicted on drug trafficking charges in Florida in 1988, and leaders
of Colombian drug cartels are reported to have gone to Panama during
an earlier extradition scare in their home country in the mid-1980s.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
