<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 0224EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-OAS-Panama     08-24 0681</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-OAS-Panama,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>OAS Concerned Over Continued Impasse in Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rejecting U.S. appeals for a tougher stance,
the Organization of American States approved a statement early today
expressing deep concern over the failure of an OAS mediating team to
promote a democratic transfer of power in Panama.
   The statement approved by OAS foreign ministers after 12 hours of
marathon closed-door negotiations ``resolutely exhorts'' Panamanians
to settle their differences before Sept. 1. That is the date on
which the Panamanian constitution calls for the installation of a
new president.
   The United States joined the 30 other OAS members in approving
the statement at 12:28 a.m. EDT even though the document did not
demand that Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega step down as commander of
Panama's military forces.
   That has been a consistent U.S. position for 18 months, but many
other OAS members believe an endorsement of that stance could set a
dangerous precedent. They see the U.S. position as a violation of
OAS provisions barring intervention in the internal affairs of
member countries.
   During the meeting, which started shortly after noon and extended
until after midnight, a number of draft statements were circulated
among delegates assembled at the ornate OAS headquarters building a
few blocks from the State Department.
   But all met with resistance from both the U.S. and Panamanian
delegates. In the end, the delegates approved a simple
five-paragraph resolution that offended no one but said little.
   The plenary session had been scheduled to get under way at 3 p.m.
Wednesday but it wasn't gaveled to order until 12:21 a.m. today.
Approval of the statement came seven minutes later.
   The delegates expressed ``deep concern'' that parties to Panama's
political conflict have been unable to reach a solution and said the
mediating team would be available for additional consultations upon
request.
   Afterward, Panamanian Foreign Minister Jorge Ritter credited the
four OAS mediators with getting a dialogue started among Panamanian
officials and opposition leaders.
   But the chief U.S. delegate, Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence
Eagleburger, said that until democracy is restored in Panama, each
member of the 31-nation OAS has an obligation ``to isolate this
outlaw regime.''
   He said Noriega's purported alliance with cocaine traffickers is
aggression ``as surely as Adolf Hitler's invasion of Poland 50 years
ago was aggression.'' Two Florida grand juries indicted Noriega last
year on drug trafficking charges.
   The Panamanian crisis erupted in May when authorities threw out
the results of a national election which, according to independent
observers, had been won handily by the anti-Noriega candidate,
Guillermo Endara. The OAS mediation effort was approved a week after
the election results were voided.
   Wednesday's meeting was the fourth time in four months that the
foreign ministers gathered here to discuss the crisis. In the
interim, the mediators made numerous trips to Panama attempting to
hammer out a solution.
   In the absence of an agreement, it is unclear what will happen in
Panama on Sept. 1, the date when an ``elected president'' is due to
take office.
   Ritter told reporters Wednesday night the government has a strong
incentive to reach an agreement with the opposition before that date
in order to satisfy the country's constitutional requirements.
   The mediating team issued a report to the ministers Wednesday
expressing optimism that a restoration of democratic rule in Panama
may be within reach.
   But State Department officials said there was no basis for any
such a conclusion and a Panamanian opposition leader, Ricardo Arias
Calderon, called the mediation effort a failure because Noriega
refused to negotiate in good faith.
   State Department officials objected not only to the positive tone
of the report but also to its criticism of U.S. policy toward
Panama. The report called attention to the ``negative effect'' on
the negotiations ``of the maneuvers carried out by the armed forces
of the United States'' in Panama. U.S. military personnel in Panama
numbers about 10,000.
   A State Department official, speaking privately, expressed
irritation that the report singled out the United States for
criticism without mentioning Noriega by name at any point in the
report.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
