<FIRST>r a PM-TravelingPoets Bjt   08-24 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Traveling Poets, Bjt,0600</SECOND>
<HEAD>LA's Beat Poets Take to Road to Spread the Word</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ROGERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 1950s were a time of innocence, says poet
S.A. Griffin, when people such as beat writers Jack Kerouac and Neal
Cassidy could pack up a big old car and head down the road just to
see what was there.
   ``It's time for someone to do it again,'' Griffin said shortly
before he and four other poets piled into a rusty, white 1959
Cadillac for a three-week reading tour across the Southwest.
   ``I feel it's very important to do this,'' said Griffin, 35, a
lean, muscular man who wears rose-colored glasses, painter's caps
and bears a strong resemblance to his hero Cassidy, the real-life
star of Kerouac's beat novel ``On the Road.''
   ``It could inspire someone else to realize how big this poetry
thing is,'' he said.
   The poetry thing Griffin refers to is what he and his fellow
travelers _ Michael Brunner, Doug Knott, Bobbo Staron and Scott
Wannberg _ say is a booming beat scene that has emerged in Los
Angeles.
   Thus the five have put together the Karma Bums tour and are
spreading their words in clubs in Albuquerque, Santa Fe and Taos,
N.M., Denver and Boulder, Colo., and San Francisco before returning
home for an end-of-tour reading in September.
   Once upon a time, performance art was common in cities like San
Francisco and New York, said Wannberg, whose second book, ``The
Electric Yes Indeed,'' has just been published by Shelf Life Press.
   Now, he said, the scene has shifted to Southern California, which
was once looked upon by the other big cities as a cultural abyss.
   ``It seems to have fizzled in San Francisco,'' added Wannberg, a
big, bearish man who talks in the same dramatic Charles
Bukowski-influenced tones in which he writes. ``There is definitely
more happening here now than many people would admit to.''
   Readings are around town just about every night, noted Wannberg,
36, who has read locally for more than a dozen years.
   They take place in venues that include both trendy West Side
bistros, where celebrities sometimes read their works, and gritty
biker bars, where the performers must vie with noisy drunks for the
audience's attention.
   Much of what gets read in both places, Wannberg acknowledged, is
patently awful. Some of it, however, is also quite good, he was
quick to add.
   ``But if we're having a poetry renaissance, I don't think it's a
renaissance that's actually recognized by most of the rest of the
country,'' he saidr is one small, free-form effort to change that,
said Griffin.
   As they do in Los Angeles, the poets reciteheir work from appear
in clubs in one city after another. Often they act out their work on
stage as well.
   They say they hope the audience joins in whenever it feels the
massive in the United States,'' Griffin said. ``But too many peple
turn their backs on it because cliques existither somebody at a
reading or somebody with a master's degree telling them about
Shakespeare.''
   Or, as Knrned-poet, quipped just before the tour kicked off
Friday amid the thumping of bongo drums at os Angeles club: ``Poets
are those guys with skinny chests who can't play guitars very well.''
   The audience _ largely bearded, buckskin-jacketed and middle-aged
_ howled its approval.
</TEXT>
