<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 0340EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-HairPulling     08-24 0654</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hair Pulling,0669</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Helps Women Stop Pulling Out Their Hair</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millions of Americans plagued by an uncontrollable
impulse to yank out their hair can get control of their bizarre
habit and stop themselves from going bald by taking a new medicine,
researchers report today.
   Experts say it has become evident in recent years that this
affliction is common, even though most victims keep it secret by
wearing wigs or fake eye brows.
   In a report in the New England Journal of Medicine, doctors show
that an experimental drug called clomipramine can help people reduce
their hair pulling and sometimes stop it entirely.
   The drug ``allows them to say `no,''' said Dr. Susan E. Swedo.
``They still have the urge, but their ability to resist it
increased.''
   No one knows precisely how many people pull out their hair, a
disorder known as trichotillomania. Estimates range as high as 8
million Americans, although Swedo said that between 2 million and 4
million is probably more accurate. Virtually all of them are women.
   Researchers said that hair pulling has been poorly recognized, in
part, because victims are adept at hiding the consequences of their
obsession. While many wear wigs, others lie that they are bald
because they take chemotherapy. Some who have a fringe of hair comb
the remaining strands over the top, just as balding men do.
   ``They are convinced that they are crazy,'' said Swedo. ``They
have to do this thing that is painful and disgusting, yet they
continue. They struggle against it all their lives.''
   Victims of the obsession, which frequently starts just after
puberty, often don't realize they have a treatable disorder that
affects millions of people. In fact, nine of the patients who took
part in the latest study sought doctors' help after learning about a
related ailment known as obsessive-compulsive disorder on a
television report last year.
   Swedo, a researcher at the National Institute of Mental Health,
tested clomipramine on 13 women. Three completely stopped pulling
their hair, while the rest had at least a 50 percent reduction in
the severity of their symptoms.
   The same drug has also been shown in other studies to be
effective in helping people with obsessive-compulsive disorder. The
medicine has not yet been approved by the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration for routine use. However, doctors can obtain it from
its maker, Ciba-Geigy, for treating severe cases.
   A newly approved drug called fluoxetine, or Prozac, also appears
to be effective against obsessive-compulsive disorder and hair
pulling, although it has not been as widely tested as clomipramine.
   Dr. Michael A. Jenike of Massachusetts General Hospital said that
until the development of these medicines, obsessive-compulsive
disorder ``was considered to be untreatable. Now we can get many
people completely better or at least well enough so they can
function. It's not an exaggeration to call this a breakthrough.''
   The Obsessive Compulsive Foundation estimates that as many as 5
million Americans have the anxiety disorder. Typically, they have
irrational compulsions to do something over and over, such as wash
their hands or make sure the door is locked. They may wash for five
hours a day or check the door 50 or 60 times, even though they
realize the repetition is senseless.
   Both clomipramine and fluoxetine can also be used to treat
depression. The drugs appear to relieve hair pulling and other
obsessive behavior by increasing the brain's supply of a chemical
messenger known as serotonin.
   In the latest study, patients successively took clomipramine and
another depression medicine called desipramine. While they got
markedly better on clomipramine, the other drug had little effect.
   Swedo said that clomipramine may work best when combined with
behavior modification training.
   ``You can decrease symptoms by half or three-quarters and still
be bald,'' she said. ``You just don't pull so fast. We don't mean to
imply that clomipramine is the only treatment.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890824-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 0341EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-UninsuredNewborns     08-24 0363</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Uninsured Newborns,0374</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study Links Lack of Health Insurance with Risky Births</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Babies born into families without medical insurance
are more likely to start life in poor health, probably because of
limited access to care, a study reported today concludes.
   The research found that those whose parents have no insurance are
about one-third more likely than those from insured families to die
or be seriously ill at birth.
   The study was not designed to definitely pinpoint the cause.
However, the authors said they believe that ``the elevated and
increasing risks of adverse outcomes in uninsured newborns are
explained most plausibly by diminished access to care, together with
other factors related to lower socio-economic status.''
   The study was based on a review of the records of more than
146,000 births in the San Francisco Bay area in 1982, 1984 and 1986.
During that time, the percentage of newborns without health
insurance increased from 5.5 percent to 8 percent. The increases
were largest among people of Hispanic and Asian backgrounds.
   By 1986, the chance of an adverse hospital outcome _ defined as a
prolonged hospital stay, transfer to another hospital or death _ was
31 percent greater among the uninsured babies, even when racial and
ethnic differences were taken into account.
   The study was directed by Dr. Paula Braveman of the University of
California, San Francisco, and published in today's New England
Journal of Medicine.
   In an accompanying editorial, Drs. Donald M. Berwick of the
Harvard Community Health Plan and Howard H. Hiatt of Brigham and
Women's Hospital said they doubted that insurance alone would close
the gap.
   ``The relations between poverty and poor health are too deep and
intricate to be disrupted with a mere insurance form,'' they wrote.
   Among the study's other findings:
   _In 1986, 20 percent of Hispanic newborns were uninsured,
compared with 3 percent of blacks, 6 percent of whites and 12
percent of Asians.
   _Uninsured blacks were more than twice as likely as insured
blacks to have sickly newborns.
   _Babies who required transfer to another hospital ran up bills
averaging nearly $56,000.
   _Low birth weight and malnutrition were 28 percent more common in
newborns without insurance.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
