<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     08-24 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up Against Yen, Shares Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose Thursday against the Japanese
yen in Tokyo while share prices lost ground in quiet trading.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which lost 221.07 points Wednesday, dropped another
106.73 points, or 0.3 percent, closing the day at 34,786.55.
   The dollar finished trading at 143.60 yen, up 1.25 yen from
Wednesday's close of 142.35 yen. After opening higher at 143.45 yen,
the U.S. currency ranged between 143.37 and 143.83 yen.
   Traders said the dollar gained ground due to news reports that a
key official in the Cabinet of Prime Minister Toshiki Kaifu would
resign over a sex scandal.
   In a nationally televised news conference late Thursday morning,
Chief Cabinet Secretary Tokuo Yamashita apologized, saying ``that
such news would be reported was due completely to my own
indiscretion.''
   Yamashita, 69, who is the government's main spokesman, said he
was ``seriously considering'' whether to resign or stay in office.
   Yamashita's remarks were prompted by an article in the respected
weekly Shukan Shincho magazine alleging that, starting in 1984, he
had an affair with a 26-year-old office worker he met at a Tokyo bar
where she worked part time. It said the affair ended in 1987.
   On the stock market, securities dealers said traders were
discouraged by a decline in the value of the yen against the dollar.
   ``Also contributing to the drop in the index were reports of the
Yamashita (affair),'' said Masahiro Umemori, an equity researcher at
Nomura Securities Co.
</TEXT>
