<FIRST>r i PM-DrugSummit     08-24 0368</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drug Summit,0378</SECOND>
<HEAD>Venezuela, Bolivia Watch for Colombia Drug Lords; Summit Proposed</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Colombia, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Venezuela increased its forces on the
border to keep out drug dealers who may try to escape a crackdown in
neighboring Colombia, President Carlos Andres Perez said.
   In Bolivia, authorities said Wednesday that border patrols also
were reinforced and police helicopters were on alert for Colombian
traffickers.
   Perez also proposed that nations of the Western Hemisphere hold a
summit to come up with strategies to combat drug trafficking.
   ``Narcotics trafficking has to be fought as the most abominable
crime of the century,'' the Venezuelan leader said late Tuesday in a
speech at the anniversary celebration of a cooperative educational
institute.
   Perez said it also would have to be considered a crime ``without
frontiers'' to combat effectively.
   Venezuelan press accounts have warned of the possibility of drug
smugglers entering Venezuela to escape the recent crackdown in
Colombia.
   Perez said Venezuela had tightened patrols along its 1,000-mile
border with Colombia, traditionally an area plagued by smuggling and
guerrilla activity.
   Venezuela does not have a history of drug trafficking, although
it is being increasingly used as a transfer point for cocaine and
other drugs being smuggled to Europe and the United States,
according to police.
   In Bolivia, however, there are dozens of cocaine processing labs
in the northern Beni jungle region, and officials increased patrols
along Bolivia's border with Brazil.
   The U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration has said that the raw
material for at least one-third of the cocaine that reaches U.S. and
European markets is produced in Bolivia.
   ``The violence and corruption that exists in Colombia could be
transferred to Bolivia, especially because of the offensive by the
Colombian government,'' said Bolivia Sen. Daniel Cabezas, head of
the Senate committee on drugs.
   In June, two Colombian drug traffickers were captured when police
raided the town of Santa Ana de Yacuma, home to some of Bolivia's
top cocaine traffickers. There have been several killings in Santa
Cruz, 450 miles east of La Paz, involving Colombian drug runners,
police have said.
   At least 350,000 Bolivians make their livings growing coca
leaves. The leaves are processed into cocaine paste, which is
refined into cocaine.
</TEXT>
