<FIRST>r a PM-PlaneCrash     08-24 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Plane Crash,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Family of Four Killed in Plane Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIVERMORE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A family of four was killed when their
small airplane hit a power line that had been strung over a highway
two days earlier.
   The pilot, Paul Humphries, 39, apparently was flying low over
I-580 near Altamont Pass to navigate his way to the Livermore
Airport beneath a thick layer of clouds. The plane clipped one of
four lines strung over the highway.
   The family from Pleasanton was returning Tuesday night from a
visit with relatives in Vancouver, British Columbia.
   Killed were Humphries, his wife, Lorraine, 37, son, Stephen, 10,
and daughter, Michelle, 6, said Tom Spigelmire, a close friend of
the family's.
   However, the Alameda County Coroner's office would not confirm
the identification of the victims late Wednesday.
   The plane careened a few hundred feet then erupted into a
fireball and ignited the hillside, witnesses said. The plane, a
four-seat single engine Mooney, was owned by the family, authorities
said.
   The steel cables that some authorities said were to blame for the
crash were strung on Sunday but weren't transmitting power at the
time, said Jim Feider, deputy manager for the Western Area Power
Administration office in Sacramento.
</TEXT>
