<DOCNO> AP890824-0055 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 0645EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-GutterStickers     08-24 0206</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gutter Stickers,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>County Posting Stickers By Sewers to Warn Against Bay Pollution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UPPER MARLBORO, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prince George's County is posting
stickers next to all 32,000 county gutters reminding residents that
what goes into the sewers eventually winds up in the Chesapeake Bay.
   ``Do Not Litter - Chesapeake Bay Drainage,'' read the stickers
which officials hope to complete distributing in the next two years.
   ``Storm drains are for rain only and not for oil and not for
grass clippings and not for Styrofoam,'' said County Executive
Parris N. Glendening.
   ``Some home mechanics and home gardeners dump their oil waste and
yard waste in storm drains on Saturday,'' Glendening said Wednesday.
``On Sunday, they go to the bay and bemoan the oil slicks and other
pollutants. Some people think it goes to sewage treatment plants,
but not so.''
   Prince George's County is the first in the state to place
warnings on storm gutters, although other counties encourage
community groups to do so.
   County environmental officials estimate that about half of the
organic pollutants in the bay, nitrogen and phosphorus, come from
storm water runoff collected by storm gutters. The two elements,
when present in extreme quantities, deoxygenate water and disrupt
the bay's ecological balance.
</TEXT>
