<FIRST>r i PM-Baltics-Glance     08-24 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baltics-Glance,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baltic Republics at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Baltics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Independent states until a Soviet-Nazi treaty
signed 50 years ago deeded them to the Kremlin's sphere of
influence, the three restive Baltic republics of western Soviet
Union have been raising a growing clamor for control over their
internal affairs.
   Here are some facts and figures on these republics:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ESTONIA _ Located across the Gulf of Finland from Finland and
bounded on the east by the Russian republic, Estonia has an area of
18,040 square miles and a population of 1.6 million. Two-thirds of
its inhabitants are ethnic Estonians, who speak a language related
to Finnish. Russians make up 28 percent of the population. Capital:
Tallinn.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   LATVIA _ Sandwiched between its two Baltic neighbors and bordered
on the east by Russia and Byelorussia, Latvia dramatically shows the
influence of the Russian influx feared by Baltic militants. Results
for the 1989 national census are not yet available, but Latvians
already are a minority in their homeland of 25,480 square miles, and
may number only 40 percent of the republic's 2.7 million residents.
Capital: Riga.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   LITHUANIA _ The largest and most populous of the Baltic republics
with 26,080 square miles and 3.7 million inhabitants, Lithuania is
bounded by Latvia, Byelorussia and Russia and has a short frontier
with Poland. Lithuanians total some 80 percent of the population,
making this the Baltic state with the highest percentage of its
titular nationality. Capital: Vilnius.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890824-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 0648EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Hitler-StalinPact     08-24 0256</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hitler-Stalin Pact,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>East Germany Acknowledges, Defends Hitler-Stalin Pact</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Baltics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East Germany has openly acknowledged for the first
time the existence of secret protocols in the 1939 non-aggression
pact between Nazi Germany and the Soviet Union.
   The Communist East German leadership strongly defended the pact,
saying the treaty gave Moscow time to prepare for war.
   Communist Party historian Heinz Kuehnrich said in a newspaper
interview Wednesday that the pact, which contained protocols that
put the then-independent Baltic republics into the Soviet orbit, was
essential to Moscow's defense strategy.
   ``The Soviet Union gained territory for its defense (against Nazi
aggression),'' Kuehnrich told the Junge Welt newspaper, a party
organ for young people.
   On Aug. 23, 1939, Hitler and Stalin divided Eastern Europe into
spheres of influence. Within days, Nazi Germany invaded Poland. The
Soviet Union later occupied eastern Poland.
   Less than a year later, Stalin took over the Baltic states of
Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania. That action is now an explosive issue
in the Soviet Baltic region, with the 50-year anniversary sparking
increased demands for independence.
   Western accounts say the pact paved the way for the beginning of
World War II.
   Kuehnrich called the interpretation ``nonsense, that stands the
facts on their heads.''
   He denied the pact set the stage for war.
   ``The timing of the pact and the beginning of war has been used
to trick people into believing that the Soviet Union was partly
responsible for the war,'' the historian said.
   ``Hitler wanted war, not the Soviet Union,'' Kuehnrich said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
