<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     08-24 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Higher, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was higher in quiet European trading
this morning, but down from its earlier levels.
   Gold prices fell.
   The dollar jumped in Asian trading and opened strongly in the
European business day. But then it fell back a bit on profit-taking.
   The foreign exchange market was being dominated by chart-related
movements, with most technical analysts calling for the dollar to
rise in the near-term, traders said.
   ``After 1.9400 (West German marks) held, the dollar was bound to
rebounce,'' one Rome trader said. He added, however, that the dollar
was likely to encounter profit-taking intermittently.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.5660 to buy one pound, compared with $1.5700 late Wednesday.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Wednesday:
   _1.9603 West German marks, up from 1.9555
   _1.6893 Swiss francs, up from 1.6870
   _6.6135 French francs, up from 6.5965
   _2.2133 Dutch guilders, up from 2.2000
   _1,406.50 Italian lire, up from 1,399.50
   _1.1760 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1727
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose 1.25 yen to a closing 143.60 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at a lower rate of 143.35 yen.
   Gold opened in London at $363.30 a troy ounce, compared with late
Wednesday's $364.25. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion
dealers fixed a recommended price of $363.60.
   In Zurich, the bid was $363.75 compared with $363.85 late
Wednesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $2.48 to close at $364.75.
   Silver was quoted in London at $5.17 a troy ounce, down from
Wednesday's $5.19.
</TEXT>
