<DOCNO> AP890824-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 0842EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0504 08-24 0739</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0504,0761</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 1st item to UPDATE and precede to LONDON, add survivors;
SUBS 3rd graf of Anderson item to CORRECT spelling of Huntington; A PMs
separate moved on Laing as a0516.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>R.D. Laing</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   R.D. Laing, the British psychiatrist who became a
counterculture hero of the 1960s with his controversial attacks on
the nuclear family, died while vacationing in France, his son said
today. He was 61.
   The Scottish-born psychiatrist collapsed on a tennis court
Wednesday in the southern city of St. Tropez, said his son Adrian.
He said he did not know the cause of death. ``It's a shock,'' he
said in an interview.
   An unorthodox pioneer in the treatment of schizophrenics, Ronald
David Laing jarred traditional psychiatry with his first book, ``The
Divided Self: An Existential Study in Sanity and Madness,''
published in 1960.
   He rejected notions that schizophrenia is a genetic or biological
aberration, believing instead in the family's role in creating the
disease, although he later became more open to physiological
theories, said his son.
   Laing's views on the strains the nuclear family could put on an
individual's sanity fell in with the rebellious spirit of the 1960s
counterculture, which made him one of its gurus.
   Contending that most psychiatry added to patient misery, he
refused to treat them with drugs or electric shocks unless they
asked for them.
   ``Sanity, Madness and the Family,'' written with A.A. Esterson
and published in 1964, presented case histories based on his
approach to families.
   At Kingsley Hall, the London residential treatment hostel he
helped to run, he experimented with the therapeutic use of mescaline
and LSD. He was a prominent campaigner for the legalization of
marijuana.
   He is survived by his common-law wife, Margarita, an infant son
by her; his first wife, Anne, and their daughters Caron and Fiona;
and sons Paul and Adrian, said Adrian Laing.
   His survivors also include two sons from a second marriage, Adam
and Max, and a daughter Natasha, as well as a child Benjamin by
another common-law wife, said Adrian.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Cleland Anderson</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cleland ``Andy'' Anderson, an editor who worked
for The Associated Press for 34 years, died Monday of natural causes
at age 81.
   Anderson earned a bachelor's degree in journalism at Ohio State
University. In the 1930s, he worked for the Ohio State Journal and
Ohio Legion News, both in Columbus; Toledo News-Bee and The
Washington Post.
   Anderson joined the AP in 1938 in Huntington, W.Va., and
transferred to Baltimore in 1940.
   In 1944, he transferred to New York, and worked in the AP
Newsfeatures department and later on the main national news desk.
Anderson retired in 1972.
   He is survived by a son, Richard H. Anderson, of Stamford, Conn.;
a daughter, Margaret Surridge, of Loveland, Ohio; a sister, Enid
Coleman, of New York state; and two grandchildren.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Eugene Robel</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eugene Frank Robel, a labor activist who won a
U.S. Supreme Court ruling against a law that banned communists from
working in defense plants, was struck by a train and killed Sunday.
He was 78.
   Robel, a retired Todd Shipyard machinist, was a lifelong member
of the American Communist Party.
   During the 1950s, he was once called to testify before the House
Committee on Un-American Activities. Robel and six others were
expelled from Local 79 of the Machinists union. He was allowed to
continue to work and continued to support unions and honor picket
lines.
   In the 1960s, with help from the American Civil Liberties Union,
Robel challenged the Internal Security Act of 1950, a section of
which forbade communists from working in military plants.
   He was arrested in 1963 for holding communist beliefs while
working at the shipyard. The U.S. Supreme Court, ruling in his case,
overturned the law's provision in 1967.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Mark Finston</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mark Finston, a columnist for 24 years with
The Star-Ledger of Newark, died Tuesday at his home at age 54. The
cause of death was not immediately determined.
   Finston received a law degree in 1959 from the University of
Pennsylvania. However, he lost interest in the profession and joined
The Times of Trenton in 1961. He moved in 1965 to the Ledger, where
he wrote the ``Reporter at Large'' column.
   Finston is survived by his wife, Beth; twin daughters Deborah and
Elizabeth; his mother; a sister and a stepsister.
</TEXT>
