<FIRST>r a PM-INS-Cards 1stLd-Writethru a0520 08-24 0284</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-INS-Cards, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0520,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>INS `Green' Cards _ Which Aren't Green, Anyway _ Get New Look</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, `The immigration ...' to CORRECT name to Jervis,
sted Javis.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Immigration officials will change the color of
immigrant work permits, commonly known as green cards, to prevent
counterfeiters from duplicating the documents.
   The new cards, to be issued to aliens who have achieved
permanent-resident status, are rose-colored on the front and will
bear the photograph, signature and fingerprint of the worker. The
reverse side will bear pink-to-blue rainbow shading to cut down on
forgeries, the Immigration and Naturalization Service said Wednesday.
   ``The more you change the color the more confusing it is to
counterfeiters,'' explained Neil Henry, deputy Los Angeles district
director for legalization for the INS.
   Officials say the temporary work permits probably will still be
called green cards, however. The cards haven't been green since the
1960s, Henry said, but the name has stuck through several color
changes, most recently blue and off-white.
   The immigration service does not plan to replace the 10 million
cards already in circulation, Verne Jervis, an INS spokesperson in
Washington, told The New York Times. The new cards will be phased
in, issued to new aliens, workers who have lost their cards, or
permanent residents' children when they reach age 14.
   INS Western Regional Director Bill King said the cards will be
issued in conjunction with INS plans to begin accepting applications
for seasonal agricultural worker status.
   The four-year program will permit noncitizen participants to
legally enter or remain in the United States as agricultural
workers, King said. The filing period begins Sept. 1 and runs
through Nov. 30.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
