<DOCNO> AP890824-0065 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 0906EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FitzgeraldSearch 1stLd-Writethru a0487 08-24 0618</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fitzgerald Search, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0487,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researchers View Wreck of Edmund Fitzgerald</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with research ship back out today,
more background on Edmund Fitzgerald. Pickup 5th graf pvs, `Wednesday,
researchers...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SST</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAIGE St. JOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITEFISH POINT, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Explorers in a research boat
returned today for a second glimpse of the wreck of the Edmund
Fitzgerald, after an initial look showed the ship remarkably intact
in the cold depths of Lake Superior.
   ``This is amazing, totally amazing,'' archaeologist Phil Wright,
on board as an observer for the Canadian Marine Heritage
Conservation Program in Ottawa, said Wednesday as he watched a
monitor in the dark control room of the research vessel.
   He watched the screen intently as a small submersible robot sent
up images, showing the large white ship upright in the black mud,
its name clearly visible on its side.
   The Edmund Fitzgerald had taken on more than 26 tons of
concentrated iron ore pellets at Superior, Wis., and was bound for
Cleveland when it sank in a gale Nov. 10, 1975. The 729-foot vessel
disappeared in Canadian water 17 miles off the coast of northern
Michigan. All 29 aboard died, their bodies never recovered.
Singer-songwriter Gordon Lightfoot recounted the tragedy in a ballad
that became a popular hit in the 70s.
   Wednesday, researchers lowered a submersible robot carrying
specialized video cameras 556 feet down to the wreck. The view was
startlingly clear.
   The first glimpse was a ghostly faint image of the ship's white
radio tower.
   As the robot dropped lower and nearer, the battered pilothouse
loomed onto the screen, showing crisp pictures of portholes burst by
tremendous pressure, electronic equipment tossed about within, and
the ship's bell with its clapper tied by a cord.
   The hull remained white, barely dusted with lake sdiment and just
beginning to rust where the force of the sinking had bent and ripped
its steel sides.
   ``It was just like tinfoil,'' said Chris Nicholson, who developed
and piloted the small video robot attached by cable to the mother
ship. Three-dimensional images from the robot will enable
researchers to map details of the Fitzgerald down to the centimeter.
   Searchers had expected to encounter bodies of some of the
Fitzgerald's American crew, but none was seen in Wednesday's initial
exploration.
   ``We are not here to disturb, we are only here to remember,''
said Clifford Wilson, captain of the research boat, Grayling, on
loan for the expedition from the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service.
Wilson held a short shipboard memorial service for the crew before
the robot was lowered.
   Tom Farnquist, director of the Lakes Shipwreck Historical
Society, said the reason for the search was to produce sharp, color
footage of the wreck to satisfy public curiosity.
   The expedition, coordinated by the society, is testing the new
video system for underwater exploration. After more looks at the
Fitzgerald today, the team hopes to document the deep remains of as
many as five other ships preserved by the depth and coldness of the
largest of the Great Lakes.
   The official U.S. Coast Guard report concludes the Fitzgerald
sank by taking on water through its hatches as the ship plowed
through a tremendous storm with waves of up to 35 feet. However,
others believe the boat punched a hole in its hull when the waves
set it down upon a shallow shoal.
   Either way, the boat went down so quickly it disappeared from
radar within minutes of its captain telling another boat that he was
holding his own in the storm.
   Because official conclusions on why the Fitzgerald sank differ,
researchers think the expedition will shed new light on the disaster.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
