<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Kidnapping 1stLd-Writethru   08-24 0753</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Kidnapping, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0509,0771</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Gold Dealer Kidnapped by Masked Palestinians</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with autopsy on Palestinian-American youth
youth, reports on other violence. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two masked Palestinians kidnapped an Israeli
gold dealer who went to the occupied West Bank at night to collect
debts, the army and Israel radio said today.
   The victim was the first Israeli civilian abducted during the
20-month-old Palestinian uprising. Soldiers put the West Bank town
of Tulkarem and three surrounding villages under curfew and searched
for the victim.
   Also today, a Scottish pathologist who conducted an independent
autopsy on the body of a Palestinian-American killed last week said
he died of a gunshot wound to the back and did not appear to have
been tortured.
   The boy's family alleged that the body showed signs of a beating
and cigarette burns. There were reports that the boy had been in
army custody.
   In another development, Israel's Supreme Court turned down
appeals by four Palestinians seeking to to block army orders that
they be deported, Israel radio reported.
   The deportations would bring to 59 the number of Palestinians
ejected from the occupied lands during the Arab uprising against
Israeli rule.
   In Jerusalem, the body of a 15-year-old Palestinian youth was
taken to the Augusta Victoria Hospital by a cousin who said the
youth died while being questioned by soldiers. The army said they
believed the youth died of natural causes and ordered an autopsy.
   Arab reporters in the occupied Gaza Strip, meanwhile, said a
19-year-old Palestinian killed Wednesday was shot by Israelis
disguised as Arabs who opened fire on masked youths painting
graffiti on walls.
   The army confirmed the death of Iyad Omar Abu Kamal in Gaza City
but denied the youths were painting anti-Israeli slogans. An army
spokesman said the youths were being arrested because they looked
suspicious.
   The spokesman said troops opened fire on the youths only after
they failed to halt.
   Army officials declined comment on whether the soldiers were
disguised.
   A total of 547 Palestinians have been killed by Israelis during
the uprising that began in December 1987, and 97 have been slain by
fellow Arabs as alleged collaborators. Thirty-eight Israelis also
have died in the violence.
   In the West Bank, troops searched the city of Tulkarem after the
kidnapping Wednesday night of Israeli gold merchant Shaul Mishaniya.
   The army spokeswoman said Mishaniya was in an Arab taxi when two
masked men armed with knives commandeered the car. Arab reporters
said dozens of masked youths surrounded the car.
   The army spokeswoman quoted Mishaniya's family as saying he
apparently went to the West Bank regularly at night for dealings
with Arab gold merchants and money changers.
   Yuval Neeman, a legislator from the right-wing Tehiya Party, said
on Israel radio that the nearly 10,000 Tulkarem refugee camp
residents should be deported in retaliation for the kidnapping.
   Four deportations approved by the Supreme Court today follow
repeated complaints from the United States that such actions violate
human rights conventions.
   The court ruling said the four were uprising leaders. One of
those ordered deported was a Bir Zeit University physics professor,
Taysir Aruri, whose case has been championed by Israeli and foreign
physicists.
   In Jerusalem, officials said Nasser Nabil Nasrallah, 15, was dead
when brought to Augusta Victoria Hospital on Wednesday night. His
cousin, Hamad Nasrallah, said Nasser died while the two were being
questioned by soldiers in Bethany near Jerusalem.
   Hamad said he was being interrogated by one Israeli serviceman
when a second soldier questioning his cousin on the other side of
the car suddenly cried out, ``Your friend is dead.''
   ``I didn't hear any shots or anything,'' said Hamad. Hospital
officials said they did not know the cause of death.
   The results of an autopsy of the Palestinian-American boy, Amjad
Jibril Tawil, were similar to those of an autopsy conducted by the
government. Tawil's body was found near the West Bank town of
Ramallah on Friday.
   There were reports that Tawil, who was born in Denver, Colo., was
taken into army custody during a stone-throwing clash. The army said
Monday a government autopsy and a reconstruction of events ruled out
involvement by soldiers.
   Scottish pathologist Dr. Derick Pounder told a news conference
today that there was no signs of torture, as the boy's family
alleged, and said the youth died of a single gunshot wound to the
back. Israeli officials said earlier the boy died of a single
gunshot in the chest.
</TEXT>
