<FIRST>r w PM-HUD-Demery     08-24 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD-Demery,270</SECOND>
<HEAD>Demery Lobbied for Top HUD Job, Files Show</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thomas T. Demery, a top housing official in the
Reagan administration, sought the help of senators, a congressman
and a key Bush aide in an unsuccessful bid to become secretary of
Housing and Urban Development, according to files released today.
   As assistant secretary for housing for two years, ``I have become
greatly challenged and sensitized to the public policy questions
surrounding the homeless, the availability of low-income housing,
and the difficulty the elderly and first-time homebuyers face in
finding affordable housing,'' Demery said in a form letter dated
Dec. 7, 1988.
   The letter was sent to Sens. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H.; Donald
Riegle, D-Mich.; Arlen Specter, R-Pa.; Rep. Carl Pursell, R-Mich.;
and Robert Teeter, who was director of the office of then
President-elect Bush.
   Demery enclosed his resume and asked for ``an opportunity to
discuss these issues with you.''
   Jack Kemp, then a congressman and failed GOP presidential
candidate, ultimately won the job; Demery has gone into private
business but his conduct at HUD is under scrutiny in the
investigation of alleged fraud and abuse at the agency during the
Reagan administration.
   The letters were contained in a box of files opened to the press
today under the Freedom of Information Act. However, most of
Demery's office files are missing, according to James Lafferty,
HUD's deputy assistant secretary for public affairs. Demery has said
he doesn't have them and Lafferty says the department has no
evidence that he may have taken them.
</TEXT>
