<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 1016EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--MisplacedPool     08-24 0174</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Misplaced Pool,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man's Pool Has to Go, City Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANCHESTER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $30,000 kidney-shaped swimming pool
built partly on city property is about to go down the drain.
   City water commissioners voted Wednesday to order developer David
Brady to get rid of the pool, which is partly in his back yard and
partly on land owned by the Manchester Water Works.
   Brady said he encroached on about 5,000 square feet of city land
by mistake, but commissioners said they weren't convinced.
   The deciding factor apparently was the difference between Brady's
pool proposal on his application for a city building permit and the
pool that eventually was built.
   The permit showed a lap pool entirely on Brady's land, but the
finished product was much larger and extended more than 50 feet over
the property line.
   Brady says his building crew neglected to get a new permit when
plans for the pool were changed. The commissioners rejected his
offer to buy or lease the city land for 1{ times its market value.
</TEXT>
