<FIRST>r a PM-Prosecutor-Defender     08-24 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prosecutor-Defender,0278</SECOND>
<HEAD>Couple Will Have To Limit Arguments To In-House Issues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GAINESVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dan and Chandelle Summer don't get to
argue in court anymore.
   Summer is an assistant district attorney and his wife is a
defense attorney. They squared off in a burglary trial this year.
   But shortly after the case ended in a hung jury, District
Attorney C. Andrew Fuller told Summer he could no longer handle
cases involving his wife's clients.
   Mrs. Summer sued Fuller, claiming his policy hurt her business by
causing delays in court cases when other attorneys had to be found
to fill in for her husband.
   U.S. District Judge William C. O'Kelley, in an order signed last
week, agreed there is no Georgia law preventing the two from
opposing each other in a court case. But he also said Fuller has the
right to decide which assistant handles any case.
   Mrs. Summer said she plans to appeal. Her husband declined to
comment.
   ``I wished the judge had found that harm had been done and gone
on to decide the underlying issue, which is basically marital
discrimination,'' she said.
   ``There was never a suggestion that we compromised our
positions,'' she added. ``When we get home, we're too tired to
discuss law. It's boring. We argue about other subjects, like who's
going to do the dishes tonight.''
   Fuller said he instituted the policy because he wanted to avoid
any appearance of impropriety, and he had been forming the policy
for months before the burglary trial.
   ``We want to put forward the image that indicates everyone is
being represented fairly,'' he said Tuesday.
</TEXT>
