<FIRST>r a PM-AccidentRehearsal     08-24 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Accident Rehearsal,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fire Drill Simulates Space Shuttle Explosion, Radiactive Leak</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD BENEDICT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Aerospace Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA and other officials who staged a
safety drill to simulate a space shuttle explosion that released
radioactive material said there were a few glitches that need to be
ironed out.
   More than 200 federal, state and local officials participated
Wednesday in a six-hour test of the communications network that
would link all the agencies in case of such an explosion, a
possibility that NASA said is extremely remote.
   Joel Reynolds, NASA safety chief, said the test simulated a
launch pad fire that the astronauts were able to escape before the
shuttle Atlantis exploded, causing the release of a small amount of
radiation, but not enough to order an evacuation.
   ``It was the type of thing where we'd tell people to get inside
their cars or a building to prevent inhalation of the material,'' he
said.
   Reynolds said there were problems with some communications links
and with a computer-generated model of the radiation dispersal
pattern.
   ``But that's why we had the exercise, to work out the rough spots
and help us work together as a team,'' he said. ``We'll sit down
tomorrow and assess what has to be changed.''
   Atlantis is scheduled for launch Oct. 12 with the Galileo
spacecraft. The crew of five astronauts is to release the payload on
the start of a six-year outward trip to orbit the planet Jupiter.
   Galileo will be powered by a pair of 122-pound radioisotope
thermoelectric generators, each containing about 24 pounds of highly
toxic plutonium-238 dioxide. Instruments called thermocouples
convert the heat released by the plutonium's decay into electricity.
   ``I can't see how those (plutonium) packages can break apart ...
but we want to be prepared,'' Reynolds said.
   The safety drill involved safety officials from NASA, the
Departments of Energey and Defense, the Environmental Protection
Agency, Federal Emergency Management Agency, and state and local
radiation protection and law enforcement organizations.
   Federal law requires that NASA have a written contingency plan
that would be enacted for any launch accident involving radioactive
material.
   Some anti-nuclear and environmental groups have protested the use
of plutonioum on a spacecraft, citing the 1986 space shuttle
Challenger explosion as an example of how things can go wrong. They
have said the radioactive fallout could result in many incidents of
cancer in the area.
   NASA estimates the odds of another shuttle disaster at somewhere
between 1-in-80 and 1-in-800.
   The agency said an exhaustive post-Challenger safety review
indicates the chances of a launch accident in which substantial
quantities of plutonium, pulverized to breathable form, could be
released is about 1-in-2,700. And even then, NASA said, any
contamination would be minor.
   The nuclear generators were tested to withstand blast pressure
effects of up to 2,000 pounds per square inch. The worst-case
overpressures created in the Challenger explosion was between 200
and 400 psi.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
