<HEAD>Students Tear-Gassed, Whites Arrested in South Africa</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with student protesters tear-gassed, activists
challenging president to debate. ADDS byline. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHAM VENTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police fired tear gas today at
hundreds of protesting university students and arrested 22 white
women from a civil rights group in a crackdown on supporters of a
nationwide defiance campaign.
   Police headquarters reported unrest in nine black and mixed-race
townships near Cape Town and said four officers had been injured in
rioting. Numerous clashes were reported between stone-throwing
youths and police units using tear gas and whips.
   Anti-apartheid leaders coordinating the defiance campaign accused
the government of distorting their intentions, and they challenged
acting President F.W. de Klerk to face one of them in a nationally
televised debate. There was no immediate response from de Klerk's
office to the challenge, announced at a news conference in
Johannesburg.
   The white women, members of the Black Sash civil rights
organization, stood in a market square in central Cape Town with
banners that read, ``One Person, One Vote,'' and ``Defiance is the
Right To Peaceful Protest.''
   Police declared the demonstration illegal under
state-of-emergency regulations and ordered the women to disperse.
When they refused to do so, they were led into a police bus.
   Among those arrested was Mary Burton, president of the Black
Sash. The nationwide group runs assistance centers for blacks and
regularly stages anti-government demonstrations.
   About 200 bystanders, both black and white, cheered in support of
the Black Sash as the women were arrested.
   At the University of Cape Town, about 1,000 students, black and
white, marched across a highway bordering the campus before being
dispersed by police sing whips and tear gas. Many of the students
regrouped and marched back to the campus behind a protester carrying
the black-green-and-gold flag of the outlawed African National
Congress guerrilla movement.
   Since anti-apartheid groups launched the mass defiance campaign
Aug. 2, there have been almost daily confrontations between police
and demonstrators in the Cape Town area.
   Police have broken up many protests, often with tear gas, and
arrested and detained dozens of activists. Anglican Archbishop
Desmond Tutu, a Nobel Peace Prize winner, was among those
tear-gassed at a demonstration Wednesday.
   The protesters are attempting to end segregation of hospitals,
schools, neighborhoods, beaches and other facilities.
   Organizers have planned rallies to protest an international rugby
team that is touring South Africa and scheduled to play the national
squad in Cape Town on Saturday. Anti-apartheid groups say the tour
breaks the international sports boycott imposed to protest apartheid.
</TEXT>
