<HEAD>More Than 100 East Germans in West German Embassy Allowed to Leave
Hungary</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with group arriving in West Germany,
East Germany denying it will impose travel restrictions, background on
exodus, higher figure on refugees. Pickup 8th graf, `A government...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 100 East Germans who had
sought refuge in West Germany's Embassy in Budapest were allowed to
leave the country at dawn today, the state news ageny MTI reported.
   It said the Hungarian government, ``on the basis of humanitarian
considerations,'' allowed 101 East Germans to leave Hungary with
International Red Cross travel documents.
   ``MTI has been authorized to state that this solution is to be
considered an exception and may not serve as a precedent,'' the
official report said.
   In Vienna, diplomatic sources speaking on condition of anonymity
said 150 East Germans were involved.
   The group was flown from Budapest to Vienna, where the refugees
boarded buses for West Germany, Austrian Red Cross officials said.
   In Bonn, the West German Foreign Ministry confirmed the move, but
it was not clear from its announcement if the transfer took place
with the consent of East Germany.
   At least 5,000 East Germans have reached the West via Hungary
since mid-July. Communist Hungary, which has reduced border
restrictions with Austria, has embraced social and political reform,
while East Germany maintains a hard line.
   The Bonn-based Die Welt newspaper said today the East German
government is planning to impose strict new travel regulations to
Hungary to stem the flow of refugees fleeing to the West across
Hungary's border with Austria.
   East Germany denied the report. The state-run news agency ADN
quoted a Foreign Ministry official as saying the report on planned
travel restrictions was ``an outright lie.''
   ``These lies and fabrications are being spread in Cold War style
to create confusion and to slander East Germany,'' ADN quoted the
unidentified official as saying.
   ``The truth is that travel to Hungary as well as to Bulgaria and
Romania continues as usual,'' ADN said.
   A West German government spokesman in Bonn said the permission
for the 101 refugees to leave Hungary was seen as a result of
repeated trips to Budapest by state secretary Juergen Sudhoff.
   Word of the departure of the East Germans holed up in the embassy
came after Hungarian border guards Wednesday stepped up their
surveillance of the border with Austria.
   About 250 East Germans had arrived in Austria by dawn Wednesday,
but only about 30 more during the day, reporters and other witnesses
said.
   An apparent mass escape attempt of East Germans was obstructed
Wednesday by Hungarian border guards in the Lake Neusiedl area along
the Hungarian-Austrian frontier, well-informed sources said.
   Early on Wednesday, Hungarian guards, some of them with dogs,
were seen manning the border at 130-foot intervals.
   An incident involving the occupants of three buses was confirmed
today by the government daily Magyar Hirlap, which said there were
signs the exodus of East Germans was organized, and that East
Germans were getting assistance from foreigners.
   It said on Wednesday at Sopronpuszta that three buses, three
taxis and two cars pulled up near the border, and that the occupants
started running toward the crossing. The paper hinted that the East
Germans were prevented from crossing the border but did not
elaborate.
   Magyar Hirlap also said that at Sopron, a main border crossing to
Austria, the border guards' barracks are filled with several hundred
would-be escapees.
   In reply to a question about their fate, an unidentified deputy
commander of the guards said, ``We'll release them, only to see them
back again.''
</TEXT>
