<FIRST>u i PM-CysticFibrosis 1stLd-Writethru a0485 08-24 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cystic Fibrosis, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0485,0465</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scientists Isolate Gene for Cystic Fibrosis</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates throughout with comments from today.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Researchers have discovered and isolated the gene
that causes cystic fibrosis when it is defective, a major step that
could help in developing treatments for the fatal disease, a
scientist said today.
   Analysis suggests the gene plays a role in transporting
substances across cell membranes, a process scientists suspect lies
at the heart of cystic fibrosis, said Lap-Chee Tsui of the Research
Institute at the Hospital for Sick Children in Toronto.
   The discovery will ``open up the door to more focused
experiments'' to find treatments that strike at the basic cause of
the disease, he said in a telephone inteview.
   ``This is one of the most significant discoveries in the history
of human genetics,'' said Dr. Ronald Worton, chief geneticist at
Hospital for Sick Children.
   For cystic fibrosis, the finding is ``the most exciting event
since this disease was first described in the medical literature 50
years ago,'' Robert Beall, executive vice president of the Cystic
Fibrosis Foundation in Bethesda, Md., declared today.
   Cystic fibrosis is the most common lethal genetic disease of
young people in North America. Some 30,000 Americans have it, and
1,000 to 1,200 new cases are diagnosed each year.
   Half of cystic fibrosis patients die before reaching their
mid-20s, mostly from respiratory complications. Treatment now is
limited to fighting the effects of the disease rather than the cause
of the illness itself.
   Apart from cystic fibrosis patients, some 12 million Americans
carry a defective form of the gene, but do not suffer the disease
because they also have a normal version. The disease appears only in
people who have inherited a defective form of the gene from each
parent.
   The new work will help in detecting people who carry a single
defective version of the gene and could pass it on to their
offspring, Tsui said.
   The disease makes the body produce abnormally thick, stick mucus
that clogs the lungs and digestive system, interfering with
breathing and digestion. Scientists believe the problem stems from a
defect in transporting of tiny charged particles across cell walls.
   In the new work, researchers found that the protein produced by
the gene bears a structural resemblance to proteins that are known
to play a role in transport across cell walls.
   The new research will be reported in the journal Science by a
team of more than two dozen scientists, led by Tsui, Jack Riordan of
the Research Institute, and Francis Collins of the Howard Hughes
Medical Institute and the University of Michigan at Ann Arbor.
   Scientists say they will now focus on how the gene functions and
how the defect can be rectified.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890824-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 1113EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-PreschoolMolest     08-24 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Preschool Molest,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defense Rests After 10 Months of Testimony in Marathon Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The defense reluctantly rested its case in the
marathon McMartin Pre-School molestation trial, now in its third
year, after questioning a man whose child prompted investigation of
the school six years ago.
   The attorneys for Raymond Buckey and his mother, Peggy McMartin
Buckey, ended their presentation Wednesday after 10 months of
testimony from more than 40 witnesses.
   ``On behalf of Mr. Buckey, we will rest our case in chief,''
attorney Danny Davis announced after the witness left the stand.
   ``On behalf of Mrs. Buckey, we rest,'' said attorney Dean Gits.
   The lawyers repeatedly proposed more witnesses during the course
of the trial, but Superior Judge William Pounders refused their
requests, citing the need to bring the proceedings to a conclusion.
   Pounders has vowed to have jury deliberations begin by Dec. 1.
After the defense rested, the prosecution began presenting rebuttal
evidence.
   Buckey, 30, and his mother, 62, are charged with 64 counts of
molestation and a combined count of conspiracy. They are the only
defendants left in a case that began five years ago with seven
teachers charged. The district attorney's office dismissed
accusations against five teachers after an 18-month preliminary
hearing, saying there was insufficient evidence to convict them.
   Both defendants testified during the defense case and adamantly
denied that they molested any children.
   The last witness to take the stand, the father of the boy whose
allegations prompted the case, denied molesting his own child. The
boy, who was 2{ when he attended the preschool, never testified.
   The defense had asserted that the child was molested at home
early in the case but retracted the statement this week. Davis says
he now believes the child was not molested by anyone.
   The prosecution spent 14 months presenting testimony from 61
witnesses during the trial, which has set records for length and for
cost, which has been estimated at $15 million.
   Jurors have dropped out because of illness or job problems, and
only one alternate now remains in addition to the 12 regular jurors.
The judge has voiced concern that loss of two more jurors would
create a mistrial and he has urged all lawyers to speed
presentations.
</TEXT>
