<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 1120EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Angola     08-24 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Angola,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angolan Guerrilla Leader Says Truce Over</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Guerrilla leader Jonas Savimbi said today
that a truce in Angola's 14-year-old civil war was over, and he
urged his rebel forces to resume fighting.
   In a statement issued from the rebels' southern Angolan
stronghold of Jamba and released in Lisbon, Savimbi said: ``The
Angolan people, to their infinite sorrow, accept that the war has
restarted.''
   Savimbi accused Angolan government forces of launching a military
offensive on Aug. 17.
   A cease-fire began June 24, two days after Savimbi sealed a truce
with Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos at a summit of 18
African leaders at Gbadolite, Zaire.
   Although the truce effectively collapsed one week later, with
both sides swapping accusations of military attacks, government and
rebel representatives continued to hold sporadic peace talks in
Zaire until last week.
   Savimbi's statement also said his group, the National Union for
the Total Independence of Angola, ``rejected in the most violent
terms'' a communique released by eight African leaders who discussed
Angolan peace prospects Tuesday in the Zimbabwean capital, Harare.
   The leaders supported dos Santos' claim that Savimbi agreed to
accept ``temporary and voluntary retirement'' during a cease-fire
and peace negotiations, and that guerrillas should recognize and be
integrated into exisiting Angolan political structures.
   The Western-backed guerrillas have been fighting the government
and its Cuban allies to force a power-sharing agreement since
shortly after Angola gained independence from Portugal in 1975.
   The guerrilla movement was not party to U.S.-brokered
international accords signed in New York by which South Africa
pledged to halt aid to the guerrillas and allow Angola's southern
neighbor, Namibia, to gain independence. In return, Cuba began a
phased withdrawal of its estimated 50,000 troops from Angola.
   The rebels still receive annually between $15 million and $18
million in U.S. military aid.
</TEXT>
