<FIRST>r a PM-People-Kennedy     08-24 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Kennedy,0184</SECOND>
<HEAD>John Jr. Accused Of Driving Without Car Insurance, Registration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John F. Kennedy Jr. has pleaded guilty to
speeding and driving an uninspected car, but plans to contest
charges that his car was unregistered and uninsured, a newspaper
reports.
   Kennedy, 28, is expected to appear Friday before an
administrative law judge at a state Motor Vehicles office, the Daily
News reported today.
   The lack of insurance on Kennedy's 1973 Volkswagen was the most
serious offense cited on July 7, said George Filieau, a Motor
Vehicles spokesman.
   Kennedy, sworn in this week as an assistant district attorney in
Manhattan, pleaded guilty by mail and paid what he thought was owed
for the speeding and inspection tickets.
   However, his check was returned because it was insufficient and
he still has to register the car, according to Filieau.
   He could be fined $100 for pleading guilty to driving an
uninsured vehicle; if he contests the charge and is found guilty,
his license must be revoked for one year and he could be fined up to
$1,000.
</TEXT>
