<HEAD>Bush Applauds Election of Solidarity Figure as Prime Minister</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 4 grafs with Bush-Schleuter remarks after 5th graf,
``I also,'' picking up at pvs 6th graf, The president; deletes pvs grafs
8-13, The president ... lobsters; Poul is correct</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today lauded the
election by Poland's parliament of Solidarity activist Tadeusz
Mazowiecki as the East bloc's first non-Communist prime minister.
   ``We wish him well, of course,'' the president told reporters as
he visited a fellow vacationer, South Carolina Gov. Carroll
Campbell, on a motor yacht tied up at a dock in Kennebunkport.
``It's a fascinating period in eastern Europe.''
   Bush said the White House had sent a formal message
congratulating Mazowiecki on his election today by the Sejm, the
lower house of Poland's National Assembly.
   In a written statement later, the president promised ``our strong
support as (Mazowiecki) seeks to lead his country toward economic
recovery and democratic change.''
   ``I also salute President (Wojciech) Jaruzelski for his political
wisdom in endorsing a government reflecting the genuine will of the
Polish people and Solidarity, under the leadership of Lech Walesa,
for its constructive role in helping bring about a new beginning in
Poland,'' Bush's statement added.
   Late this morning, Bush greeted two overnight house guests,
Danish Prime Minister Poul Schlueter and his wife, Anne Marie Vessel
Schlueter, and returned to the subject of dramatic changes in Poland
and elsewhere in the Soviet bloc.
   ``The prime minister would agree with me that there are
fascinating changes taking place in Europe, changes he might not
have predicted when he became prime minister, changes so fast I
couldn't have predicted them just seven months ago when I became
president,'' Bush said in brief remarks.
   Schlueter added that ``you are seeing right now very positive and
exciting international developments.''
   Bush said his talks with Schlueter, whom he has known since both
were diplomats at the United Nations in the 1970s, would include
drug trafficking. Schlueter said, ``We shall also find time to
discuss politics. We can't avoid that.''
   The president on Wednesday praised Soviet President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's involvement in Poland's political changes as a positive
step toward establishing a new coalition government.
   Bush, speaking at a news conference on the lawn of his oceanside
vacation home, lauded Gorbachev for urging Polish Communist
officials to be more cooperative with Solidarity leaders.
   Bush was asked if he thought the Soviets were playing a helpful
role in Poland with Gorbachev's 40-minute phone call Tuesday to
Soviet Communist Party leader Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski.
   After Gorbachev's intervention, Polish communist leaders backed
away from some demands and announced they would be willing to enter
a partnership with the Solidarity-led government.
   ``There will be bumps in the road as these countries move toward
more democracy. There's no question about that,'' Bush said. ``But I
felt that the statement I saw attributed to Mr. Gorbachev was very
positive in this regard _ very.''
   Bush was asked whether he'd consider inviting Gorbachev to
Kennebunkport.
   ``Well, he'd be welcome,'' the president said. Bush added that
the Soviet leader would like the seaside town, declaring ``everybody
likes it.''
   However, a question on what he considered a fair price for a
pound of lobster stumped him. ``I don't know. Can't give it to you.''
   In other comments, Bush said:
   _Talks between U.S. and Colombian officials will soon get under
way in Washington on what U.S. aid the South American nation might
need to help fight drug cartels. The administration has offered a
wide array of non-military assistance.
   _France is within its rights in keeping warships off Lebanon
standing by for a possible evacuation of French nationals. ``I am
not about to criticize the French for what they are doing,'' the
president said.
   _His wife, Barbara, is ``doing just fine'' on a new prescription
medicine to help alleviate some double-vision that is a side effect
from a thyroid imbalance diagnosed last winter.
   _He's having a ``total vacation'' even though ``the fishing has
been lousy'' and he's being followed around the golf course by an
army of reporters, photographers and television crew. ``A modest
kind of shy guy like me, I like to play golf without a lot of people
watching,'' he said.
</TEXT>
