<FIRST>r a PM-ApartmentsCollapse 1stLd-Writethru a0497smaybeunnervedwhentheyheadeNation'sFirstApartmentBuilding
08-24 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Apartments Collapse, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0497,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Scaffold Collapses Beside Nation's First Apartment Building</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to UPDATE with official saying building damage
was minimal; Picks up 3rd graf, `The three-story ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A three-story scaffold that collapsed at what
is said to be the first U.S. apartment building dragged down two
balconies, but overall damage to the 138-year-old structure was
minimal, authorities said.
   No one was hurt, but authorities had feared the collapse might
have damaged the Pontalba Apartments in Jackson Square, one of the
city's most photographed landmarks.
   Manuel Weber, a maintenance director for the Louisiana State
Museum, described the damage as minimal. He and other state
officials met today to discuss the damage, while workers began
rebuilding the scaffold.
   The three-story, state-owned building was completed in 1851 and,
with a companion building on the opposite side of Jackson Square,
was undergoing a $10 million renovation to replace the brick.
   When the scaffold collapsed onto Jackson Square, it brought down
parts of the building as well, witnesses said.
   ``I was facing the Cabildo and there was a crack and you could
begin to hear beams crack and then it was like slow motion, it just
fell,'' said Doug Hardwick, who was eating with friends at a nearby
restaurant. ``Ten seconds, maybe 15 and then it was down.''
   Most of the damage was to a 40- to 50-foot section of scaffolding
which stood three stories high. Emergency crews who rushed to the
scene roped off the area and kept spectators away.
   It was the second Jackson Square accident within 16 months. In
May 1988, fire destroyed the top floor of the nearby Cabildo, where
the Louisiana Purchase territories were transferred from France to
the United States.
   Wednesday's collapse occurred at the Lower Pontalba Apartments
which, with the Upper Pontalba on the west side of Jackson Square,
were built for $300,000 in the 1850s by Micaela Leonard Almonaster.
They are designated as national historic landmarks.
</TEXT>
