<FIRST>u w PM-US-Colombia 2ndLd-Writethru a0574 08-24 1052</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Colombia, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0574,980</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Mulling Response to Colombian Violence</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 12th graf pvs bgng, `I would,' to UPDATE
with DEA making no plans to evacuate agents or their families.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials scrambled today to determine how
to react to a rash of bombings in Colombia by drug traffickers who
declared war on their government in retaliation for a crackdown on
the drug trade.
   ``Everyone's rushing around'' trying to figure out how to
respond, said a State Department official who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   President Bush said he had ``no real comment'' on the situation
in Colombia.
   ``There will be meetings with the proper Colombian officials in
the not so many hours,'' Bush said at the summer White House in
Kennebunkport, Maine, as he prepared to meet the visiting prime
minister of Denmark.
   The situation concerning the one man in Colombian custody whom
the United States wants to extradite _ accused money-launderer
Eduardo Martinez Romero _ was unclear.
   A U.S. government plane has been at the Bogota airport since last
weekend and could be used to transport Martinez to the United States
for trial on the charges filed in Atlanta in March, according to an
administration source.
   However, the source said the extradition paperwork was still
being done and that he didn't know if Martinez could be whisked out
of Colombia.
   Bill Dempsey, a spokesman for the Marshals Service that
customarily handles the transport of people being extradited, said
today, ``We're ready'' to move Martinez. ``We're standing by for any
order from the Department of Justice, but we have no further
instructions at this point.''
   A Defense Department source said the Pentagon had received no
immediate orders either to help evacuate U.S. personnel in Colombia
or to send them help.
   Bush had said Wednesday that U.S. troops would not be dispatched
because Colombian President Virgilio Barco specifically had rejected
that option.
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said Wednesday that
U.S. diplomats in Colombia and other Latin American countries where
the cartel has staged successful terrorist attacks have been
operating on a heightened state of alert as a result of the
crackdown.
   ``I would say that our people in Colombia and in other places
where ... threat exists have always been on a high state of
readiness or care in their security procedures. ... That
continues,'' he said.
   Drug Enforcement Administration spokesman Frank Shults said today
there were no immediate plans to evacuate the two dozen DEA agents
stationed in Colombia nor their families. In the past, agents have
been removed from areas of other countries, including Mexico and
Peru, when tensions increased.
   ``However, there is a heightened sense of the need for security
in Colombia based on actions down there today,'' Shults said. ``The
Department of State is the primary agency responsible for the
security of American personnel overseas, and we will be meeting with
State Department officials to assess this situation.''
   In Colombia today, drug traffickers bombed the headquarters of
two political parties _ killing one person _ and set fire to two
politicians' homes in Medellin, the base for the world's biggest
cocaine cartel. In addition, officials said they defused powerful
bombs found in suitcases left at the Medellin offices of two
national radio networks.
   At one of the stations, the bombers left behind a communique
dated Wednesday and signed by ``The Extraditables,'' a group known
to carry out bloody acts for the Medellin drug cartel.
   ``We declare total and absolute war on the government, on the
industrial and political oligarchy, on the journalists that have
attacked and ravaged us, on the judges that have sold out to the
government, on the extraditing magistrates, on the presidents of the
unions and all those who who persecuted and attacked us,'' it said.
   ``We won't respect the families of those who have not respected
our families. ... We will burn and destroy the industries, the
properties and the mansions of the oligarchies,'' it said.
   Colombian Justice Minister Monica de Greiff had been scheduled to
fly to Washington to discuss procedures for extraditing those drug
traffickers wanted in the United States. However, it was unclear
when, or even if, she would make that trip in light of the violence
in her country, said an administration source, who spoke on
condition of anonymity.
   Thus far, none of the top leadership of the Medellin and Cali
cartels has been arrested. Martinez is considered one of the major
finanial people for Medellin, but not the chief of its
money-laundering operation.
   Drug traffickers' death squads have hit hard in Colombia and
neighboring Venezuela, but FBI spokesman Mike Kortan said, ``We have
not attributed any terrorist act to them in the United States.''
   Meanwhile, Ms. de Greiff was quoted in The Washington Post today
as saying that if U.S. financial aid is to have any impact on her
country's drug war, it should come as soon as possible and without
any strings attached. She said her country had not received any of
$5 million in U.S. aid announced in April because of wrangling over
how the money is to be spent.
   The Justice Department announced that Colombia will be offered a
$2 million program to help protect its judges and others threatened
by terrorist attacks. The agreement was signed Wednesday.
   At the State Department, Boucher said there would be other
meetings this week with senior Colombian officials, but he declined
to say when, where or who would be involved. ``We're trying to avoid
too much focus on specific meetings and individuals because of the
security situation,'' he said.
   The joint effort between the United States and Colombia began
when Barco imposed a state of siege after Friday's assassination of
Luis Carlos Galan, a leading presidential candidate and outspoken
foe of drug traffickers.
   The emergency measures have resulted in the arrests of some
11,000 people and allowed the immediate resumption of extraditions
to the United States. The Colombian Supreme Court, under attack from
drug traffickers, threw out the extradition law in 1987.
   The Justice Department this week issued its ``Most Wanted'' list
of 12 alleged drug cartel leaders, but none has been arrested.
   U.S. officials say the Medellin cartel supplies an estimated 80
percent of the cocaine sold illegally in the United States.
</TEXT>
