<FIRST>r a AM-DaniloffReturns     08-24 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Daniloff Returns,0543</SECOND>
<HEAD>Daniloff Takes Active Role in Soviet Exchange</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANICA KIRKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a borrowed office, beside a watercolor
no one bothered to hang, Nick Daniloff is engaged in international
diplomacy.
   Behind the scenes in government is an unusual spot for the former
U.S. News and World Report correspondent, who gained notoriety three
years ago after being imprisoned on trumped-up espionage charges.
   But now he's Vermont's man on the Soviet Union, spending his
summer months arranging the visits of a delegation of people from
Karelia, the Soviet province that Gov. Madeleine Kunin hopes will
officially become Vermont's sister state.
   ``I suppose some people might look on it as being ironic,''
Daniloff said. ``But it's for a good purpose and that's what
counts.''
   Daniloff insists he never was a spy, and that his imprisonment
followed the FBI's arrest of Gennadiy Fedorovich Zakharov. The
Soviet employee of the United Nations allegedly sought to obtain
classified information of the U.S. government from an FBI informant
at a New York City subway station.
   But neither he nor state officials are concerned that the Soviets
may be unnerved when they hear Daniloff is on the telephone, helping
arrange for the exchange of officials from Karelia.
   ``I have a gripe with the KGB, but I don't have a gripe with the
Soviet Union,'' he said in an interview this week.
   ``My understanding is that the folks in Karelia sort of shrugged
their shoulders and went on about their business. I understand there
was one official in the Soviet Embassy in Washington who raised his
eyebrows and then no more was said about it.''
   Following the 1985 summit between former president Ronald Reagan
and Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev, personal contacts between
individuals in the superpowers were given official sanction. States
like Vermont, Alaska and Iowa have capitalized on the relaxation of
relations.
   Several independent groups in Vermont have organized exchanges of
singing students, dairy farmers and journalists. But the Karelians
are coming at the invitation of Kunin, who visited the province last
year.
   Kunin said she sought Daniloff's advice before going to the
Soviet Union. To fulfill a promise, she plucked a flower from a
bouquet at the American ambassador's residence in Moscow and placed
the carnation at the grave Daniloff's great great grandfather in a
nearby cemetery.
   When planning the Karelians' visit to Vermont, state officials
again sought Daniloff, who settled in Vermont after his Soviet
imprisonment to write a book linking his great great grandfather's
experience of imprisonment with his own. He has a home in Andover.
   ``Some people are just good for information but with Nick, you
really get understanding,'' Kunin's former chief of staff Elizabeth
Bankowski said.
   Daniloff has traveled around Vermont this summer, speaking with
those who might be interested in talking to the Soviets during the
visit, which begins Labor Day.
   The Karelians are expected to visit a Guilford dairy farmer who
has already sent a prized Holstein to the Soviet Union as a goodwill
measure.
   Daniloff also is hopeful future educational exchanges and
business deals can be arranged.
   ``All of these things are built brick by brick,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
