<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--WineTrain     08-24 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Wine Train,0196</SECOND>
<HEAD>Napa Valley Wine Train Gets Permission To Carry Passengers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Napa Valley Wine Train won approval from
the state Public Utilities Commission to carry passengers through
the famed wine valley, but people can't get off to visit wineries.
   The unanimous PUC decision Wednesday followed a settlement worked
out during months of negotiations among the railroad, the PUC and a
coalition that opposed the train.
   Service begins Sept. 16 and tickets will cost $25 round trip,
Train President Jack McCormack said.
   The railroad's only right-of-way is on 21.3 miles of tracks
between Napa and St. Helena. Operators agreed to submit to an
environmental impact report; run no more than 15 round trips a week
nor more than three a day; and insist that passengers remain on the
train for the entire three-hour excursion.
   Wine Train operators eventually hope to allow passengers to
debark to visit wineries.
   The coalition against the train _ including virtually the
valley's entire governmental, winery and grower establishment _ has
alleged the operation would be noisy and further disrupt life in a
valley already crowded with 2 million tourists a year.
</TEXT>
