<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 1314EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Minorities-Congress     08-24 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Minorities-Congress,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Minorities Seen Gaining in House From 1990s Redistricting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minorities stand a good chance of gaining seats
in the House after congressional district lines are redrawn based on
results of the 1990 census, a demographic expert said Thursday.
   William O'Hare, director of policy studies at the Population
Reference Bureau, also predicted that ``there is going to be a
mountain of litigation'' following the census over issues such as
adjustments for undercounted minorities, whether or not to exclude
illegal aliens and inclusion of military personnel overseas in the
count used for reapportionment.
   ``We think that the redistricting in the 1990s offers a lot of
opportunities and a few potential pitfalls,'' O'Hare told a news
conference. ``Clearly, there's room for more election of
minorities.''
   In the 1991-92 reapportionment, O'Hare said, ``the states that
are likely to gain the most congressional seats _ for example,
California, Texas, Florida _ all have large minority populations.''
   He said the country's Hispanic population was expected to show a
particularly strong gain, from about 14.5 million in 1980 up to a
projected 22 million in the 1990 census _ with most of the increase
concentrated in sunbelt states.
   Asked what net gain of minority members he expects there will be
in the House, O'Hare said: ``Certainly half a dozen to 10 is not
unreasonable. ... I would say that's optimistic, but not
outlandishly optimistic.''
   The 435-seat House now has 36 minority members _ 22 blacks, nine
Hispanics, four Asian-Americans and one American Indian.
   He said that currently blacks make up about 12 percent of the
U.S. population but have only 1.5 percent of elected officials,
while Hispanics comprise 8 percent of the population but are less
than 2 percent of elected officials across the country.
   O'Hare released cpies of a new Population Reference Bureau
report, ``Redistricting in the 1990s: A Guide for Minority Groups,''
that was funded by the Ford Foundation and includes chapters written
by eight experts in minority demographics and politics.
   The Washington-based Population Reference Bureau describes itself
as a private, non-partisan organization which aims to increase
public awareness and understanding of population issues.
</TEXT>
