<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--MassEarthquake     08-24 0136</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Mass Earthquake,0138</SECOND>
<HEAD>Small Temblor Felt in New England</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A minor earthquake shook sections of southern
Massachusetts along the Connecticut and Rhode Island border about
noon Thursday, but there were no early reports of any damages or
injuries.
   ``No one's called about damage, but everyone in the town felt
it,'' said New Bedford Police Cadet Henry Turgeon.
   A seismologist at Boston College's Weston Observatory in Waltham,
Richard Spielman, said initial indications were that the temblor
rated about a 2.4 on the Richter scale.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude. An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause
slight damage in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable
damage, 6 severe damage.
</TEXT>
