<FIRST>r a PM-MarijuanaRaids     08-24 0278</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marijuana Raids,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Agencies Raid Marijuana Fields In Central, Southeastern Oklahoma</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HINTON, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Law enforcement officers armed with machetes
began harvesting thousands of wild marijuana plants today in fields
in central and southeastern Oklahoma.
   Gov. Henry Bellmon, who has pushed state-coordinated efforts at
eradicating marijuana, briefly joined members of the Oklahoma
Highway Patrol tactical team and the Caddo and Canadian county
sheriff's departments in the fields near Hinton before flying to
Hugo where another eradication program was under way.
   About 180,000 wild marijuana plants were being cut, hauled to a
trench, doused with diesel fuel and burned by the patrol and
deputies. The plants ranged in height from 3 feet to over 16 feet.
   Scott Rowland, a spokesman for the Oklahoma Bureau of Narcotics
and Dangerous Drugs, said agents from the OBNDD and members of the
Oklahoma National Guard will be in southeastern Oklahoma through
Sunday cutting down marijuana from cultivated fields in that region.
   Rowland estimated 3,000 plants would be cut down and burned
today. Members of the tactical team whacked down plants, loaded them
onto a front-loader and took them into a cleared field to be burned.
   The plot was spotted from the air several days ago, and Caddo
County Sheriff Butch Hamilton called for help in eradicating it.
   At the site along the Canadian-Caddo county line, Bellmon was
asked whether the fight was a losing battle since marijuana grew
wild and whether it might not be better to just overlook it.
   ``Marijuana does grow wild, but it can be controlled,'' Bellmon
said. ``I am not willing to say we can't win the war on drugs.''
</TEXT>
