<FIRST>r a PM-Computer-Soviets     08-24 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Computer-Soviets,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Plead Innocent To Conspiring To Sell Computer Gear To Soviets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RORY MARSHALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men pleaded innocent today to charges they
conspired to sell sophisticated computer equipment to the Soviet
Union in violation of U.S. export rules.
   U.S. Magistrate Philip K. Sweigert set trial for Oct. 16 for
David Whyte of Mississauga, Ontario, and John Townsend, a British
citizen who had been living in New Castle, Australia.
   The pair are charged with three other men and two companies in a
scheme in which they allegedly conspired to export U.S.-made
computer equipment without a Commerce Department export license.
   The Digital Equipment Corp. VAX 8700 super minicomputer that
federal agents say was designated for export can be used to design
nuclear weapons, submarines and missile and radar tracking systems.
None of the computer equipment reached the Soviet Union.
   A federal grand jury handed down up 12-count indictment in the
case on Aug. 17.
   Townsend and Whyte are both charged with one count of conspiracy
to defraud the United States, one count of conspiracy to violate
Export Administration regulations and one count of money laundering.
   Whyte also is charged with one count of attempted export of
computer goods. Townsend faces two counts of attempted export of
computer goods to a controlled country and six counts of making
false statements by falsifying shipper's export declarations.
   The men remained in custody without bail.
   Whyte, Townsend and Shiv Mohan of New Delhi were arrested July 21
in Buffalo, N.Y., as they met with Robert Casperson, the president
of a Kirkland computer firm, C-Tek, allegedly to discuss plans to
divert $900,000 in computer equipment through Canada to the Soviet
Union.
   Casperson was cooperating with federal agents, but he and Mohan
also are charged in the indictment, as is Sidhartha Bose, whose
residence was not immediately available.
</TEXT>
