<FIRST>r a AM-RestoredPlane 1stLd-Writethru a0602 08-24 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Restored Plane, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0602,0358</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Keeps Promise To Restore Plane That Won 1929 Women's Air Derby</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 1st graf to CORRECT Louis to Louise.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WICHITA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixty years after Louise Thaden won the
first Women's Air Derby, her 1929 blue and gold Travel Air D4000 is
in the air again, retracing the derby's route to honor women pilots.
   The biplane roared in for a landing Wednesday night at Beech
Aircraft Corp.
   Navy Capt. William Yarbrough promised Thaden 15 years ago that he
would find and restore the plane. She died in 1979, but he kept his
promise.
   Yarbrough found what was left of the plane seven years ago in a
shed on an Arizona ranch.
   ``It was just in parts,'' he said. ``You could bring it home in a
station wagon.''
   When the plane was rebuilt, he asked Airborne Express pilot Susan
Dusenbury to retrace the derby's route on the 60th anniversary.
   ``She's got the same spit, polish, drive and twinkle in her eye
as Louise did,'' Yarbrough said. ``And, her middle name is Louise.''
   Thaden had piloted the biplane, originally built in Wichita in
what is now a Beech plant, from Santa Monica, Calif., to Cleveland.
She won the leg of the race from Tulsa, Okla., to Wichita and the
nine-day event over other female fliers who included Amelia Earhart
and Pancho Barnes.
   The First Women's Air Derby ushered women into the aviation age
and fueled young girls' dreams of flying. Twenty pilots began the
race, 15 finished, and one died.
   Ms. Dusenbury normally flies a DC-9 at 35,000 feet. On this trip
she is averaging 120 mph at 2,000 to 3,000 feet.
   ``It's sort of like being a tourist over the entire country,''
she said. ``I was flattered to honor Louise Thaden and women in
aviation.''
   The silver cross Thaden wore during the race dangles from a chain
around Ms. Dusenbury's neck. She also has Thaden's aviator's scarf.
   Ms. Dusenbury will stop in Kansas City, Mo., and East St. Louis,
Ill., before arriving in Cleveland on Saturday. Yarbrough is
following by car.
</TEXT>
