<FIRST>r a AM-CDC--MilitaryTesting     08-24 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-CDC--Military Testing,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tests Show Drug Use By Recruits Dropped After Testing Instituted</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release 6 p.m. EDT.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drug use by military recruits apparently dropped
by half in the first months of mandatory drug-testing of armed
forces applicants, military and health officials said Thursday.
   Subsequent testing of some 6,000 urine samples collected from
random recruits in March and April 1988 showed that 7.3 percent had
recently used marijuana, 1.8 percent had used cocaine and 0.7 were
positive for both, according to a report from the Office of the Army
Surgeon General, published in Thursday's weekly report of the
Centers for Disease Control.
   Those numbers were roughly twice the results of the first seven
months of the Defense Department's new applicant testing program. Of
more than 320,000 recruits tested from June-December 1988, 2.4
percent were positive for marijuana, 0.9 percent were positive for
cocaine and 0.3 percent were positive for both.
   The applicants who provided urine samples in the March-April
pilot study were not told they would be drug-tested, but the samples
were not personally identified and the results could not be linked
to individuals, the CDC report said.
   Positive specimens from those pilot tests were not confirmed;
data from other military drug tests indicates that 85 percent to 90
percent of the positive samples would have been confirmed on repeat
testing, the report said.
   The Defense Department has screened all applicants for military
service since June 1988, under an act of Congress. The testing
program is ``the largest non-random drug-testing program in the
United States,'' the CDC said.
   Early findings from the program were released in January. Some
defense officials said privately at the time that while the program
had blocked more than 11,000 apparent drug-using recruits in its
first seven months, it was not worth its multimillion-dollar cost.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890824-0109 </DOCNO>
