<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Soviet     08-24 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Soviet,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Council Expresses Hope For Stable Ties With Poland</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Council of Ministers congratulated
Poland's new non-Communist prime minister Thursday and expressed
hope his election would not damage relations between the countries.
   Tadeusz Mazowiecki, a veteran Solidarity activist, was elected
prime minister earlier in the day by the Sejm, the lower house of
Poland's National Assembly. The historic vote made him the first
non-Communist chief of government in the East bloc.
   Within hours, the Council of Ministers, or Soviet cabinet, sent
Mazowiecki a telegram of ``friendly congratulations'' that also was
carried by the official Soviet news agency Tass.
   ``We express the certainty that the traditional relations of
friendship and all around cooperation between the Soviet Union and
Poland will continue developing in the basis of sovereign equality
and respect, mutual benefit and mutual responsibility,'' the Council
of Ministers said.
   An interview with Mazowiecki also was printed Thursday in the
Soviet government's evening newspaper, Izvestia. The new Polish
leader was quoted as saying his government would be open to all,
including the Polish Communist Party, but that the time was clearly
past ``when only one camp could form the government.''
   At a regular news briefing, Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman
Yuri A. Gremitskikh also reacted to Mazowiecki's election with
equanimity.
   ``The Soviet side takes the decision into account and we shall
regard comrade Mazowiecki as our partner in the relations that link
our two countries,'' he said.
