<HEAD>Former Congressman Says He May Face More Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCEVILLE, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former U.S. Rep. Pat Swindall, who
awaits sentencing on a perjury conviction, said he expects to be
indicted again _ this time on charges of tampering with a federal
jury.
   Swindall told the Gwinnett Daily News on Wednesday that he was
offered an opportunity to enter a plea to charges that he tampered
with a jury selected last fall to hear his perjury case. He said he
refused the offer.
   ``I expect I'll be indicted on this jury-tampering matter,'' said
Swindall, a Republican from Georgia's 4th District.
   Swindall's attorney, Tom Thrash, declined to comment. U.S.
Attorney Bob Barr was out of town and could not be reached for
comment.
   Swindall was convicted in June on nine counts of lying to a
federal grand jury investigating a drug money-laundering scheme. He
is to be sentenced Monday.
   Swindall was indicted in that case last October and tried to go
to trial immediately in an effort to clear his name before the Nov.
8 election, when he faced a strong opponent.
   A jury was selected, but was never sworn in because U.S. District
Judge Robert Vining ended the proceedings due to Swindall campaign
literature that mentioned the case.
   The judge said he was disturbed that a campaign mailing reprinted
a letter from a polygraph examiner who said Swindall did not lie
when asked about his knowledge of the alleged drug money operation.
   The mailing was sent the day after Vining told Swindall, a lawyer
representing himself, that he could not mention the polygraph test
in the trial. Four of the 14 people selected as jurors and
alternates lived in Swindall's district, where the brochure was
mailed.
   Swindall ended up losing the Nov. 8 election to actor Ben Jones,
a Democrat.
