<FIRST>r i AM-Hoffman     08-24 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hoffman,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oscar-Winner Urges Young Actors `to Beat the System'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dustin Hoffman says young actors should do whatever
they must to beat the system and find work, even if it means
pestering celebrities like Dustin Hoffman.
   He praised actor Neal Foster, 23, who coaxed Hoffman into his
campaign to raise money to put on a play.
   ``If you know that no one cares and that the odds are you're not
going to work, then you have to beat the system. Now this guy's
beating the system,'' Hoffman said of Foster, speaking Wednesday
before a capacity audience at the Playhouse Theater.
   ``You have to find a way to act; he's finding a way to act.''
   ``You cannot get a job by doing what everyone else does. He
(Foster) knows that.''
   Hoffman is appearing in London through Sept. 23 in Shakespeare's
``The Merchant of Venice.''
   The Oscar-winning star is Foster's biggest catch yet in a series
of celebrity interviews to finance a staging of Anton Chekhov's
``The Sea Gull.'' Foster, a 1988 graduate of the Bristol Old Vic
theater school, wants to appear in and produce the play next April
in Birmingham, England.
   Foster approached Hoffman at the stage door of ``Merchant'' on
June 21 to enlist his help and Hoffman immediately agreed. The event
sold out the theater and contributed nearly $5,200 toward the
$23,500 needed, Foster said.
   Foster needs about $3,000 more and said he hopes to reach that
when he holds his next interview, with Jack Lemmon, on Sept. 20.
   When asked during the interview about unfulfilled ambitions,
Hoffman quoted the late English actor-knight, Sir Ralph Richardson,
who said: ``I'd like to learn a little bit more about acting before
it's too late.''
