<FIRST>r i AM-China     08-24 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Papers Publish Old Deng Speeches</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Speeches by Deng Xiaoping were splashed across the
front pages of major Chinese newspapers Thursday as the official
media intensified their new, adulatory treatment of the aging senior
leader.
   Three different speeches by Deng _ all given decades ago _ filled
the top half of the front pages of several national newspapers.
Rarely have old speeches been reprinted and so prominently displayed.
   But Deng's prominence in the official media has grown
substantially since he ordered the military to crack down on June
3-4 on the mass pro-democracy movement in Beijing. Troops killed
hundreds, perhaps thousands, of people.
   Deng, 85, has not been seen in public since June 9, when he
addressed martial law troops in Beijing. He is reported to be ill
with cancer.
   The press has quoted him regularly and released several of his
early essays. A book of reminiscences about his early career has
come out and a major movie has been made about his role in leading a
Communist uprising in 1929. The China Art Gallery displays a bronze
bust of him.
   The three speeches that were published Thursday are among 39
contained in a new volume of his selected works that was released
this week.
   The Guangming Daily, published for intellectuals, carried a
speech given in 1950, less than a year after the Communists came to
power in China.
   In it, Deng spoke to journalists about the importance of their
work, emphasizing their responsibility to educate the masses in
political ideology and carry out party policy.
   The Economic Daily and the Workers Daily published a speech Deng
made four years later to a group of party officials about the need
for the party to turn its focus from revolution to construction.
   A 1961 speech to members of the Communist Youth League, the
party's youth branch, about the league's responsibilities, was
printed in China Youth News.
   On Deng's birthday Tuesday, all major newspapers carried a 1957
Deng speech from the new collection on their front pages. In that
speech, Deng said democracy should be implemented within the party,
but he rejected Western-style democracy for China.
</TEXT>
