<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   June Christy concedes she might get a little
teary-eyed when her lively brood of flaxen-haired quadruplets sets
off for kindergarten Monday.
   ``I'll try to control myself,'' she said, smiling. ``I used to
chuckle at these first-time mothers who got all weepy the first day
of school. I used to think what's the big deal? Now I understand.
   ``It's just that separation,'' she said.
   Dad Richard Christy sees it as an opportunity for Jill, Jeffrey,
Philip and Alison to meet new friends and enjoy new experiences.
   For the 5-year-old Christy youngsters, it promises to be a treat.
   There's recess, ``where you get to go out and play,'' said
Alison. Jill looks forward to meeting lots of children. Jeffrey can
find others to share his budding athletic interests. There's also
the fun of riding the bus, says Philip.
   At the suggestion of school officials, the four will be split
into pairs with different classrooms and teachers to encourage
individual development.
   ``It will be interesting to hear from their mother when she hears
four different versions of something,'' said one of the teachers,
Zoe Boynton.
   Once the four are in school, June Christy plans to do some kind
of school volunteer work in addition to being a part-time registered
nurse. And when the house is a little quieter, she can finally get
to a project she's had on hold for years: updating scrapbooks on her
children.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONGVIEW, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Jack Blankenship left the U.S.
Navy in 1946, but the Defense Department didn't forget: It tracked
him down to return the canteen he left decades ago on a South
Pacific island beach.
   An Ohio couple found the canteen while they were touring World
War II battle sites in the New Georgia islands, near New Guinea and
Guadalcanal.
   Blankenship's name, rank, serial number and blood type were
etched into the back of the rusty canteen, which had remained inside
its metal cup.
   The finders _ Pete and Betty Medley of Shelby, Ohio _ assumed
pharmacist's mate Blankenship had been killed. They contacted Sen.
John Glenn, D-Ohio, and asked him to help locate Blankenship's next
of kin _ and, through the Defense Department, they learned he was
very much alive.
   ``We were just very thrilled that this man had lived through that
war and was still alive and well,'' Mrs. Medley said Tuesday.
   The canteen arrived in the mail this week, and Blankenship
recalled he had left it and his other gear after being shot in the
leg during a shore mission.
   Blankenship said he immediately called the Medleys after the
Defense Department called him about his canteen. When Pete Medley
answered the phone, Blankenship could hear him yell, ``Betty! It's
him!''
   Blankenship, a former pastor at Valley Baptist Church in
Longview, said he and his family feel touched and excited about
receiving the canteen. They said they are grateful to the Medleys,
whom they hope someday to meet, and to Glenn.
</TEXT>
