<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     08-24 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czechs Release All But 2 of Those Detained Monday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   All but two of the 370 people
detained during a protest on the 21st anniversary of the 1968
Soviet-led invasion of Czechoslovakia have been released, a
government spokesman said Thursday.
   Two Hungarians under investigation on charges of breaching public
order for their alleged role in stirring up the anti-government
protest are the only two people still in custody, the spokesman,
Miroslav Pavel, told a news conference.
   They were identified as Tamas Deutsch and Gyoergy Kerenyi, two
activists with the Hungarian opposition youth group FIDESZ. Kerenyi
addressed a crowd chanting for freedom at the start of Monday's
protest before being grabbed by plainclothes police.
   According to state-run media, 50 foreigners were among the 370
people detained. Hundreds of helmeted riot police swarmed through
central Prague to break up the protests.
   Pavel did not say whether any of the 320 Czechoslovaks detained
would face charges or simply be fined for their participation in the
banned demonstration.
   Diplomats in Prague said eight Italians and seven Dutch residents
were released and ordered to leave the country Thursday.
   A Dutch Embassy spokesman said the Dutch were fined before being
released.
   Seven Hungarians, including five cameramen and photographers,
were released Wednesday and left for home, the official news agency
CTK reported.
   Two Austrian cameramen also were freed Wednesday after what
Austrian radio termed ``massive intervention'' from Vienna's embassy
in Prague.
   A West German TV crew and an American reporter also were briefly
detained Monday, as well as three Poles who spent two days in
detention. The identities of the remaining foreigners were not known.
   Pavel said that Czechoslovak authorities, who blamed foreign
``provocateurs'' for Monday's protest, would continue to punish
outsiders who violated national law.
   ``Czechoslovakia welcomes tourists ... but that does not free
them from the obligation to respect Czechoslovak laws,'' he said.
``Czechoslovak authorities will not permit the center of town to
become a place for all kinds of demonstrations on which cheap
political capital would be banked at our expense.''
   Czechoslovakia's entrenched Communist leadership, which came to
power after the 1968 invasion, has resisted mounting pressure at
home and from East bloc reformers to relax its monopoly on power.
</TEXT>
