<FIRST>r a AM-People-JFKJr     08-24 0222</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-JFK Jr,0226</SECOND>
<HEAD>JFK Jr. Due in Court For Traffic Tickets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John F. Kennedy Jr. is due for his first
appearance before a judge since becoming an assistant district
attorney _ but as a defendant, not a prosecutor.
   Kennedy, 28, has a Friday date before an administrative law judge
at the state Department of Motor Vehicles in the borough of Queens
to answer summonses for speeding and driving an uninsured,
unregistered and uninspected vehicle, agency spokesman Tom Apple
said Thursday.
   Port Authority police issued the summonses July 9 after stopping
Kennedy for doing 63 mph in a 50 mph zone, Apple said.
   Kennedy pleaded guilty by mail to speeding and driving an
uninspected car, but his check was not enough to cover his $127
fines, and he did not answer the other two charges, Apple said.
   The son of the late president could delay the hearing with a
phone call or send his lawyer if he simply intends to plead guilty,
Apple said. A guilty plea on the uninsured vehicle charge would cost
Kennedy his license for one year, the spokesman said.
   Kennedy was sworn in as a prosecutor in the Manhattan district
attorney's office Monday. A spokesman for District Attorney Robert
Morgenthau, Gerald McKelvey, said, ``We expect Mr. Kennedy to handle
this in an appropriate manner.''
</TEXT>
