<FIRST>r a AM-NoWhiteFlight     08-24 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-No White Flight,0454</SECOND>
<HEAD>Few Whites Leaving Public Schools After Desegregation Ruling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NATCHEZ, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge predicted about one-fourth
of white students would leave for private schools when he
consolidated this river city's two racially split high schools.
   But registration records show nearly as many students are
returning to public classrooms as are leaving as the opening of
newly desegregated schools nears, officials say.
   ``I'm very, very optimistic,'' Superintendent Melvin Buckley said
Wednesday. ``It looks like the issue of white flight may be a moot
point.''
   Records show that 50 students previously in private or parochial
schools have pre-registered in the public schools for 1989-90, while
60 students have transferred their public school records and
transcripts to private or parochial schools in the Natchez area. An
additional 30 transcripts were requested by students whose families
have moved from Natchez.
   Classes open Sept. 5 in the district, which enrolled about 6,400
students in 1988-89.
   When he ordered a sweeping desgregation in July, U.S. District
Judge William H. Barbour Jr. predicted that 560 to 700 white
students, 24 to 29 percent of white enrollment, would leave.
   Private and parochial schools, where classes started this week,
show increased enrollment, but spokesmen say the numbers are less
than expected a month ago.
   Adams County Christian School reported fewer than 200 new
students. Many of those are new to the Natchez area and many are
pre-schoolers and kindergarteners, a staff member said. Earlier,
there were predictions the school might see as many as 600 new
students.
   Enrollment at Natchez Cathedral School, operated by the Catholic
Diocese of Jackson, is up slightly this fall. Exact enrollment
figures will be made public in September.
   ``I really think it's going to work. I think, finally, the
majority of people want to see what the end product will be, what
the school system is going to be like,'' said George F. West Jr.,
school board president. ``Really, the response is interesting. It's
totally different from what people had expected.''
   Barbour's ruling consolidates the predominantly white South
Natchez and all-black North Natchez High student bodies into one.
They will attend the former South Natchez campus in a school that
will be known as Natchez High.
   The former North Natchez campus will be a middle school for
grades 7 through 9. The judge's ruling also created two elementary
school attendance zones and paired an all-black school with a
majority-white school in each zone.
   Buckley said that if enrollment holds up, the district will not
have to lay off any of its 450 teachers. Administrators had feared
that between 14 and 40 teachers could lose their jobs if enrollment
fell drastically.
</TEXT>
