<SECOND>AM-Eastern-Tickets,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>would-Be Eastern Passengers Must File Claims</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Would-be passengers on Eastern Airlines who
were unable to use their tickets because of the strike against the
company were advised by the Department of Transportation Thursday
that they must file claims for refunds by Aug. 31.
   The department said Eastern customers seeking ticket refunds
should file a proof of claim form with the federal bankruptcy court
in New York. Proof of claim forms may be obtained from a federal
courthouse or from Eastern by calling (800) 628-0010.
   The department said it issued the consumer advisory because it
believed many ticketholders might not have heard about the deadline.
Eastern and the bankruptcy court initially advised passengers not to
file claims until a procedure was established, the advisory said.
   On July 21, Eastern filed a plan calling for full refunds in
cash, with interest, to people holding unused tickets purchased
before the carrier filed for bankruptcy protection on March 9 and
severely reduced its schedules. This plan still must be approved by
the court.
   Forms should be sent to United States Bankruptcy Court, Eastern
Air Lines Inc. Claims Processing Center, P.O. Box 1587, Grand
Central Station, New York, N.Y. 10163.
   The refund plan covers not only ticket holders but passengers
with unresolved baggage or cargo claims, the department said.
