<FIRST>r w AM-NAACP-SilentMarch     08-24 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NAACP-Silent March,280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Says It Expects Thousands for Saturday March</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the NAACP say they expect several
thousand people to gather on the capital's monument grounds Saturday
for a civil rights demonstration modeled after the historic ``Silent
March'' conducted 72 years ago in New York City.
   The Washington reprieve ``will be concerned with one issue alone
_ the Supreme Court and its recent hostile decisions'' diluting
affirmative action and minority set-aside programs, according to
Benjamin L. Hooks, executive director of the NAACP.
   But the brief march, led by six drummers with muffled drums, is
designed to duplicate in tone and style the 1917 demonstration in
which 8,000 people, led by W.E.B. DuBois, paraded in silence down
New York City's Fifth Avenue to protest segregation and the
lynchings of blacks in the South.
   Organizers have asked men to wear black, and women to children to
wear white. The march will culminate with a rally at the Capitol,
where Hooks and other civil rights leaders will speak. The Rev.
Jesse Jackson and the Rev. Jospeh Lowery, head of the Southern
Christian Leadership Conference, and mayors Kurt Schmoke of
Baltimore and Marion Barry of Washington also are scheduled to
appear.
   Hooks and other NAACP officials would not predict a turnout more
specific than ``several thousand.'' Hooks said ``We are not looking
toward bringing vast numbers of peopole to Washington. In this
instance, the medium is the message and the medium is the silent
march.''
   The Supreme Court has often been the target of major
demonstrations in the capital in recent years. Last spring, an
estimated 325,000 turned out to urge the court to stand by its 1973
decision which legalized abortion, but the court, weeks later,
softened that ruling in a case seen as a victory for anti-abortion
forces.
</TEXT>
