<FIRST>r w AM-Hakim     08-24 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hakim,150</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Yorker Will Be Head Attorney in Iran-Contra Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York City attorney Stuart E. Abrams will be
the lead prosecutor for the case of Iran-Contra arms dealer Albert
Hakim, Independent Counsel Lawrence Walsh announced Thursday.
   Abrams, 36, a partner in the Chicago-based law firm of Mayer,
Brown &amp; Platt, was an assistant U.S. attorney for the Southern
District of New York from 1982 to 1989. He prosecuted bank fraud,
public corruption, money-laundering and tax-evasion cases, and was
in charge of the district's Major Crimes Unit from 1986 to 1988.
   Hakim is charged with conspiring to pay illegal gratuities, in
connection with the installation of a security fence at the home of
former National Security Council staffer Oliver North; and in the
establishment of a Swiss bank account for North's children.
   Hakim and his partner during the Iran-Contra affair, Richard
Secord, were North's chief arms dealers in the secret supply
operation for the Nicaraguan Contras.
   No trial date has been set.
