<FIRST>r a AM-GreekBanker     08-24 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greek Banker,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Magistrate Clears Way For Greek Banker's Extradition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fugitive Greek banker, accused in a
multimillion-dollar embezzlement scheme that helped topple the
government of Premier Andreas Papandreou, may be extradited to his
homeland, a magistrate ruled Thursday.
   In her order of extradition, U.S. Magistrate Joyce Alexander
found that the charges facing George Koskotas merited extradition
under a United States treaty with Greece, particularly his alleged
use of a fraudulent travel visa.
   Koskotas, 35, former chairman of the Bank of Crete, is accused by
Greek authorities of embezzling $200 million from 1986 to 1988 by
placing the bank's funds in his own accounts and accounts held by
his associates.
   Koskotas maintains he acted with the approval of Papandreou and
put the money into accounts controlled by the premier's party.
   Alexander's ruling clears the way for the State Department to
send Koskotas back to Greece, according to Assistant U.S. Attorney
Victor A. Wild.
   Susan Kempe, a Greek desk officer at the State Department in
Washington, could not immediately say what action the department
would take.
   However, Alexander granted attorneys for Koskotas a stay to
prepare an appeal. Koskotas will remain in custody.
   Koskotas had earlier refused to testify at his extradition
hearing.
   ``I am afraid if I testify here today I would endanger the lives
of my wife and children,'' he told the court.
   His attorney, Ron Liebman, said that Koskotas fled Brazil shortly
after learning Greek secret police were dispatched with orders to
kill him.
   Liebman was on vacation, and did not immediately return telephone
calls placed to his office.
   Among other things, Koskotas is accused of arranging a loan to be
deposited in a German bank, funneled through his brother, Stavros
Koskotas, and used to purchase a major soccer player from the German
soccer club Eintract Frankfurt for his team, Olympiakos.
   Koskotas has been held at the Essex County Jail in Salem since he
was arrested by federal authorities in November 1988 when he arrived
from Brazil.
</TEXT>
