<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 2202EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SonofHeaven     08-24 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Son of Heaven,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Celeste Welcomes Extension of China Exhibit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CHALFANT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Richard Celeste welcomed a nine-week
extension of a Chinese art exhibit Thursday, weeks after blocking
China from taking part in the Ohio State Fair because of the deadly
crackdown on students in Beijing.
   The closing day of the exhibition, which has attracted 530,000
visitors since it opened March 1, was extended from Sept. 4 to Nov.
5.
   The governor said at a news conference that ending the exhibition
early had been considered in response to the attack by Chinese
government troops on pro-Democracy students in Beijing in which
hundreds were believed killed, but said that was considered
inappropriate.
   Celeste said there was no inconsistency in extending the exhibit
within weeks of telling the Chinese they could not participate in
the fair.
   ``This is an exhibit sent here to help encourage understanding of
several thousand years of Chinese art and history, and would help us
to put, perhaps, events in China in some kind of a historical
context,'' he said.
   ``The participation in the Ohio State Fair was an altogether
different matter. It was something that was directly related to the
relationship that we have had with our sister province (Hubei),''
Celeste said.
   ``It was with great reluctance even there that I took the actions
that I took, but I think we've conveyed a message about how people
in Ohio feel about current events in China,'' he said.
   Celeste said the exhibition was a unique venture which should be
encouraged to continue. It was organized by the Overseas
Archaeological Exhibition Committee of the People's Republic of
China and Son of Heaven Inc. of Seattle.
   Son of Heaven has drawn visitors from all 50 states and from 50
nations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
