<FIRST>r a AM-ParalyzedWoman     08-24 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Paralyzed Woman,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Reviewing Welfare for Paralyzed Woman</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL L. BRAUN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who was told he must divorce his paralyzed
wife to get welfare assistance learned Thursday state officials
would reconsider.
   Alan Flowers had wept outside a courtroom Wednesday after a judge
handed down a 25-year prison term to the man who in January shot his
wife, Cynthia, 29, in the neck, paralyzing her from the chest down.
   ``What happened here ... was just a small part of what our
suffering is about now,'' said Flowers, 46.
   Reserve Circuit Judge Robert Cannon, who sentenced Clarence
Burgess, 52, vowed to look into the matter personally. Flowers
credited the judge's prodding for getting Milwaukee County
Department of Social Services officials to meet with him and his
wife at their home Thursday.
   The officials told Flowers they would reassess his wife's
eligibility for Aid for Families with Dependent Children.
   ``My heart goes out to Judge Cannon,'' Flowers said Thursday.
``He's a very, very fair and understanding judge.''
   Cannon said Thursday, ``I want to see that they're taken care of
immediately because apparently they've been getting the runaround
until this point.''
   Flowers said Social Services officials initially told him his
wife was not eligible for child care or other funds that would let
him return to work. He has turned over his auto sales and towing
business to a relative so he can care for his wife full-time.
   ``I was told that if I divorced her, she'd be eligible for AFDC
right away,'' he said. ``I turned and walked out of the office
crying.
   ``I can't do that. She's my wife.''
   Also on Thursday, a man who would only identify himself as
``Dan'' came to the couple's home and arranged to pay $1,659 in
delinquent payments on the couple's home, fending off repossession
for now.
   And a woman from the company that owns the wheelchair Mrs.
Flowers is using came to the house to tell the Flowers the chair
would not be repossessed as they had been told it would.
   ``There's nothing that can make me feel happy except to see my
wife get the help she needs'' so she can walk again, Flowers said.
   But the family's health insurance coverage ran out six weeks ago,
cutting off funding for her physical therapy.
   ``When she got out of the hospital, she could move her toes and
ankles,'' Flowers said. ``Now, without the therapy, it's nothing.''
   The state Justice Department's crime victims' compensation fund
awarded the family $40,000, but all the money went to the county for
medical bills, Flowers said.
   ``We never saw a dime, and there's over $180,000 still owed for
medical bills,'' he said.
</TEXT>
