<FIRST>r a AM-Lutherans     08-24 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lutherans,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Lutheran Denomination Confronts Familiar Issues: Budget And Abortion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROSEMONT, ILL. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new Evangelical Lutheran Church in
America held its first decision-making assembly Thursday and quickly
confronted two problems nagging many other denominations: abortion
and money.
   Abortion, like many other issues on which the newly merged
denomination so far has not established policies, broke unscheduled
into the process at a women's caucus meeting.
   The caucus proposed a resolution opposing attempts to
re-criminalize or restrict abortion, contending that action on the
issue had become necessary because of the recent U.S. Supreme Court
decision permitting state restrictions.
   To objections that a resolutions committee wanted to refer that
issue to a planned two-year study of sexuality, Barbara Nelson of
Lindsborg, Kan, replied:
   ``It is a stopgap until that study is done. It's about what's
happening in some states now.''
   The three major Lutheran denominations in the United States, the
Lutheran Church in America, the Lutheran Church-Missouri Synod and
the American Lutheran Church, merged into the new 5.3-million-member
church on Jan. 1, 1988. The three denominations had taken varying
positions on abortion.
   The eight-day assembly, representing the fourth-largest body in
U.S. Protestantism, began Wednesday.
   On the troubling financial situation, Bishop Herbert W.
Chilstrom, the denomination's president, told the approximately
1,050 delegates at the O'Hare Exposition Center, ``You ought to get
it out of your heads that there is some quick-fix for the problem.''
   Chilstrom said congregational giving was up a strong 5.5 percent
last year, outpacing inflation, and totaling $1.1 billion.
   But local churches used 92 percent of it, either on
congregational expenses or for local projects for the needy or
special causes such as hunger, relaying a reduced 8 percent for work
of regional synods or the national church.
   As with most major denominations, ``a higher percentage of funds
is staying at the local level,'' he said.
   He said the denomination had a $15.8 million shortfall below its
$104.3 million in expenditures in its first 14 months and a
continuing deficit in its 1989 budget, with expenditures cut from a
planned $99 to $92 million.
   To cope with the shortage, Childstrom detailed various measures
taken to cut expenses, including a hiring freeze, curtailed travel,
reduced meetings, no salary increase and some planned staff
reductions.
   ``It would seem out of the question for a reduction in services
and programs that are offered churchwide,'' he said.
   A special program among congregations, including an emphasis on
tithing, is planned to counter the financial squeeze.
   Chilstrom said that ``false assumptions about savings'' resulting
from church mergers was behind the drop in congregational support to
churchwide operations, as well as mounting local costs and expanded
local help projects.
   The denomination's executive council recommended a 1990 budget of
$102.5 million, with provisions that it be periodically revised to
keep expenditures in line with revenues.
</TEXT>
