<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Premier     08-24 0826</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Premier,0851</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mazowiecki Appeals for Interest and Friendliness from Press</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Tadeusz Mazowiecki faced the press
Thursday for the first time as prime minister of Poland, the modest
journalist limited the limelight so he could talk with two men who
guided him to his place in history.
   ``I would like to say that having left this room, in a moment, I
will call the Holy Father, John Paul II. And then the first prime
minister from Solidarity will get through to Lech Walesa,''
Mazowiecki said as he concluded the news conference.
   Then he thanked the scores of journalists who had peppered him
for more than an hour with questions on everything from his economic
plan to his travel schedule and urged them to change their focus:
   ``I ask you for further interest not in myself, but in Poland, in
our common problems, and for friendliness.''
   After President Wojciech Jaruzelski nominated the Solidarity
editor as prime minister Saturday, journalists besieged his cramped
offices at the independent movement's weekly newspaper, hoping for a
few words with the man about to lead the East bloc's first
non-Communist government.
   Before meeting the press Thursday, Mazowiecki visited his new,
spacious offices at the Council of Ministers building below the
cavernous hall where the news conference was held.
   ``I wanted to see ... I noticed that it was a little bit dark in
there. The windows are small, but the space is huge. I'd like to
preserve some human element,'' he said.
   A journalist since he founded the Catholic monthly Wiez, or Link,
in 1958, Mazowiecki spoke Thursday about the problems of the press
in Poland where the Communist government has tightly controlled
newspapers, radio and television.
   Solidarity was granted access to the mass media in the April
accords that led to restoration of its legal status after a
seven-year ban. The vigorous underground press went public, and
lines form for Mazowiecki's weekly and the opposition daily as soon
as they hit the newsstands.
   Solidarity also was given limited time on TV and radio, and
censorship rules have been much relaxed.
   The new prime minister said he is determined that society be
honestly informed about his government's activities.
   ``I want this government to tell the truth,'' he said.
   But asked whether he would abolish censorship, Mazowiecki replied
the president and parliament were responsible for changes in that
policy.
   In the coming months, the news may be bitter as Mazowiecki tries
to put together an economic plan to fight inflation, meet a $39
billion foreign debt and fill stores with goods shoppers can afford
or want to buy.
   Mazowiecki asked for time to name ministers representing Poland's
many political factions and develop an economic approach.
   ``My first task is to form the government and get acquainted with
everything. I'm not going to show any bright ideas right now because
they wouldn't be true. Maybe I'll be able to tell you more in a few
days,'' he said.
   That government that will be different from any he has known for
45 years, and Mazowiecki was asked about trips he probably never
thought he would take in a role he hardly could have imagined.
   ``Of course, I will be happy to go to Moscow and I will be happy
to go to Washington, if such is the need of Poland,'' he said.
   The country to send the first telegram of congratulations was,
unexpectedly, East Germany, a Warsaw Pact ally that has been highly
skeptical of the radical departures from socialism undertaken by its
neighbor to the east.
   Mazowiecki said Poland's democratic reforms do not represent a
threat to countries within the military alliance that he has pledged
to respect.
   ``I don't think that people striving for reforms should be
identified with enemies of the Warsaw Pact and those who want to
undermine it,'' he said.
   The new prime minsiter also said he expected a cordial
relationship with Jaruzelski, who only eight years ago declared
martial law to suppress Solidarity and imprison thousands of
activists, including Mazowiecki.
   ``It is my task and duty as prime minister to fully respect the
competences of the president and I hope for full respect for myself
on the part of the president. My first contacts with the president
show that it is going to be like that,'' he said.
   He appealed for patience from Poles, many of whom are more
interested in a quick improvement in their living standards than
dramatic steps toward democracy.
   ``I think that at the moment we should hope. I'd like to express
such hope and ask people who are on strike or intend to, to enable
this government to form itself and begin its activities,'' he said.
   And he set his goal: ``What I would like to achieve _ and I say
this with all sincerity and openness _ is what Poland needs very
badly: creation of a new climate.''
</TEXT>
