<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 2219EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-GemMistake     08-24 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gem Mistake,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Misdirected Package Holds $2 Million in Gems</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KNOXVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Businessman Larry Jackson expected an
overdue shipment of weightlifting gloves. The package he opened,
however, contained an estimated $2 million in uncut gems.
   ``Do I feel like a fool for turning it in?'' he said with a laugh
Thursday. ``Yeah.''
   The 50-pound, locked and sealed steel container was delivered by
American Eagle airlines Wednesday to Jackson's business, Atlas
Fitness Products Inc.
   The box had no return address, but it came with airline paperwork
showing it was the lost piece of a 25-package shipment of
weightlifting gloves Jackson received in July from Pakistan.
   Jackson took delivery even though it didn't resemble his usual
glove shipments. ``You don't have to be a rocket scientist to figure
out that this was not what it was supposed to be. I mean, it came in
what was like a little vault,'' he said.
   So Jackson called the U.S. Customs office.
   ``The inspector on duty said just to hold it and return it to the
shipper,'' said Liz Orgeron, a Customs spokeswoman in New Orleans.
   But Jackson, a reserve deputy with the Knox County Sheriff's
Department, said he became concerned when no one retrieved the box
by the end of the day.
   ``I did not want to be responsible for it because I knew it was
something that appeared to be of great value,'' he said.
   Jackson called the sheriff's department and a detective was sent
out. But the detective didn't want to take possession of the package
without knowing what was inside.
   ``I understand his point,'' Jackson said. ``The thing came from
the Islamic world. God knows, what was in it. It could be cobra
venom ... or a bomb or something.''
   With the help of a local auto mechanic and his blowtorch, the box
was opened.
   Inside were more than 50 quartz-like stones, some purplish,
others milky white, wrapped in Afghan newspapers.
   A local jeweler, after consultation with a colleague, determined
the uncut gems were kunzite, which are native to Afghanistan, and
conservatively estimated their value at $2 million.
   Ms. Orgeron said American Eagle was trying Wednesday to track
down the gems' owner. Airline officials at company headquarters in
Dallas did not return phone calls.
   Ms. Orgeron said it was unclear where the package was supposed to
go, but the airline determined it was definitely not Knoxville. She
said the routing problem likely occurred when the package passed
through John F. Kennedy Airport near New York City.
   The gems were being kept in a vault at the sheriff's department
awaiting pickup by customs officials, said Sheriff Joe Fowler.
   Jackson, meanwhile, is still wondering where his missing gloves
are. ``Customs promised me they were going to make an effort to find
them,'' he said. ``That's the least they can do, since I'm not
allowed to keep the stones.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
