<SECOND>AM-Bush-Appointments,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ivory Coast Ambassadorship, Defense Positions Filled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush on Thursday announced
he will name career foreign service officer Kenneth Brown as
ambassador to the Ivory Coast.
   Brown is deputy assistant secretary of state for African affairs
and previously was consul general in Johannesburg. He was ambassador
to the Congo in 1981 and before that served in a variety of
diplomatic posts.
   Bush's vacation White House also announced the president will
name Christopher Jehn as assistant secretary of defense for
management and personnel, and Ronald E. Ray as asssistant secretary
of veterans affairs for human resources and administration.
   Jehn is vice president of the Navy-Marine Corps Planning and
Manpower division and has served in various other posts at the
Center for Naval Analysis, a federally funded research and
development center.
   Ray, a Medal of Honor winner for his Army service, is president
of the Ronald E. Ray, Inc. investment company in Winter Haven, Fla.,
and previously was a White House fellow in the Commerce Department.
   In addition, the White House said Bush will name Tony Armendariz
as a member of the Federal Labor Relations Authority, succeeding
Jerry Lee Calhoun, for the term expiring at the end of July 1992.
   Armendariz is general counsel for the University System of South
Texas in Kingsville, Texas. He was formerly the Texas assistant
attorney general and district counsel for the U.S. Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission.
   The authority oversees labor relations with federal employees.
