<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 1716EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-INS-GreenCards     08-24 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-INS-Green Cards,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>INS Sees Red Over Black Market Green Cards</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Green cards,'' which reflect an alien's
permanent resident status in the United States and have been
off-white since 1977, are being changed to pink in an effort to
curtail the black market in the documents, an official said Thursday.
   ``You can buy a lousy reproduction'' of the old green cards for
$5,000 to $10,000, said Immigration and Naturalization Service
spokesman Verne Jervis.
   ``But people have been known to pay $20,000,'' he said. ``It
depends on how much money the person has, how good the card is and
how much the person is willing to pay.
   ``Some people will pay an almost unending amount of money'' for
the cards, he said.
   Those who hold the cards have all the rights and privileges of
citizens except they cannot vote, may not leave the country for more
than a year without losing permanent resident status and do not hold
U.S. passports, he said.
   The new cards will be phased in over time, said Jervis.
   Production of the new cards began Aug. 1 at the Immigration Card
Facilitity in Arlington, Texas. The $4 million changeover of
equipment will be completed within a few months, but until then,
some of the cards being issued will remain the familiar off-white
color, he said.
   The INS changed the cards for several reason, he said.
   ``One, it's an improved card, as far as duplicating it is
concerned,'' he said. ``It has some additional security features,
such as the special ink'' that helps combat forgeries.
   ``Another reason is that the equipment that we have been
producing the card on for the last 12 years is due for a replacement
anyway,'' Jervis said. ``New technology has evolved during that
time. As long as we have to get new equipment, we may as well take
advantage of the new technology.''
   One feature of the new card is a stamped expiration date, he
said. The laminated cards will be valid for 10 years.
   The cards also have the individual's picture, fingerprint, name,
date of birth and file number on the front and encoded information
on the back, he said.
   The INS will not undertake the overwhelming task of replacing the
10 million cards already held by permanent resident aliens, said
Jervis.
   The service replaces about 230,000 cards a year that have been
either lost or stolen or because of changes such as a changed name,
Jervis said.
   A ``good many'' of the 230,000 were reported lost or stolen, said
Jervis, but he could not estimate how many of those may have ended
up being sold on the black market.
   The new cards, because of the encoded information, will enable
those who want replacements to do so by mail rather than in person,
which had been required for the old cards, he said.
   The INS is processing applications of 1.8 million people who
applied for temporary resident status under the amnesty program for
those who have been in the United States since before 1982. The
period to apply for that program ended in May 1988. After 18 months,
those people have one year to apply for permanent resident status,
he said.
   In addition, some 1.3 million special agricultural workers have
applied for temporary resident status under a separate program, and
they will be given permanent resident status without need for
additional application between December 1989 and December 1990,
Jervis said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890824-0149 </DOCNO>
