<FIRST>u w AM-US-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0665 08-24 0665</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0665,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Weighs Tighter Sanctions Against Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Inserts two grafs after 16th pvs, Specifically, the ..., to
add Pentagon comment; also corrects spelling of Adolf in 6th graf, Deputy
Secretary ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration is weighing the
possibility of tightening existing sanctions against Panama now that
efforts by the Organization of American States to achieve a
democratic transfer of power are at an apparent dead end, officials
said Thursday.
   The reevaluation of administration policy toward Panama followed
what officials regarded as a disappointing outcome of a three-month
effort by OAS mediators to promote a restoration of democratic rule
in Panama.
   The officials declined to specify what economic measures against
Panama are under consideration. Last year, the Reagan administration
froze Panama's assets in the United States, withheld fees owed to
Panama for Panama Canal operations and suspended certain trade
benefits.
   The measures have contributed to a substantial economic decline
in Panama.
   After OAS foreign ministers approved a blandly worded resolution
early Thursday following all-night discussions, the U.S. and
Panamanian delegations engaged in unusually heated verbal sparring,
with each side blaming the other for the impasse.
   Deputy Secretary of State Lawrence Eagleburger compared Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega to Adolf Hitler and derided Panama as an
``outlaw regime'' that deserves the censure of all OAS member
states. Eagleburger's remarks prompted a walkout by Panamanian
Foreign Minister Jorge Ritter.
   In a vitriolic two-hour rebuttal, Panamanian delegate Romulo
Escobar Betancourt blamed the United States for the lack of progress
toward a political solution in Panama, citing both the U.S. economic
sanctions and what he described as the unsettling impact of U.S.
military maneuvers in Panama.
   He also challenged Eagleburger to prove his allegations about
Noriega's involvement in drug trafficking.
   ``If you have any evidence to show Gen. Noriega is involved in
drug trafficking, bring it here to the OAS,'' Escobar said. Noriega
was indicted last year on drug smuggling charges by two federal
grand juries in Florida.
   The OAS resolution expressed ``deep concern'' over the inability
of the mediators to lay the groundwork for a political settlement in
Panama. It also ``resolutely exhorts'' Panamanians to settle their
differences by the time a new president is scheduled to be sworn in.
   Under Panama's constitution, an ``elected president'' is due to
take office on Sept. 1, but Ritter said it is unclear what will
happen on that date because there is no officially recognized
successor to President Manuel Solis Palma.
   Panamanian authorities voided the outcome of last May's national
elections after independent observers concluded that the opposition
candidate had won by a comfortable margin.
   Ritter expressed hope that the government and opposition leaders
can agree on a course of action by Sept. 1 that would enable the
country to sidestep the possibility of a constitutional crisis.
   At the State Department Thursday, deputy spokesman Richard
Boucher said ``the key to solving the problem is for Noriega to be
willing to discuss the terms for his departure.''
   State Department officials were outraged Wednesday when a report
submitted by the OAS mediators blamed the United States, in part,
for the continuing impasse in Panama without making any reference to
Noriega.
   Specifically, the report said U.S. military maneuvers in Pamama
had a ``negative effect'' on the negotiating process and were
``inopportune.''
   At the Pentagon, spokesman Fred Hoffman defended the U.S.
military exercises in the canal area, saying they were conducted in
accordance with the Panama Canal treaties and the U.S. mission of
defending the canal.
   ``What we're doing is not confrontational,'' Hoffman said. ``We
have notified the PDF (Panamanian Defense Forces) in advance of
these exercises. They are are all covered fully under the terms of
the treaties.''
   The official U.S. view is that Noriega precipitated the crisis by
refusing to recognize the perceived victory by the opposition
candidate in the elections last May and then aggravated the
situation by insisting on retaining his post as commander of
Panama's military forces.
</TEXT>
