<DOCNO> AP890824-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 2243EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Turtles     08-24 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Turtles,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Center Says Commerce Guarding Turtle Findings Like Espionage Matter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Center for Marine Conservation accused the
Commerce Department on Thursday of squelching scientific findings
and treating the issue of endangered sea turtle deaths as if it were
a ``matter of Soviet intrigue and espionage.''
   The agency, caught between the opposing demands of shrimpers and
environmentalists, is under a court order to draft final regulations
by Sept. 8 that would protect endangered sea turtles from drowning
in shrimpers nets.
   The public was given 15 days to comment and has deluged the
department with thousands of letters. But the Center for Marine
Conservation says it has been unable to obtain biological opinions
from the agency's own scientists on the most effective way of
preventing sea turtle deaths.
   At issue is whether shrimpers must be required to equip their
nets with devices that allow turtles to escape, the choice of
environmentalists, or whether they should restrict their tow times
and check their nets before the submerged turtles drown, the choice
of many Gulf Coast shrimpers.
   Under temporary regulations, shrimpers are being required to pull
their nets every 105 minutes or use the turtle excluder devices,
TEDs.
   The Center for Marine Conservation said Commerce has
``squelched'' biological recommendations and ignored the findings of
its own scientists that TEDs are far more effective in preventing
turtle deaths than restricted tow times.
   The center's Marydele Donnelly accused the agency of withholding
so much information on its scientists' own studies that her
organization has been forced to file Freedom of Information Act
requests.
   ``Conservation of endangered species is not a matter of Soviet
intrigue and espionage,'' she said. ``The American public has a
right to know how and why Commerce Secretary ( robert) Mosbacher
came to such outlandish conclusions regarding 105-minute tow times
when the record is clear that these regulations are based on false
premises.''
   Commerce spokesman Brian Gorman said every possible credible
source of information, from within and outside the agency, is being
considered as the final rules are drafted.
   Meanwhile, public comment on the issue continues to pour in. The
National Marine Fisheries Service has counted 3,100 letters to date
and more are coming in, said Charles Karnella, chief of the
protected species management division.
   He said the letters are overwhelmingly in favor of TEDs, but
would not provide a tally.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890824-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 2103EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MedicalApplicants     08-24 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Medical Applicants,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fewer Med School Applicants for Fourth Straight Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROCKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of medical-school applicants has
declined for the fourth straight year and scores on admissions tests
are down slightly, but there is no immediate threat to quality
medical care, a researcher said Thursday.
   And while more women and minorities are applying to medical
schools, there is room for improvement, said Barbara Barzansky,
assistant director of the American Medical Association's Division of
Undergraduate Education and co-author of a study in Friday's Journal
of the AMA.
   ``The increasing diversity is encouraging,'' Ms. Barzansky said.
``But there's a lot more _ especially in the area of minorities _
that needs to be done.''
   While the number of freshmen increased slightly for the first
time since 1984, applications and total enrollment still are down.
   ``There are a lot more opportunities for young people these days
where you can go out and start your career a lot sooner, instead of
having to spend four years in medical school and three years in
residency,'' Ms. Barzansky said.
   The number of applicants has dropped from 35,944 in 1984 to
28,123 in 1987 and 26,721 in 1988, the study showed.
   But the number of freshmen in 1988 increased to 16,781 from
16,686 the year before.
   That means medical schools accepted one freshman student for
every 1.6 applicants, up from one out of every 2.1 in 1984, the
report said.
   Average admissions-test scores for the students dropped slightly,
from 56.4 out of a total possible 90 in 1987 to 55.2 in 1988.
   But Ms. Barzansky said there was little cause for concern.
   ``It's not as if suddenly the whole medical school class has
declined drastically,'' she said. ``Students still have to meet the
same standards for graduation.''
   Ms. Barzansky said while applications and enrollment are down,
there is no immediate threat to the country's supply of doctors.
   ``If you look at the average number of physicians there's no
shortage,'' she said. ``If you look at certain specialties, there
may be a problem.''
   Possible problem areas include primary-care physicians _ mostly
general practitioners and family doctors _ and those willing to work
in rural and inner-city areas, she said.
   ``There are still concerns about providing medical care across
the country, making sure everybody's got access,'' Ms. Barzansky
said.
   Another study in the journal said 83 percent of medical school
graduates had education-related debts.
   The average owed was $38,489, up from the $14,600 owed on average
by the 74 percent of 1974 graduates with debts, said study co-author
Paul Jolly, an associate vice president at the Association of
American Medical Colleges.
   Jolly and Ms. Barzansky said increased financial aid is key to
easing debts and boosting minority enrollment.
   Ms. Barzansky's study showed that blacks make up 6 percent of all
medical school students, 5 percent of 1988 graduates and 6.3 percent
of last year's freshmen.
   Asian enrollment was up from 7.6 percent among graduates to 12.4
percent among entering freshmen, while Hispanic enrollment held
steady at about 5.4 percent, the study said.
   ``Minority enrollment is rising very slowly,'' Jolly said.
``There is a lot of financial aid available for minority students,
but it is not enough.''
   The number of women in medical schools also has increased, with
women making up 37 percent of those entering classes and 33.3
percent of graduates.
   The total number of women in medical school, however, has
declined since 1985, the study said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
