<FIRST>u i AM-Obit-Yakovlev     08-24 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Yakovlev,0540</SECOND>
<HEAD>Aircraft Designer Yakovlev Dead at Age 83</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Aircraft designer Alexander S. Yakovlev, who built
warplanes that challenged German Messerschmitts in World War II and
modern passenger jets, has died after a long illness, Tass said
Thursday. He was 83.
   Yakovlev, who died Tuesday, was awarded the Soviet Union's
prestigious Lenin Prize and was twice named a Hero of Socialist
Labor. The official Soviet news agency did not say what illness he
had suffered from.
   He was eulogized in an obituary signed by President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev and other top Soviet officials.
   ``Yakovlev was known for his tireless search for fresh ideas,
creative courage and great talent for organization,'' Tass said.
   Born April 1, 1906, Yakovlev's career as a dedsigner spanned more
than 60 years. He was the last of a generation of aircraft designers
including Oleg Antonov, Alexei Tupolev and Sergei Ilyushin who
dominated Soviet aviation for decades.
   One Western expert in Moscow, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said it had been unclear in recent years whether Yakovlev
was still in charge of design of Yakovlev planes.
   As a 20-year-old aircraft fitter at Moscow's Central Airport in
1927, Yakovlev designed the AIR-1, a light airplane that set a world
record by covering the 800-mile route from the Crimean city
Sevastopol to Moscow in 15 hours and 30 minutes.
   The best-known Yakovlev planes of the past decade are the Yak-38,
known by NATO experts as the Forger, the country's only plane
capable of landing and taking off from naval vessels, and the
120-passenger Yak-42 short-haul passenger jet.
   Yuri Gagarin, a test pilot who was the first man in space, made
his first flights in a Yak-18 training plane.
   During World War II, Yakovlev's fighter planes, the Yak-1 through
Yak-9 were the dominant force in the Soviet air force. Of 61,000
fighters built by the Soviet Union during the war years, 37,000 of
them were Yaks.
   In a 1976 article, the weekly Moscow News cited a telegram the
Soviet Defense Committee received from air force pilots telling them
how they had fought off 25 German planes with seven Yak-1s.
   ``The pilots ... showed that these Soviet planes were more than a
match for the famous Messerschmitts and Junkers,'' it said.
   In the opinion of Western experts, the design of the Yak-3,
considered one of the best of Yakovlev's World War II fighters, was
``impossibly crude and the welding looked as if it had been done by
a village blacksmith,'' the paper said.
   But the outer finish was superb and the plane was reliable, it
said.
   In the postwar years, as the MiG became the dominant Soviet
jetfighter, Yakovlev increasingly turned his attention to civilian
aircraft.
   One such plane, the Yak-55, was displayed on Sunday in Moscow's
first air show in more than 20 years.
   Yakovlev, in a 1976 interview with the labor newspaper Trud on
his 70th birthday, said, ``I want to work and work, so that I can
penetrate still further into the unknown, so that I can reach new
unscaled summits. This is the purpose of life for a designer.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
