<FIRST>u a AM-APAppointments     08-24 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Appointments,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Bureau Chiefs Named</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New chiefs for three Associated Press foreign
bureaus were named Thursday by Louis D. Boccardi, president and
general manager of the news cooperative.
   Andy Torchia, chief of bureau in Johannesburg for the past eight
years, becomes chief of Nordic services, based in Stockholm, Sweden.
He will be responsible for operations in Sweden, Norway, Finland and
Denmark.
   Barry Renfrew, chief of bureau in Seoul, South Korea, since 1987,
has been appointed as Torchia's successor in South Africa.
   Kelly Smith Tunney, who has held several AP news and executive
positions, most recently as a news correspondent on the Seoul staff,
succeeds Renfrew.
   Torchia replaces Larry Gerber, whose appointment as assistant
chief of bureau in Los Angeles was announced earlier.
   A 21-year veteran of the AP's foreign service, Torchia, 52,
joined the AP in New York in 1961, and worked in London before
serving as chief of bureau in Nairobi, Kenya; Lisbon, Portugal; and
Johannesburg.
   A native of Lancaster, Pa., he is a graduate of Yale University.
   Renfrew, 35, began his career with the AP as a newsman on the
General Desk in New York in 1978. He also worked in the Charleston,
W.Va., bureau. His first foreign assignment was to the staff in
Sydney, Australia, in 1983. He was chief of bureau in Islamabad,
Pakistan, before his most recent assignment to Korea.
   Born in London, he is a graduate of Clark University in
Worcester, Mass.
   Before her assignment in Seoul in 1988, Mrs. Tunney, 49, was an
assistant general manager and director of corporate communications
for the AP in New York. She had previously held a variety of news
and administrative posts. She has been assistant personnel manager,
director of media relations, director of corporate relations, a
correspondent in Vietnam in 1967 and a newswoman in New York,
Washington and Los Angeles.
   A native of New York City and graduate of the University of
Kansas, she joined the AP in Miami in 1962.
</TEXT>
