<FIRST>u i AM-Angola     08-24 0442</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Angola,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angolan Guerrilla Leader Goes Back to War</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S.-backed guerrilla leader Jonas
Savimbi ordered his fighters back to the battlefield in Angola on
Thursday, ending a fractured truce that was the country's latest
hope in a 14-year-old civil war.
   The rebel leader accused Angolan government troops of launching a
big military offensive against his fighters in southern Angola on
Aug. 17.
   ``The Angolan people, to their infinite sorrow, accept that the
war has restarted,'' Savimbi said in a statement issued from his
southern Angolan stronghold of Jamba and released in Lisbon.
   His announcement comes the day after seven of the African leaders
who helped broker Angola's June 24 cease-fire ended a meeting in
Harare, Zimbabwe, to try to put the fractured peace process back on
track.
   Cuban-backed Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos sealed the
truce with Savimbi at a summit of 18 African leaders at Gbadolite,
Zaire.
   The rebel leader Thursday also said his National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola ``rejected in the most violent terms''
a communique released by the leaders who met in Harare.
   In it, they supported dos Santos' claim that Savimbi agreed at
the Gbadolite summit to accept ``temporary and voluntary
retirement'' during cease-fire and peace negotiations, and that his
guerrillas would be integrated into the existing Angolan political
structure.
   Savimbi says he would never agree to leave Angola and wants peace
on condition dos Santos holds elections leading to a power-sharing
arrangement.
   The rebel leader never has had the opportunity to test his
popularity at the polls. His followers have been at war since
Portuguese colonizers hastily withdrew from the country in 1975,
leaving rival groups to fight for power.
   Angolan government and rebel delegates have held sporadic talks
in Zaire to try to resolve their differences since the cease-fire.
   The United States, which gives Savimbi between $15 million and
$18 million in aid a year, said Wednesday it had expected another
round of talks in Zaire shortly.
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said national
reconciliation in Angola only can be achieved by direct negotiations
between the two sides and siad Washington has urged both parties to
progress on the central issue of how to achieve reconciliation.
   A major U.S. oil company is among several international concerns
that have interests in the oil- and mineral-rich nation and stand to
benefit from peace there.
   The Angolan peace process followed U.S.-brokered international
accords signed in New York by which South Africa pledged to halt aid
to Savimbi and allow Angola's southern neighbor, Namibia, to gain
independence. In return, Cuba began a phased withdrawal of its
estimated 50,000 troops from Angola.
</TEXT>
