<FIRST>r w AM-US-SouthAfrica     08-24 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-South Africa,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Urges Government Restraint</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department urged South Africa on
Thursday to exercise restraint in dealing with demonstrations by
blacks opposed to its apartheid racial policies.
   The department said that recent waves of arrests of opposition
leaders could endanger an emerging trend toward negotiations between
the white minority and black majority.
   The statement was prompted by several weeks of clashes between
authorities and anti-apartheid groups that launched a defiance
campaign Aug. 2 to end the segregation of hospitals, schools,
beaches and other facilities.
   On Thursday, police in Cape Town fired tear gas at hundreds of
protesting university students and arrested 22 white women from a
civil rights group. Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu, a Nobel Peace
Prize winner, was tear-gassed Wednesday when police broke up a
protest.
   ``We call on all parties in South Africa to reject the continuing
cycle of violence,'' the statement said. ``One of the tragic results
of this violence has been that now, soon after large numbers of
detainees had been released, the government has begun to rearrest
key opposition leaders.''
   The announcement said that events in South Africa ``serve to
underline the need, which we have long advocated, for the government
to allow all sides to freely voice their opposition.
   ``We again urge the South African government to create a climate
in which real negotiations with legitimate black leaders can take
place.
   ``All sides should avoid actions that may reduce the chances for
an early start to negotiations. We call on the South African
government to exercise maximum restraint in the use of force against
peaceful political protesters,'' it said.
