<FIRST>u i AM-Refugees 1stLd-Writethru a0591 08-24 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Refugees, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0591,0599</SECOND>
<HEAD>108 East Germans Allowed To Leave Hungary</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Refugees-Labor, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Horn comment, ADD East German
denial. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government allowed 108 East Germans
who took refuge in the West German Embassy to leave Hungary on
Thursday and they arrived in West Germany, officials said.
   Diplomatic sources said at least 190 others crossed the border
into Austria illegally on Thursday.
   Up to 5,000 East Germans have reportedly reached the West by way
of Hungary, almost all of them illegally, since the exodus began in
mid-July.
   Foreign Minister Gyula Horn said 150,000 to 200,000 East Germans
are in Hungary now, and the official MTI news agency quoted him as
telling reporters an increasing number of them do not want to return
home.
   Hungary, one of the most liberal Soviet bloc nations, began
removing barbed wire and other obstacles from its frontier with
Austria in May.
   The strict East German regime seldom lets its citizens travel to
the West, but they have been able to visit neighboring Hungary with
ease.
   The Bonn-based Die Welt newspaper said Thursday that East Germany
plans to impose strict new travel regulations to Hungary as of Sept.
1 to stem the refugee flow.
   The East German Foreign Ministry called it ``an outright lie.''
   The state-run news agency ADN quoted a ministry official as
saying, ``These lies and fabrications are being spread in Cold War
style to create confusion and to slander East Germany. The truth is
that travel to Hungary as well as to Bulgaria and Romania continues
as usual.''
   The 108 East Germans were allowed to travel West, with documents
provided by the International Red Cross, ``on the basis of
humanitarian considerations,'' MTI said.
   Austrian radio quoted Austrian Red Cross officials as saying the
International Committee of the Red Cross in Geneva organized the
transfer in response to a request from Bonn.
   The group flew to Vienna, the Austrian capital, on a chartered
flight and then continued by bus to West Germany, the officials said.
   Horn said Hungary was not interested in any increase in the
number of East Germans staying here or ``in transit.'' He said
Hungary views this a problem that must be solved by the two Germanys.
   Witnesses confirmed reports that Hungarian border guards
intercepted a group of about 150 East Germans who traveled to the
border in three buses and three taxis Wednesday.
   One escaper, who gave his name only as Lothar K., told The
Associated Press about 50 guards used truncheons to disperse the
group as they tried to walk toward the border with arms linked to
protect women and children.
   ``I never imagined something like that could happen,'' he said on
Thursday.
   He and his wife and child hid in the bushes throughout the night
and then furtively crossed the border at daybreak, he said.
   Diplomatic sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said many
others later escaped across the border at another point.
   Few reports of border violence have surfaced since the exodus
began. The shooting death Monday of an East German who struggled
with a Hungarian border guard was deemed an accident by Hungarian
and Austrian officials Thursday.
   A group of four young East Germans who fled to Austria Thursday
said a guard who caught them indicated when he sent them back that
he would look away if they tried again. A few hours later they tried
again and succeeded, with no guard in sight.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
