<FIRST>u w AM-HUD-PaineWebber     08-24 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Paine Webber,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>House Subcommittee Wants Investment Executive to Testify</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House panel investigating favoritism and
mismanagement in federal housing programs was in a standoff with
Paine Webber Inc. Thursday over whether the company's chief
executive officer will be called to testify next month.
   Rep. Tom Lantos, D-Calif., chairman of the House Government
Operations housing subcommittee, invited Donald B. Marron, chief
executive officer of the investment firm, to testify on Sept. 27
about the firm's consulting arrangements with the Department of
Housing and Urban Development.
   In a letter dated Tuesday, Lantos said questions about Paine
Webber's involvement had been raised during the panel's
investigation of Lance Wilson, a first vice president of Paine
Webber and a former HUD official. Wilson has been subpoenaed to
testify at the Sept. 27 hearing.
   ``In your testimony please describe the results of your internal
study of the firm's involvement with HUD, company policy on
influence peddling by its employees to secure contracts, and
limitations on outside consulting work by Paine Webber employees,''
Lantos wrote.
   Paine Webber said earlier this month it had opened an
investigation of its dealings with HUD.
   In a statement issued Wednesday in New York, Paine Webber said,
``The appropriate person to testify is James C. Treadway Jr., our
general counsel, and we have so suggested to the subcommittee.''
   Andrea Nelson, a spokeswoman for the subcommittee, said the
panel's staff director, Stuart Weisberg, talked with Treadway by
telephone on Wednesday and told him it would be up to Lantos to
decide whether he would still like to have Marron appear.
   Lantos is traveling in Eastern Europe and Ms. Nelson said he
could not immediately be reached.
   Wilson said through his lawyer on Wednesday that he had gone on
administrative leave with pay, at his request.
   The company's statement said, ``Our decision to grant Mr. Wilson
the leave in no way implies any wrongdoing on his part of Paine
Webber's.''
   Wilson, who was executive assistant to former HUD Secretary
Samuel R. Pierce Jr., cited his Fifth Amendment right against self
incrimination in refusing to testify before the panel last week.
