<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru a0619 08-24 0725</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0619,0745</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rival Shiite Militias Unite Against French</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS two grafs of related developments, with minor editing to
trim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rival Shiite Moslem militias said Thursday
they had united against a French flotilla off Lebanon, and the
radical Hezbollah faction said its response will ``horrify
everybody'' if the warships approach.
   Hezbollah did not say what it would do, but has threatened
suicide attacks on Western targets and is believed to sponsor Shiite
gangs that hold most of the 16 Western hostages in Lebanon.
   Police said one person was killed and three were wounded in
shelling along the line that divides the capital into Moslem west
Beirut and the Christian eastern sector.
   Skirmishes along the line have occurred daily since an artillery
war began March 8 between the 20,000 men of Gen. Michel Aoun's
Christian army command and a Moslem alliance led by the 40,000
Syrian soldiers stationed in Lebanon. By police count, 791 people
have been killed and 2,208 wounded.
   A senior Soviet official drove from Damascus, Syria, for talks
with Moslem and Christian on deadlocked efforts to end the fighting
and ease tension over the French naval buildup in the eastern
Mediterranean.
   Lebanese military sources said some French vessels were cruising
40 miles off Lebanon, ``distant from commercial shipping lanes.''
   The aircraft carrier Foch, with 2,000 marines aboard, leads the
task force. The French say it is on ``hmanitarian mission,'' to
evacuate the 7,000 French citizens in Lebanon if necessary.
   Syria and its allies claim France, which governed Lebanon from
the end of World War I until 1943, is allying itself with the
Christians. Syrian troops have been in Lebanon since 1976, a year
after the civil war began, under an Arab League peacekeeping mandate.
   Ali Akbar Velayati, the foreign minister of Iran, sent a message
to U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar asking for
``urgent and decisive measures to prevent this ... provocative
military interference and keep the Frnech fleet away from Lebanese
territorial waters.''
   Hezbollah and Amal, a more moderate Shiite militia allied with
Syria, have fought a bloody power struggle for 16 months, but said
Thursday they were joining forces against ``this
American-Israeli-French plot.''
   Their declaration followed a meeting in Tyre, 50 miles south of
Beirut, with Abbas Mousawi of Hezbollah and Amal chieftain Nabih
Berri as joint chairmen.
   Mousawi said afterward: ``We can confront this ... plot only if
our ranks were consolidated. This danger threatens all of us.''
   ``We're facing the threat of Lebanon's partition,'' he said.
``France has declared its support of the partitioning of Lebanon.''
   He waved a clenched fist in the air and said: ``Our battle will
horrify everybody!''
   Berri said: ``The war between Amal and Hezbollah is over for
good. We tell France ... that we will certainly strike at the French
force if it approaches our coasts.''
   Police say 575 people have been killed and more than 1,550
wounded in the Amal-Hezbollah war for supremacy among the 1 million
Shiites, Lebanon's largest sect.
   Hezbollah has threatened suicide attacks against Western targets
if France tries to help the Christians.
   The Revolutionary Justice Organization, which holds American
hostages Joseph Cicippio and Edward Tracy, both 58, has said French
involvement would endanger their lives.
   Six more Americans are among the hostages, but no French captives
now are being held. The hostage held longest is Terry A. Anderson,
chief Middle East correspondent of The Associated Press, kidnapped
March 16, 1985.
   Gennady Tarasov, the Soviet envoy, met in west Beirut with acting
Premier Salim Hoss, a Sunni Moslem who leads a Moslem Cabinet
competing for power with Aoun's Christian government.
   Tarasov also conferred with Parliament Speaker Hussein Husseini,
a Shiite, and planned to meet with Christian leaders in east Beirut.
He heads the Soviet Foreign Ministry's Middle East department.
   In Damascus, Tarasov met with Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa.
Syria is Moscow's main Arab ally.
   Also Thursday, more than 100 Lebanese refugees in Limassol,
Cyprus, lined up to donate blood for casualties of the Lebanese
fighting. The Lebanese community on the east Mediterranean island
has swollen to more than 20,000 through the influx of refugees.
   In Venezuela, the lower house of Congress asked the government to
open that country's doors to to members of Lebanon's Maronite
Christian community who want to immigrate to Venezuela, newspapers
reported.
</TEXT>
