<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 1901EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Iran     08-24 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rafsanjani Looks Set To Win Parliament's Backing For Cabinet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tehran newspapers said Thursday that
Hashemi Rafsanjani, the new president of Iran, will win
parliamentary approval of his new Cabinet despite opposition from
radicals to his dismissal of hard-liners.
   The Tehran Times, which often speaks for Rafsanjani, said his
government choices would be approved only after ``a really sizzling
debate,'' scheduled to begin Sunday.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency quoted the
English-language daily as saying the debate could last three days.
   Hojatoleslam Hussein Sobhaninia, a senior member of the Majlis,
the 270-seat parliament, said a ``large number'' of deputies had
decided to support Rafsanjani's 22-man slate as a demonstration of
national unity, the paper said.
   ``All agreed that the proposed ministers should get clearance
from the Majlis, said Sobhaninia, a member of the Foreign Policy
Committee, according to the Tehran Times report.
   Noting that Iraq still occupies Iranian territory despite the
truce declared a year ago in the eight-year war, Sobhaninia said:
``If all the proposed ministers receive votes of confidence, it will
be another slap in the face of our enemies.''
   Former President Ali Khamenei, who became spiritual leader after
the death June 3 of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, urged the Majlis on
Wednesday to set aside political differences and support Rafsanjani.
   Khamenei told the deputies they should ``vote on competence
alone'' rather than ``differences of taste or God forbid, personal
matters.''
   Khamenei, Rafsanjani and others generally considered pragmatists
have denied a power struggle followed Khomeini's death, but the
Khamenei appeal underlined opposition to Rafsanjani's policies and
the ministers he has chosen.
   Radicals have considerable influence in parliament, where
Rafsanjani was replaced as speaker by Mehdi Karrubi, who was his
deputy and advocates the vilent spread of Khomeini's Islamic
revolution.
   Rafsanjani favors openings to the West to end Iran's isolation
and attract aid and foreign investment. He also seeks to liberalize
the economy, long constrained by tight state control under Prime
Minister Hussein Musavi, whose job was abolished by the new
constitution.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
