<FIRST>u i AM-Egypt-Arrests     08-24 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egypt-Arrests,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leftist Opposition Says 28 Arrested</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small leftist opposition group claimed
Thursday the security forces arrested 28 men in dawn raids and
accused them of forming a communist party.
   In Egypt, communist parties are illegal but personal belief in
communism is accepted.
   The Moscow-oriented National Unionist Progressive Party issued a
statement saying those arrested, most from its own ranks, had
sympathized with a workers' sit-in Aug. 2 at Egypt's largest metal
plant. Police stormed the plant and a worker was killed.
   There was no comment from the Interior Ministry, which is in
charge of police, but the official Middle East News Agency said
authorities were questioning members of a clandestine organization
arrested early Thursday.
   It said said tracts ``inciting change in the country's social and
political systems'' were found and the organization called itself
the ``Egyptian Communist Workers' Party.'' The agency said there
were 52 members, including three journalists and three lawyers.
   According to the opposition party, the 28 men were arrested hours
before a news conference was to be held at the Bar Association about
the strike at the steel plant at Helwan, south of Cairo.
   ``State security officials have accused them of forming an
underground organization called the Communist Workers' Party,'' the
statement said.
   At Helwan, a worker was shot to death and two policemen and 14
strikers were injured. Security forces arrested more than 600
workers, but said most were released soon afterward, and work
resumed the next day.
   The National Unionist Progressive Party has said about 300
workers are missing and believed still in custody. The workers
struck for better pay and working conditions.
</TEXT>
