<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 1925EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-US-Colombia 1stLd-Writethru a0660 08-24 0943</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Colombia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0660,870</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Evacuations for Now, US Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Desk: INSERTS grafs 10-15 bgng: ``Meanwhile, administration,'' with
Pentagon suggestions on military hardware for Colombia; SUBS 5th graf:
``The embassy,'' to give an on-the-record quote from Wednesday.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Thursday it has no
immediate plans to evacuate U.S. government personnel from Colombia
in the aftermath of bombings by drug traffickers, but acknowledged
``a very concrete threat'' exists against the Bogota government.
   The drug traffickers' declaration of war on the Colombian
government ``certainly heightens the concern about security, both
for the Colombian government and for ourselves,'' State Department
spokesman Richard Boucher said.
   ``It dramatizes, I would say, what we've long known, and that's
that these drug traffickers represent a very concrete threat to the
institutions of the government of Colombia,'' he said.
   However, there are no plans to withdraw any U.S. personnel in
Colombia, and, without such a plan the government would not even
necessarily pay for travel of those U.S. dependents who want to
leave, he said.
   The embassy has ``always been on a high state of readiness,''
State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said Wednesday. ``That
continues.''
   There are some 100 U.S. officials with the embassy in Bogota and
about two dozen Drug Enforcement Administration agents in the
country, according to officials.
   No Americans were hurt in the attacks early Thursday in Medellin
_ home to the world's largest cocaine cartel _ and the embassy in
Bogota ``was not aware of any bombings'' until diplomats heard
reports on Colombian radio, another State Department official said.
   The United States formerly maintained a consulate in Medellin,
but closed it in the early 1980s ``due to the threat,'' a State
Department official said.
   Colombia is a danger post, meaning that U.S. diplomats posted
there receive extra money to compensate for the risk, and minor
dependents are not allowed.
   Meanwhile, administration and military sources reported that the
Joint Chiefs of Staff decided Thursday to draw up a ``laundry list''
of military hardware for President Bush to consider sending to
Colombia in the event that nation requests such material.
   The sources, who spoke on condition they not be identified, said
the list sent to the White House included UH-1 ``Huey'' troop
transport helicopters, ammunition, and radio equipment, the military
sources said.
   ``No personnel is involved,'' one source said, indicating that
the choppers would be flown by Colombian pilots if they should be
sent.
   No precise numbers were disclosed, but the source said the
numbers were ``not extravagant.''
   The administration source said the list was not a formal
recommendation, but instead provided the president with ``a laundry
list of items that the Pentagon could provide if called upon to do
so.''
   The source noted that the president has strictly ruled out the
use of U.S. military troops, which is in line with the Joint Chiefs'
thinking.
   Last weekend, the Colombian government imposed a state of siege
following a string of killings that culminated in the assassination
of Luis Carlos Galan, a leading presidential candidate and an
outspoken foe of drug traffickers.
   The state of siege allows for quick extraditions of alleged drug
traffickers wanted on U.S. charges, extraditions that ended abruptly
in 1987 when the Colombian Supreme Court, under pressure from
traffickers, overturned the extradition agreement. The traffickers
have indicated that extradition is one of their major concerns due
to their fears that they would not be able to escape as they have in
Colombia.
   President Bush, contacted at the summer White House in
Kennebunkport, Maine, said he had ``no real comment'' on the
situation in Colombia.
   ``There will be meetings with the proper Colombian officials in
the not so many hours,'' Bush said as he prepared to meet the
visiting prime minister of Denmark.
   The Justice Department anounced Wednesday an agreement to offer
Colombia $2 million for a judicial protection program, part of the
$5 million authorized by Congress for such a program last year.
Dozens of judges have been killed, and most of the slayings have
been traced to the drug cartels.
   Justice Department spokesman Dan Eramian said plans for the
program had been under discussion since April, and that one reason
the entire $5 million wasn't allocated was to give officials a
chance to determine where the money could best be spent.
   Boucher said an additional $500,000 was being allocated to
purchase security equipment, although he did not specify what kind
of equipment.
   Colombian Justice Minister Monica de Greiff was quoted in
Thursday's Washington Post as saying that the U.S. embassy refused
to allow the Colombian government to use some of the money to buy
armored cars.
   However, a State Department official said the purchase of armored
cars is one of the things being considered for the remaining $2.5
million.
   ``It's in our interests for their judges not to be blown up
getting from home to work and back,'' the official said.
   The Colombian government has arrested some 11,000 people since
the state of siege began, but the only U.S. officials have said they
want to extradite is Eduardo Martinez Romero, an alleged money
launderer for the Medellin cartel who was indicted in March in
Atlanta.
   The embassy has relayed a request for Martinez's arrest, which
enables the Colombians to hold him for 30 days on behalf of the
United States, according to Boucher, and an administration source
said the extradition paperwork was being completed.
   A U.S. government plane has been at the Bogota airport since last
weekend and could be used to transport Martinez to the United States
for trial on the charges filed in Atlanta in March, according to the
source.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
