<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Strike     08-24 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Strike,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Planned Language Law Sparks Strike in Soviet Moldavia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers at more than 90 factories in the eastern
Soviet republic of Moldavia went on strike Thursday to protest a
proposed language law that ethnic Russians fear will discriminate
against them, official media said.
   The Moldavian Supreme Soviet, or legislature, is scheduled to
vote on the bill making Moldavian the republic's official language
on Tuesday.
   The Workers' Alliance of Moldavia, which claims to represent
workers in 192 businesses, met in the republic's capital of Kishinev
and Wednesday voted in favor of a protest strike, the Tass news
agency said.
   More than 50 factories in Kishinev, Bendery, Rybnitysa, Komrat
and other cities in the Soviet republic bordering Romania walked off
the job Thursday, Tass said.
   They joined a work stoppage begun Monday by mostly ethnic Russian
workers in Tiraspol, Moldavia's second-largest city where Russians
are in the majority.
   State Radio Moscow said 40 businesses in Tiraspol have been
closed by the strike.
   The strikers are demanding that the draft language law not be
adopted before widespread public discussion in the republic of 4.2
million people and before the election of a new Supreme Soviet in
the spring.
   They fear making Moldavian the republic's official language will
be a first step toward discrimination against Russians and other
migrants.
   Earlier this month, tens of thousands of ethnic Russian workers
living in Estonia went on strike to protest a law that set the
Soviet Union's first residency requirements for voting and running
for office.
   The Soviet Presidium, the nation's top executive body, ruled the
Estonian law was a violation of the Soviet Constitution.
</TEXT>
