<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 1949EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-TV     08-24 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-TV,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stations Begin Telecasts Using Advanced System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Japanese TV networks on Thursday began regular
broadcasts using a new television system that provides clearer
pictures to special sets but can still be viewed on regular sets.
   The system, called extended-definition television, or EDTV,
produces more detailed pictures with deeper colors and fewer
``ghosts'' on sets equipped with special circuitry.
   EDTV will compete against another new high-quality TV system,
called high-definition television. HDTV provides sharper images but
involves a more radical redesign of TV standards and in some cases
is incompatible with present equipment.
   Nippon Television Network said it will broadcast 5-6 hours of
EDTV programs a day. The TBS network said it will begin with about
three hours a week. Other networks in Japan are expected to begin
EDTV broadcasts this month or in September.
   ``We decided to begin EDTV broadcasting because of our interest
in improving picture quality and because of its better compatibility
with current equipment,'' said a TBS official on condition of
anonymity.
   Many broadcasters see EDTV as a more practical alternative to
HDTV, which requires a greater investment by stations and consumers.
Current HDTV monitors in Japan sell for about $60,000. EDTV sets are
available for about $2,800.
   The TV system in common use in North America and Japan divides
the picture into 525 horizontal lines, though not all the lines
appear on the screen at once. First odd-numbered lines are scanned,
and then one-60th of a second later the even lines appear, producing
30 combined images each second.
   The speed is too fast for the human eye to detect, but it creates
a flicker and fuzziness that is particularly noticeable on large
screens and in scenes with rapid motion.
   EDTV uses special cameras that scan all 525 lines at once. It
transmits a reference signal letting TV sets detect and reduce
ghosts, or double signals reflected from buildings or other objects.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
