<SECOND>AM-PLO-Kaddoumi,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>PLO Official Offers To Meet Israelis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farouk Kaddoumi, the PLO's equivalent of a
foreign minister, was quoted in an interview published Thursday as
offering to negotiate peace with Israel.
   Farouk Kaddoumi also said the current PLO dialogue with the
United States would not lead to a Middle East settlement, according
to the report in Al Qoda (Jerusalem), an Arabic-language weekly
based in London.
   It said the interview was conducted in Tunis, where the Palestine
Liberation Organization has its headquarters.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir of Israel has proposed elections in
the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, where a Palestinian uprising
began more than 20 months ago, to choose representatives who would
negotiate with Israel.
   The PLO insists that elections be held only under international
supervision, after Israeli withdrawal from the territories.
   ``Washington is trying to give Shamir more time to liquidate the
uprising or enforce Shamir's election plan,'' Kaddoumi was quoted as
saying.
   ``It is not possible for Washington to alter its political stance
unless it feels that its interests are in danger and it must respond
to the Palestinian demands.''
   ``Any dialogue with Israeli forces must be held outside the
occupied territories,'' he said. ``There are Israeli occupation
authorities imposing their will on the Palestinian people, and local
leaders in the occupied territories are under various political and
psychological pressures.
   ``This is why talks with Israeli forces must be held outside the
occupied territories and we are ready for such a dialogue.''
   He said of low-level talks with the United States being held in
Tunis: ``We must not have any illusion that the dialogue with the
United States would achieve the aspired results.''
   In December, after PLO chief Yasser Arafat publicly renounced
terrorism and recognized Israel's right to exist, the United States
ended a 13-year ban on dealings with the PLO and the talks began.
