<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-24 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Showers in the Nation's Midsection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered across the middle
Mississippi and lower Ohio valleys Thursday along a stationary front
dividing very warm and humid air from mild and drier air prevailing
in the Northeast.
   High pressure in the upper atmosphere centered over northern
Florida, helping carry moisture into the lower Mississippi Valley,
and showers and thunderstorms blossomed across the region.
   The heaviest rainfall was in southwest Louisiana and southeast
Texas, where nearly an inch of rain fell at Beaumont and Port
Arthur, Texas.
   Showers and thunderstorms moved into eastern Tennessee, northern
Georgia and the western Carolinas, with gusty winds blowing down
trees in Clinton County, S.C.
   Showers and thunderstorms also developed in the high plains of
Colorado and New Mexico.
   Rainshowers were scattered across northern and central Plateau,
with temperatures in the 40s and 50s from western Montana, Idaho and
eastern Washington south into northern Utah and northeast Nevada.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 3 p.m. EDT
included nearly an inch and a half in the Indianapolis area and
nearly an inch at Bristol, Tenn.
   The low temperature in the lower 48 states Thursday morning was
30 degrees at South Lake Tahoe, Nev., and Burney, Calif. At 2 p.m.
EDT the low was 42 degrees at McCall, Idaho, and the high 99 degrees
at Fort Smith, Ariz., and Minot Air Force Base in North Dakota.
   Friday's national forecast called for showers and thunderstorms
scattered from the lower Missouri and middle Mississippi valleys
through the lower Ohio and Tennessee valleys into the southern
Atlantic Coast region.
   Afternoon and evening thundershowers will develop across the
central and eastern Gulf Coast through northern and central Florida.
Thunderstorms are also expected across parts of west Texas.
   Showers will be widespread from the northern Rockies into the
northern Plains, with high temperatures in the 70s or 80s across
much of the nation.
   Highs will be in the 60s over the northern Rockies and much of
Maine; in the 90s from the southern Plains and Texas into the
southeastern quarter of the nation; in the 90s to near 105 degrees
from the desert Southwest into southern Arizona and southern New
Mexico.
</TEXT>
