<FIRST>u a AM-McCartneyTour     08-24 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-McCartney Tour,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>McCartney Announces World Tour</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL STIEG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A graying and glib Paul McCartney formally
announced an international concert tour Thursday that he hoped would
attract both misty-eyed Beatlemaniacs and a new generation of fans.
   ``There was a time when you thought music equals youth. I don't
think that applies anymore,'' said McCartney, 47, joining other
middle-aged rockers on tour this year _ the Who, the Rolling Stones
and former Beatles drummer Ringo Starr.
   Asked if he was touring to avoid being ``left out,'' he replied,
``I suppose there's an element of that ... but it's not my prime
reason for going out.''
   Instead, he credited the endless touring of the Grateful Dead and
its leader, Jerry Garcia, with inspiring his first tour since 1976.
``If Jerry can still do it that good, there's hope for us all,''
McCartney said.
   McCartney also said several nieces and nephews have asked him:
``Please play, because we weren't there the first time around.''
   McCartney let reporters watch the end of his new band's rehearsal
at the Lyceum Theater in Manhattan, then answered questions about
the tour, his band and new record, ``Flowers in the Dirt,'' and the
Beatles.
   Band members include Linda McCartney on keyboards and vocals;
Hamish Stuart, a guitarist and bassist from the Average White Band;
guitarist Robbie McIntosh, formerly of the Pretenders; drummer Chris
Witten and keyboardist-computer programmer Wix.
   McCartney said his show would draw from four distinct phases of
his 33-year career: pre-Beatles rock 'n' roll; Beatles songs;
greatest hits from his years with Wings, and songs from the new
album.
   Among the Beatles tunes will be selections from ``Sgt. Pepper's
Lonely Hearts Club Band,'' their landmark 1967 album.
   ``We never got to do it with the Beatles,'' McCartney said,
noting that the album was done entirely in the studio, after the
group had stopped performing live.
   Also on the proposed set list: ``Hey Jude.''
   ``I'm hoping for a little audience participation on that one _
the na-na-na at the end,'' he said.
   The tour opens with three shows at the Los Angeles Forum Nov.
27-28-29. Other confirmed dates: Chicago, Dec. 3-4-5; Toronto, Dec.
7; Montreal, Dec. 9; New York, Dec. 11-12-14-15.
   Other North American dates will be announced later, but the band
plans to play Boston, Philadelphia, Detroit, Seattle, Dallas and San
Francisco.
   McCartney said the band will return to North America in February
``to cover the cities we missed.''
</TEXT>
