<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 2022EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Grenada     08-24 0356</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grenada,0367</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Suspends Parliament To Avoid No-Confidence Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISTER HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. GEORGE'S, Grenada (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Herbert Blaize's
government suspended Parliament on Thursday amid opposition threats
to bring it down with a no-confidence vote.
   Blaize, 71, has been under intense pressure over what critics
call an increasingly authoritarian style and in January lost
leadership of his party.
   Thursday's announcement means Blaize can govern without any
parliamentary opposition until as late as February, a month before
general elections are due.
   Opposition leader George Brizan accused Blaize of treating
Parliament with ``ridicule and contempt'' during the Caribbean
island's most serious political crisis since the leftist revolution
and subsequent U.S.-led invasion of 1983.
   Brizan was notified by letter that the legislature, which was to
convene Friday after a recess, is being suspended for an indefinite
period.
   Under Grenada's constitution, the governor general of this former
British colony can suspend Parliament at any time for up to six
months.
   Because general elections must be held by March 28, it appears
unlikely a no-confidence vote can be introduced.
   In January, Blaize lost leadership of the governing New National
Party to his popular public works minister, Keith Mitchell, 43.
   The prime minister subsequently fired Mitchell from his Cabinet
and two other Cabinet ministers resigned in protest. Blaize opposes
Mitchell's wish for a broad coalition to include members of the
ousted Marxist government.
   The New National Party now holds nine of the 15 seats in
Parliament and Brizan's National Democratic Congress has the other
six. In a no-confidence vote, Mitchell and the two other former
Cabinet ministers were expected to side with the oppositon, causing
the government to fall.
   ``This confirms my view that the prime minister is not behaving
like the person I knew in 1984 when he won the elections,'' Mitchell
said Thursday. ``He now seems to put the will of the people last and
his personal position and pique first.''
   Blaize became prime minister on Dec. 3, 1984, 14 months after
U.S. troops and a small Caribbean force invaded the island to topple
a Marxist junta that seized power in a bloody coup.
</TEXT>
