<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 2318EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-GreyhoundSuit     08-24 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greyhound Suit,0601</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Says Driver Made Her Sit At Back Of Bus Because She's Black</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) _ A woman and her two children have
filed a lawsuit claiming that a Greyhound bus driver forced them to
sit at the back of his bus on a transcontinental trip because they
are black.
   Vickie H. Hairston of Winston-Salem sued Greyhound Lines Inc.
last week in Forsyth Superior Court on behalf of herself and her
children, Jemithra and Joy Hairston.
   The lawsuit alleges that Greyhound officials knew about what it
calls the ``racial feelings'' of the driver and allowed him to
continue working.
   The lawsuit asked for more than $30,000 in compensatory and
punitive damages stemming from the 1986 incident.
   ``These kinds of cases are rare anymore,'' said Romallus O.
Murphy, an attorney from Greensboro who is representing Mrs.
Hairston with the help of the NAACP. ``All of the case law is from
the early 1970s and 1960s.''
   It has been 34 years since Rosa Parks helped ignite the
civil-rights movement by refusing to move to the back of a city bus
in Montgomery, Ala.
   The lawsuit says that Mrs. Hairston and her two children boarded
a Greyhound bus in Winston-Salem on Aug. 15, 1986, bound for
Portland, Ore. At the time, Jemithra was 11 years old and Joy was 4.
   While they were traveling from Cheyenne, Wyo., to Rawlins, Wyo.,
the lawsuit says, the bus driver, identified as Joe Kant, began
harassing Mrs. Hairston and her children. It says that the only
reason for the harassment was their race.
   At Rawlins, the lawsuit says, Kant told them that they would have
to sit at the back of the bus. When they refused, they ``were
informed that if they did not move to the rear of the bus, they must
seek other transportation,'' the lawsuit says.
   The lawsuit said that ``despite the support (for the Hairstons)
of white passengers and a police officer from the Rawlins police
force, the driver insisted ... (and that) in great fear for their
health and safety (they) moved to the rear of the bus as demanded.''
   Many passengers on the bus have written to Mrs. Hairston and
volunteered to testify for her if she took legal action, Murphy
said. She did not file a lawsuit until now because she has little
money and was uncertain about how to proceed, he said.
   The lawsuit says that the incident caused Mrs. Hairston great
emotional strain and even caused an attack of skin lesions because
she suffers from lupus, a skin disease.
   The lawsuit does not name Kant as a defendant. It demands at
least $10,000 from Greyhound for breach of contract, at least
$10,000 for negligence, and at least $10,000 for intentionally
inflicting emotional distress on the Hairstons.
   There is some confusion, however, over who is being sued, because
the Greyhound bus-lines divisions was split off from the parent
company and sold in March 1987. The lawsuit says that it is suing
Greyhound Lines Inc., a corporation in Phoenix, Ariz.
   The company now in Phoenix is called The Greyhound Corporation.
Brad Parker, a spokesman for that company, said officials there know
nothing about the lawsuit.
   Greyhound Lines Inc. of Dallas, Texas, now owns the bus
operations. Elizabeth Hale, a spokesman for that company, said the
company would not be legally responsible for any incident that
occurred before it bought the bus service.
   Murphy said that he filed the lawsuit against the company that
sold the tickets to Mrs. Hairston.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
