<SECOND>AM-Panama-US,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panamanian Officials Say U.S. Defeated At Regional Meeting</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panamanian leaders Thursday praised
the hands-off decision by the Organization of American States, which
called on Panamanians to solve their own iternal problems.
   The OAS action was a blow to the United States, which since May
has campaigned for regional action to oust Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega, commander of the Panamanian Defense Forces and the
country's most powerful figure.
   The United States in February 1988 indicted Noriega on
drug-related charges.
   Leaders of Panama's political opposition meanwhile issued a
statement saying they will continue their struggle for Noriega to
step down.
   ``His removal,'' the statement said, ``is a must for the solution
of the Panamanian conflict.''
   The government annulled May presidential elections, which
international observers say the opposition won 3-1. The current
administration's term is up on Sept. 1 and the opposition wants to
take office.
   ``The OAS decision shows respect for the right of a country's
self-determination. The OAS has left Panamanians alone to solve
their own problems,'' Acting President Manuel Solis Palma said
Thursday.
   Solis made his remarks as he and Noriega visited the a rural fair
at the Rio Hato Military Base, about 80 miles southwest of the
capital.
   Noriega _ dressed in a white shirt with pockets embroidered with
Panamanian Indian symbols _ shook hands with well-wishers and waved
to the crowds, but made no comment when questioned by reporters.
   Defense Forces spokesman Maj. Edgardo Lopez Grimaldo said the OAS
refusal to condemn Panama was ``a victory for Panama and a
humiliation for the United States.''
   The OAS exhortation for an internal solution to the country's
conflicts followed several visits to Panama by a special mission
that met with opposition and government leaders in an attempt to
seek a negotiated settlement.
   Noriega said Tuesday the political opposition committed a
``historical error'' when it turned down a government offer earlier
this month to govern jointly after Sept. 1.
   Washington indicated Thursday it was considering new sanctions
against Panama but officials did not say what they might be.
   Since February 1988, the United States has imposed economic and
other barriers on Panama, including payment on Panama Canal tolls.
   The measures have contributed to substantial economic decline in
Panama.
</TEXT>
