<HEAD>Colorado Woman Arrested For Trespassing at Talk Show Host't Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW CANAAN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 37-year-old woman, who has claimed to
be NBC-TV talk show host David Letterman's wife and was ordered to
stay away from him, was arrested Thursday for trespassing at his New
Canaan home, police said.
   Margaret Ray of Paonia, Colo., was arrested at the New Canaan
railroad station after police received a report that she was walking
on the grounds of Letterman's home, New Canaan police Sgt. Frank
Basso said.
   Ray was charged with first-degree criminal trespass and was being
held at the New Canaan police station on $10,000 bond pending
arraignment in Norwalk Superior Court Friday, Basso said.
   Basso declined to comment on whether Letterman was at home at the
time of the alleged incident.
   Ray pleaded guilty May 30 to using Letterman's car without his
permission and to two counts of first-degree criminal trespass.
   A Superior Court judge then ordered Ray released from a state
mental hospital. Ray had been confined at Fairfield Hills Hospital
in Newtown since a judge found her incompetent to stand trial in
April.
   Ray was sentenced to a one-year suspended sentence and three
years' probation.
   As a condition of probation, Ray was ordered to stay away from
Letterman and continue to undergo psychiatric treatement.
   She had been charged with two counts of third-degree burglary,
two counts of sixth-degree larceny, two counts of first-degree
criminal trespass, possession of marijuana and possession of drug
paraphernalia in connection with break-ins at Letterman's home on
Feb 24 and Feb. 28.
   In June 1988, Ray was arrested when she tried to pass herself off
as Letterman's wife after she was stopped near the Lincoln Tunnel in
New York City driving Letterman's 1988 Porsche.
