<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 2114EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Haiti     08-24 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Haiti,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Elections In Haiti Before Next Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL NORTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACMEL, Haiti (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of the independent Electoral
Council says a shortage of money means no elections can be held in
Haiti before next year.
   Council President Louis Antoine Auguste said the government has
not allocated a budget to the nine-member board, which was appointed
in April by institutions such as the Roman Catholic Church, labor
unions and human rights groups.
   ``For budgetary reasons, elections before the end of December are
not feasible,'' Auguste told 150 people meeting Tuesday at the city
hall in Jacmel, a town on the southern coast of this Caribbean
nation of 6 million.
   The council has toured rural Haiti since July and expects to fix
an election schedule by next week.
   Council members are asking voters whether they think national and
local elections should be staggered or held simultaneously and
whether 1 million Haitians living abroad should be allowed to
participate.
   ``We are trying to set an example of democratic behavior,'' said
the council's general secretary, Jean-Gerard Pierre.
   ``The citizens of certain remote areas were surprised that we
felt obligated to take account of their point of view. Haitians are
not used to being consulted by authorities,'' he said.
   Jacmel residents preferred elections in two stages, first
national and then local, begining early next year. They strongly
favored the participation of Haitians living abroad.
   Former ruler Lt. Gen. Henri Namphy dissolved the first electoral
council in November 1987, hours after gunmen protected by soldiers
massacred at least 34 voters at polling stations and aborted what
would have been Haiti's first free general elections since
independence in 1804.
   Namphy accused the council of being manipulated by ``foreign
powers.'' The United States, France and Canada contributed most of
its budget.
   He was ousted in a September 1988 coup that brought Lt. Gen.
Prosper Avril to power. Namphy had led a provisional government
after dictator Jean-Claude Duvalier fled to exile in France in 1986.
</TEXT>
