<DOCNO> AP890824-0180 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 2125EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia-Crackdown     08-24 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia-Crackdown,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colombia Squeezes Drug Traffickers With New Decrees</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Colombia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAVIER BAENA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Virgilio Barco fired back in
the war on drug traffickers Thursday with a salvo of decrees, one
obliging them to emerge from hiding to regain an estimated $200
million in confiscated property.
   Using emergency powers under a 4-year-old state of siege, he
passed a decree requiring owners to personally make claims for
restitution, barring them from using the lawyers, agents and
middlemen routinely employed by drug barons.
   It also gave them just 10 days from the time of seizure to make
such claims. In the event they do not, the state becomes the owner
of the confiscated property, which would be distributed as follows:
   _Ranches, livestock and other rural property and goods go to the
National Agrarian Fund for distribution among landless peasants.
   _Urban property and goods go to the Family Welfare Institute to
help needy children and mothers.
   _Cash, automobiles and trucks go to the judicial fund to be used
in improving working conditions for judges.
   _Aircraft and sea vessels go to the Defense Ministry and to the
air force's commercial transport business.
   _Arms go to the Defense Ministry and security police.
   Another decree calls for an inventory of all private airstrips
nationwide, and the destruction of those whose legitimate use cannot
be proven.
   Yet another is designed to ensure anonymity for Supreme Court
magistrates who review these and other decrees issued in an
unprecedented anti-narcotics offensive.
   The crackdown was prompted by the assassinations of a popular
presidential candidate, a police colonel and a superior court
magistrate last week.
   The offensive has included raids and seizures at more than 700
estates, businesses and other properties owned by or linked to
Colombia's powerful cocaine cartels. Authorities estimate that $200
million in property, including mansions, airplanes, cars and other
goods, have been impounded.
   On Thursday, an infuriated Medellin cocaine cartel declared
``total and absolute war'' on the government, the political
establishment and industries in what was viewed as an obvious bid to
pressure the government into easing up.
   Drug gangs bombed two political party offices on Thursday and
burned the homes of two politicians in Medellin.
</TEXT>
