<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 2320EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-NewtonKilled 1stLd-Writethru a0737 08-24 0727</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Newton Killed, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0737,0743</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Piece Together Newton's Final Hours</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to clarify that witness was only one to give details
of Newton's final moments; SUBS 5th graf, `Investigators still...,' to
fix typo.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER McNULTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Black Panther Huey Newton ended his
rebellious life with an act of defiance, telling the gunman who was
to kill him, ``Man, I ain't getting in your car,'' a witness said.
   Police investigators continued Thursday to piece together
Newton's final hours amid speculation that his history of alcohol
and drug abuse may have contributed to his death.
   The San Francisco Examiner reported that Newton was murdered
after an encounter in drug-torn west Oakland with three ex-convicts,
who were later arrested and linked to the killing. But Oakland
police Lt. Mike Sims denied the report.
   Although family members refused to discuss Newton's drug use, a
close friend said the former Black Panther had a history of
substance abuse and entered a hospital treatment program in 1984.
   Investigators still have not identified a suspect or motive in
Tuesday's pre-dawn shooting, but they have received several accounts
from people who saw Newton in the crime-ridden neighborhood several
hours before he was slain.
   ``We've talked to people who were with him so we have a general
idea of his activities before he was killed,'' Sims said.
   Police said Newton shared drinks with a friend and left a short
time before his body was discovered at 5:30 a.m., according to
reports in Thursday editions of The (Oakland) Tribune newspaper.
   Michelle Johnson, who lives across the street from where Newton
was shot on Seventh Street, said she was awakened by loud voices on
the street moments before she heard the gunfire that killed Newton,
the San Francisco Chronicle reported.
   Johnson said she heard a brief argument and a man order someone,
apparently Newton, into a car.
   ``And the last thing Huey said was, `Man, I ain't getting in your
car,''' she said. ``It was like he was telling them, `Do what you're
going to do right here.'''
   At least three shots rang out and when Johnson peered out her
window, she saw Newton slumped on the sidewalk.
   Sims confirmed that police have interviewed Johnson but would not
reveal the contents of the discussion.
   Newton, 47, died in the same predominantly black west Oakland
neighborhood where he grew up and began organizing the Panthers in
1966. The area is now known for open dealing of crack cocaine and
frequent violent clashes between gang members.
   The neighborhood's reputation has fueled speculation that Newton
may have been there because of a drug problem, but police remained
silent on a possible motive for the slaying. Family members have
declined to comment on Newton's alleged drug use.
   Fred Hiestand, a close friend for 18 years and one of Newton'
attorneys, said the militant leader suffered from alcohol and drug
abuse but believed Newton had been clean for six months.
   ``That doesn't mean he couldn't have fallen off the wagon,'' said
Hiestand, who last spoke with Newton on Friday.
   Newton struggled to control his substance abuse problems, said
Hiestand. In 1984, Newton entered a treatment program at Alta Bates
Hospital in Berkeley, and fought recently to overcome his problems
on his own, Hiestand said.
   Earlier this year, Newton served time in San Quentin Prison for a
parole violation for possessing cocaine and drug paraphernalia.
   Preliminary results of an autopsy have not been released, and
findings of drug and alcohol tests are not yet available, Sims said.
   Police are also investigating a published account of Newton's
last hours by a woman who called herself Pat Wright, which is not
her true name, said Sims, who refused to reveal her identity.
   The woman, who lives two blocks from the shooting scene and
described herself as Newton's former girlfriend, said Newton visited
her late Monday night and stayed until 1 a.m. on the morning he died.
   ``He said he was fighting a battle, and he kept saying that two
or three times,'' she said. ``I told him I understood, but I could
tell something was wrong. He knew something was about to happen.''
   Since the shooting, the sidewalk where Newton lay mortally
wounded has become something of a shrine, with flowers, candles and
a steady stream of mourners embellishing the site.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
