<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 0030EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SpaceReef     08-24 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Space Reef,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sea Explosion Creates Artificial Reef of Space Junk</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: `Humminbird' in 11th graf is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ugly brown barge carrying 120 tons
of obsolete rocket-launching structures exploded Wednesday in flames
and smoke in the Atlantic Ocean, then sank to become an artificial
reef.
   ``She lived by fire and she died by fire,'' salvage specialist
Ryan Moore said after three pieces of space material and the old oil
barge welded into a single structure were sunk 18 miles east of the
Cape Canaveral space complex.
   Army ordnance experts used 40 pounds of plastic explosives to
blow out the barge's bottom, sending it to the ocean floor 120 feet
below.
   The reef, which will provide an environment for grouper, snapper
and other sea life, was the culmination of a nearly two-year effort
by federal agencies, industry, environmental groups, the military
and individuals.
   It consists of:
   _ A rust-red, 60-ton umbilical tower off Launch Pad 36A, which
helped launch more than 75 space flights, including the
Atlas-Centaur series that boosted the Surveyor probe to the moon.
   _ A 40-ton missile access stand from Launch Pad 29, which
supported test launches of Polaris and Poseidon missiles.
   _ A 10-ton shuttle-Centaur support stand from Launch Pad 36A.
   _ The 10-ton, 180-foot-long oil barge built in the 1940s.
   ``Its great to see some of the materials once used to launch
America into space put to good use,'' said Dave Murphree of the
Florida Sport Fishing Association, which helped coordinate the
project.
   Much of the estimated $40,000 cost was paid for by the
FishAmerica Foundation, a private fishery conservation group, and
Humminbird Depth Sounders of Eufaula, Ala., which makes sonar and
electronic fish finders.
   The barge was towed out by a barge. In calm seas, four ordnance
experts set the explosives. Around 1:30 p.m., they set a 10-minute
timer, climbed aboard a waiting speedboat and sped away from the
barge before the charge went off.
   Orange and yellow flames enveloped the barge and its cargo _
about 35 feet high _ before a small, gray-and-white mushroom cloud
spiraled up into bright, nearly cloudless skies.
   As a boatload of reporters and photographers watched from a half
mile away, the structure quickly sank. It was gone within two
minutes.
   ``We intend to support many more of these artificial reefs with
old space material,'' said Humminbird spokesman Rodney Huey. ``Maybe
our next one will have stuff that's already been in space.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
