<FIRST>u a AM-DrugAgentSlain     08-24 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Agent Slain,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Mexican President's Kin Appears Before Grand Jury</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The brother-in-law of former Mexican President
Luis Echeverria appeared Thursday before a federal grand jury
investigating the 1985 murder of U.S. drug agent Enrique Camarena.
   Ruben Zuno-Arce, 59, a prominent Mexican businessman suspected of
involvement in drug trafficking, was brought to the panel's hearing
room after being granted immunity from prosecution for anything he
may disclose while testifying secretly.
   Zuno-Arce was arrested Aug. 9 in San Antonio by U.S. immigration
agents as he tried to cross into Mexico. An inspector recognized
Zuno-Arce as one of those on a list of suspected drug traffickers,
authorities said.
   His three lawyers were not permitted to be present at the secret
proceeding but were allowed to wait in a corridor. The witness had
the right to leave the hearing room and consult with them at any
time.
   Because of the secrecy of grand jury proceedings, it was not
known whether Zuno-Arce cooperated in testifying. He was granted
``use immunity'' after he said he would invoke Fifth Amendment
protection against self-incrimination and refuse to testify.
   Use immunity means that he cannot be prosecuted on the basis of
anything he says in the closed hearing.
   In an unusual procedure, Zuno-Arce has been held without bail
since he was arrested in San Antonio, Tex. on Aug. 9. His attorneys
argued that he should be freed because he is not charged with any
crime. But in a hearing last Friday, U.S. District Judge Edward
Rafeedie ruled that Zuno-Arce is a flight risk and that he may have
significant information about the Camarena case.
   He urged prosecutors to quickly obtain a grant of immunity for
Zuno-Arce, have him appear before a grand jury and then release him
from custody.
   It was unclear how soon after his appearance Thursday the witness
could be released. The 1985 kidnapping and torture murder of
Camarena and his pilot, Alfredo Zavala-Avelar, became an
international incident. The Drug Enforcement Administration has
vowed to bring in every person involved in the murders.
   Several members of the Mexican federal police force were linked
to the killings and one, Raul Lopez Alvarez, was convicted last year
along with two drug traffickers.
   The government wants Zuno-Arce to testify in the trial of a
recently charged defendant, Juan Jose Bernabe-Ramirez, a former
member of the Jalisco State Judicial Police.
   They have linked Zuno-Arce to the sale of a home in Guadalajara
which was subsequently bought by Mexican drug lord Rafael
Caro-Quintero. Authorities believe Camarena was murdered at that
house.
   Caro-Quintero, who is accused of orchestrating the murders, is in
custody awaiting trial in Mexico City. Seven more men are charged
with murder and conspiracy in the case.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
