<FIRST>u i AM-Britain-Argentina     08-24 0266</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Argentina,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Menem's Brother To Visit London</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Eduardo Menem, provisional leader of the
Argentine Senate and brother of President Carlos Menem, will visit
London next month to attend an international lawmakers conference,
the Foreign Office said Thursday.
   The visit is the latest step in improving relations between
Britain and Argentina, which severed diplomatic relations during the
1982 Falklands War.
   The Foreign Office said in a statement that Sen. Menem will head
a delegation of Argentine parliamentarians to the
Inter-Parliamentary Union conference, which starts Sept. 4.
   The Inter-Parliamentary Union is a worldwide organization of
lawmakers who meet periodically to study international problems.
About 2,000 delegates from around the world are scheduled to take
part in the conference.
   Sen. Menem is expected to attend the opening ceremony and a
British government reception, the British domestic news agency Press
Association reported.
   Representatives of the two governments agreed during talks last
week in New York to meet in Madrid, Spain on Oct. 17-18 to discuss
normalizing relations.
   President Menem, who took office on July 8, dropped the previous
government's insistence that Argentina's sovereignty claim must be
the first issue considered, opening the way for normalization talks.
   Argentina invaded and occupied the Falklands, 325 miles off its
southeast coast, in April 1982 but Britain sent a task force and
recaptured the islands in a 74-day war that claimed nearly 1,000
lives.
   Argentina claims the Falklands, which it calls the Malvinas, as
an inheritance from days of Spanish colonial rule and says the
British, who have ruled them as a colony since 1833, stole the
islands.
</TEXT>
