<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Prisoners,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nicaragua Releases More Jailed Peasants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NUEVA GUINEA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega announced
Thursday the release of 179 peasants imprisoned after accusations of
aiding the rebels.
   In a speech before 10,000 peasants in this town, 180 miles
southeast of the capital city of Managua, Ortega said, ``They
shouldn't feel defeated, because the defeat was for Yankee
imperialism.''
   The Sandinista government recently made an agreement with a
Nicaraguan agricultural organization to free 1,200 peasants jailed
for alleged complicity with the rebels, known as Contras.
   The U.S.-backed rebels are to disband under an agreement Ortega
and four other Central American presidents signed this month in
Honduras. In return, Nicaragua has promised free and fair elections.
   About 11,000 rebels and 12,000 dependents are in camps in
Honduras as a temporary cease-fire remains in effect. The government
estimates that 2,500 more are in Nicaragua.
   Nicaragua has offered an amnesty for all Contras who lay down
their weapons and return home.
   Ortega said, ``We must change from the gun to the plow'' to
achieve national unity.
   As for Contras who refuse to abide by the peace plan, Ortega
said, ``We will look for them like a cat looks for a rat.''
   The president said that in recent days, the government has freed
239 peasants from prison.
