<FIRST>s a BC-UndergroundNewYork Adv27   08-24 0971</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Underground New York, Adv 27,0996</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Aug. 27, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Under the Big Apple: `There's an Entire World'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Under the Manhattan skyline, below Times Square,
directly south of the World Trade Center, lies a world of which most
New Yorkers remain blissfully unaware _ until disaster strikes.
   Last weekend's Gramercy Park steam pipe blast that killed three
people focused attention on the world beneath Manhattan, where
rivers run through ancient pipes, kilowatts crackle across a vast
net of lines and the homeless find refuge from the winter freeze.
   ``It's hard to determine what happened. Nobody really knows what
goes on under there,'' said Tina Casey, spokeswoman for the city
Department of Environmental Protection, as officials searched for a
cause in the fatal explosion.
   Consider what's down there and you can see why she's right.
   On any given day, more people ride beneath Manhattan than reside
atop it; 3 million people ride the subway, 108,000 travel under the
East River on the Long Island Rail Road, 105,000 use the PATH trains
beneath the Hudson River, 95,000 take the train tunnels of
Metro-North.
   Most of them never know they share the space with 11,209,507
miles of telephone wire; 19,000 miles of electric cable; 6,800 miles
of gas pipes; 6,000 miles of water mains; 106 miles of steam pipe,
and 100 miles of cable TV wiring _ all packed into the island's 23
square miles.
   Manhattan runs over, under and alongside 214.6 miles of subway
tunnels. Thousands of TA workers spend their days, and nights,
underground keeping the system running; the LIRR, Metro-North,
Amtrak, New Jersey Transit and the PATH systems all face similar
tasks on a smaller scale.
   ``It really is astounding. If you ever took a tour, there's
tunnels, walkways... A small train used to deliver Gloria
Vanderbilt's luggage beneath the Waldorf-Astoria,'' said Dan
Brucker, spokesman for Metro-North railroad, which operates on 48
acres under Grand Central Station.
   ``It's unbelievable. There's literally an entire world going
around down there.''
   A world with an assortment of oddities, including:
   _Two multi-million dollar subway tunnels that have never seen a
single train or commuter, both beneath Second Avenue.
   _A half-dozen abandoned train stations, one of them outside City
Hall, dating back to 1904.
   _A wine cellar-turned-holding pen for suspected criminals beneath
Grand Central.
   _A data management company, Datacom, operating 10 stories beneath
the World Trade Center, sharing space with 54,000 tons of
refrigeration units and six 1,000-kilowatt emergency generators.
   As long as everything works, nobody notices. But there are
problems: water main breaks (604 in the year ending June 30), subway
derailments (nine this year, down from a high of 21 in 1981),
blackouts (last biggie: 1977).
   The likelihood of such events is a constant worry, in part due to
the age of the unseen city. Half the water system, made mostly of
cast iron, was installed near the turn of the century; some
telephone wires date to the Roaring '20s; the oldest gas and
electric lines were put in during World War II.
   And each affects whatever's nearby. This down-under domino effect
crippled a 20-block section of the garment district in the summer of
1983, when a 12-inch water main burst beneath Herald Square, spewing
water into a power substation and igniting an underground inferno.
   The area, including Macy's and Gimbel's, was blacked out for
three days. The potential for disaster is worse; the largest water
mains in service measure 72 inches across.
   Last year, a main laid in 1898 ruptured, flooding Columbus Circle
near Central Park and knocking out train service for 200,000
commuters. This year, several thousand commuters were trapped
underground when an emergency cord was yanked on a subway and trains
backed up for hours.
   For some New Yorkers, the labyrinth of twisting tunnels provides
a temporary home. Beneath Grand Central, where some of the city's
thousands of homeless people seek relief from the elements, are 56
miles of steam pipes and 34 miles of tunnel running three levels
deep.
   Metro-North police patrol the station's underbelly but rarely
find such people, said Brucker.
   ``The only thing you find down there in great numbers,'' he said,
``is rats.''
   Not exactly. There's gold under the streets: in five years, the
city has collected $13.2 million in tax assessments on underground
vaults once used to store coal in Manhattan and Brooklyn. The Swiss
Bank Corp. keeps billions in bullion in its vaults in lower
Manhattan.
   The city runs deepest where it stands tallest: beneath the
110-story twin towers of the World Trade Center. Down there,
restaurants, including the elegant Windows on the World, prepare
food; the Port Authority police take target practice, all 1,452 of
them each year, and trucks make deliveries via the old PATH train
tunnels.
   ``Welcome to the catacombs,'' said a smiling Carl Durr, who's
spent 11 years working beneath the buildings, baking cakes and rolls
for unknowing diners dozens of stories above.
   Durr says he doesn't mind spending each working day underground,
and he's not alone in his feelings.
   ``They wanted me on the 106th floor. I told them I wouldn't go,''
said Mike Linz, who oversees the Inhilco Inc. food operation. ``The
only thing I do different down here is call my wife before I leave
and find out what the weather's like.''
   As constant as the climate-controlled WTC work space are the
rumors of alligators scrambling through Manhattan's 6,000-plus miles
of sewer pipes. Persistent tales of reptiles roaming the sewers even
gave rise to a movie, ``Alligator!,'' released several years ago.
   ``People are always talking about alligators in the sewer
system,'' sighed George Watford of the ASPCA, which rescues about a
half-dozen dogs and cats from beneath the city each year. ``We don't
see anything like that.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 27</NOTE>
