<FIRST>s a BC-JailedCitizen Adv27   08-24 1008</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Jailed Citizen, Adv 27,1030</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Aug. 27, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Terrorist or Victim? 2 Years in Prison While His Future Debated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mahmoud El-Abed Ahmad is an American citizen; he
is charged with no crimes in this country.
   But for more than two years, he has languished in a Manhattan
jail as governments and lawyers argue whether he can get a fair
trial in Jerusalem, where he is considered a ``dangerously violent''
member of the brutal Abu Nidal terror network.
   Israeli and American authorities believe Ahmad was a prime
participant in a 1986 attack on a bus outside Tel Aviv that killed
the driver and injured three Jewish settlers.
   But Ahmad's lawyer, former U.S. Attorney General Ramsey Clark,
insists his client is an innocent man, illegally kidnapped from
South America by the FBI. Clark says an Israeli Shin Beth security
squad tortured two of Ahmad's cousins until they implicated him in
the bus attack.
   ``Of all the cruel and unusual punishment you could be subjected
to, perhaps the worst is to be convicted of a crime you didn't
commit,'' says Clark.
   ``If the only evidence they have is a confession that is
inherently unreliable, taken by torture of another person that
cannot be objectively examined, there's no justice, search for trial
or truth,'' he argues.
   The governments of Israel and the United States, which initially
lost the right to extradite Ahmad but regained it on appeal only to
have it challenged again, insist they have indisputable evidence
linking the 36-year-old man to the attack.
   Over 28 months, a parade of legal experts and personalities has
traveled to the federal courthouse in downtown Brooklyn to give
their opinions why Ahmad should or shouldn't be forced back to
Israel.
   Alan Dershowitz, the Harvard law professor and legal writer,
appeared for prosecutors and argued the fairness of Israel's courts.
But the noted Israeli civil-rights lawyer and anti-Zionist Leah
Tsemel says physical and emotional torture are commonly used in
Israel to force prisoners to say what the authorities want to hear.
   U.S. District Judge Jack B. Weinstein is considering a writ of
habeas corpus filed by Clark and a decision could come next month. A
habeas writ puts the burden of proof on the federal authorities to
justify Ahmad's continued detention.
   Ms. Tsemel, born in Jerusalem several years before the nation of
Israel was founded, represents hundreds of Palestinians and other
Arabs whose rights are allegedly routinely trampled by Israeli
security forces trying to maintain control of the Occupied
Territories, seized in 1967.
   ``There is a stage where it's mistreatment, and then it becomes
torture,'' she says of interrogation by the Israeli security force
Shin Beth. ``I don't think all the security services men are
sadists. I think they have a target _ they want a confession.''
   Should Weinstein decide for the government, he could well
sentence Ahmad to such treatment while condemning him to prisons
that are ``considered among the worst in the world,'' Ms. Tsemel
told the judge.
   Shin Beth does have a nasty reputation, Dershowitz concedes, but
he asserts his studies of the Israeli legal system have found the
perception to be largely hype designed to intimidate recalcitrant
Palestinian suspects.
   Israeli interrogators ``rely very heavily on the fear that things
are going to be a lot worse than they are at the interview,'' he
says. ``Both sides have reason for wanting it to be believed that
interrogated subjects are tortured.''
   The state attorney for Israel, Dorit Beinish, insists Ahmad _
charged with murder, attempted murder, attempted arson and other
crimes _ will be treated fairly, tried in civil court by a
three-judge panel and will not be held under the harsh conditions
common in the jails of the Occupied Territories.
   Ahmad, whom Israeli authorities sometime refer to as Mahmoud Abed
Atta, is charged with taking part in an April 12, 1986, attack in
which three men _ allegedly Ahmad and his two cousins _ hurled
Molotov cocktails and then opened fire with machine guns on a bus
carrying Jewish settlers in the Occupied West Bank.
   Ahmad was born in the West Bank town of Ramala and became a U.S.
citizen seven years ago. His last job was working at his brother's
filling station in Puerto Rico. According to travel documents, he
was visiting his family near Ramala at the time of the attack, but
he denies involvement.
   A month later, when his visa expired, Ahmad left Israel and
traveled to Europe and then New York in an unsuccessful effort to
get a visa extension so he could return to Ramala, where his wife
and children were living, Clark said in an interview.
   Ahmad then went to Venezuela. For the next several months, as
Israeli authorities mounted an international search for him, Ahmad
made frequent trips to Spain, Cyprus, Colombia and Mexico to address
Palestinian gatherings.
   He was arrested entering Caracas on April 27, 1987, but because
Venezula has no extradition treaty with Israel he was handed over _
illegally, Clark asserts _ to the FBI. Agents hustled him onto a
flight to New York, and U.S. authorities arrested him once he was
within American jurisdiction. Since then he has been held without
bail at the Metropolitan Correctional Center in Manhattan.
   Ahmad was likely involved in the attack, a federal magistrate and
a federal judge in Brooklyn agree; but they are at odds over what
should be done with him.
   In June 1988, Magistrate John L. Caden ruled the attack on the
bus a ``political objective'' and thus outside the jurisdiction of
the U.S.-Israel extradition treaty. He also said the way the FBI
nabbed Ahmad and put him in an American jail was unconstitutional.
   U.S. District Judge Edward R. Korman later reversed Caden in a
sharply worded ruling saying the magistrate applied ``erroneous
legal standards'' and ``his findings of fact are plainly erroneous.''
   Korman's ruling that Ahmad could be returned to Israel was
immediately challenged and is under review by Weinstein.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 27</NOTE>
