<FIRST>a a BC-EXP--Briefs Adv28   08-24 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-EXP--Briefs, Adv 28,0484</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv28</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, Aug. 28, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>UK Sets Up National Pilot Program to Train Family Doctors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Medical students at the University of
Kentucky will combine the fourth year of school with the first year
of residency under a pilot program aimed at producing more family
practitioners for the state.
   ``We need them badly,'' said Dr. Nicholas J. Pisacano, executive
director of the American Board of Family Practice, which approved
the program that cuts training from seven years to six. ``Several
schools and some of the top medical educators in the country are
watching it carefully.
   ``The program has the portent of revolutionizing medical
education in the United States. If not, we'll document its failure.''
   Three UK College of Medicine students entered the program July 1.
``They will be monitored continuously all year to see if they met
the criteria and standards,'' said Pisacano. ``We won't certify any
second-class people.''
   According to a study of students graduating from the UK and
University of Louisville medical schools from 1976-79, 75 percent of
the Kentucky graduates that stayed in the state for post-graduate
training now practice in the state.
   ``Ideally, those in the program will stay. It is highly likely
that they will,'' said Dr. Alan K. David, chairman of UK's Family
Practice Department.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Increased Sightings of Young Dolphins Encouraging Sign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEAUFORT, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Increased sightings of dolphin calves in
the past three months is encouraging, but recovery from two years of
poisoning that killed hundreds of dolphins will be a slow process,
researchers say.
   ``Seeing more babies is a good sign, but these calves have to
grow up,'' said marine scientist Keith Rittmaster. Calves accounted
for almost 16 percent of the bottlenose dolphins seen along the
North Carolina coast, compared with 7.3 percent before the 1987-1988
``die-off'' whose cause is still debated.
   ``I think it's higher than has been recorded anywhere for the
bottlenose dolphins. I suspect the whole population is trying to
bounce back,'' he said.
   Because there is little data, it is impossible to say if dolphin
birth rates have increased elsewhere along the East Coast, said
Gerald P. Scott, of the National Marine Fisheries Service in Miami.
In fact, Scott predicted that dolphin births would drop over the
next few years because of the die-off.
   The dolphins found dead in 1987 and 1988 were of all age groups,
but a larger percentage of them were sexually immature _ 3 to 6
years old _ and their deaths could cost much of the next generation,
he said.
   About 750 dolphins washed ashore along the East Coast during that
time. The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration blamed the
deaths on a toxin from red tide algae. Some scientists and
conservationists blame pollution.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Aug. 28</NOTE>
</DOC>
