<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 0233EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-KodakReorganization Bjt   08-24 0613</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kodak Reorganization, Bjt,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kodak Announces Reorganization That Will Eliminate 4,500 Jobs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A restructuring plan announced by Eastman
Kodak Co. to bring in up to $1 billion in extra cash next year
probably won't involve the sale of major divisions, analysts say.
   Kodak officials said Wednesday that disappointing second-quarter
earnings prompted the reorganization, under which it will eliminate
4,500 jobs worldwide this year, or about 3 percent of its work
force, and sell or consolidate certain operations.
   The company, which employs 145,000 people worldwide, including
47,000 at its Rochester headquarters, previously announced plans to
cut 1,000 jobs this year. That figure is included in the new
cutbacks.
   Robert Welk, a Rochester-based economics consultant, said paring
the payroll is wise because Kodak has too many employees compared
with its competitors.
   ``They're addressing what has to be done,'' he said. ``It
definitely is going to be a different company.''
   ``It's not a massive restructuring,'' said Alex Henderson, an
analyst for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. ``It's a major
belt-tightening, very much needed by Kodak.''
   Company spokesman Paul Allen could not provide specifics on where
the jobs would be eliminated.
   The reductions will be targeted at divisions with combined sales
of $1.25 billion, or about 7 percent of Kodak's overall $17 billion
in sales last year, officials said. Kodak said it would sell, close
or reorganize those businesses to reduce operating costs.
   The units most likely to be affected are smaller ones the company
started or bought in the 1980s, analysts said.
   Some have speculated its Information Systems operation, which
includes copiers and microfilm and graphics equipment, would be
targeted. That segment lost $144 million in the second quarter.
   David Nelson, an analyst for Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., said
Kodak apparently is avoiding ``a fire sale of assets.'' But, he
added, ``You don't reassure your employees by leaving them to wonder
whether they're part of the $1.25 billion in businesses which are up
for grabs.''
   Kodak laid off about 13,000 workers in 1986 and 10,800 in 1983.
In both instances, profits rose substantially the next year.
   ``We have dealt with adversity in the past, but never with such
broad-based intensity,'' said Kodak's chairman and chief executive
officer, Colby Chandler. ``These uncharacteristic actions are being
carried out with great resolve by the entire management team.''
   Chandler said the restructuring should improve operating results
by up to $1 billion next year.
   At company headquarters, Kodak said it would freeze workers' pay
in 1990 except in special cases and change the pay structure of
managers so it will be linked more closely to financial results.
   Up to 40 percent of pay for top managers _ Chandler, President
Kay Whitmore and Vice Chairman J. Phillip Samper _ will be tied to
the company's financial performance.
   From 15 percent to 30 percent of the pay of other senior
executives and 15 percent of the pay of managers below the rank of
vice president also will be based on how well the company does,
Allen said.
   Chandler said divisions also would attack costs by cutting back
on excessive inventories and shortening the length of time between
sales and receipt of payment.
   On Aug. 1, the company announced earnings fell 85 percent in the
second quarter, to $60 million, or 18 cents a share, from a record
$390 million, or $1.20 a share, last year.
   For the first half of 1989, earnings fell 60 percent to $260
million, or 80 cents a share, from $650 million, or $2 a share, a
year earlier.
   Kodak announced the restructuring after the stock market closed
Wednesday. Its shares rose $1 to finish at $50.75 in active trading
on the New York Stock Exchange.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890824-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 0236EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-WangPresident Bjt   08-24 0638</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wang President, Bjt,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>Troubled Wang Laboratories Names New President</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard Miller, the new president of Wang
Laboratories Inc., may get the chief executive title as well if he
succeeds in turning around the hard-pressed computer maker, an
analyst says.
   ``He's the finest financially oriented executive I've met,'' said
James I. Magid, a senior adviser to the investment firm of Needham &amp;
Co. ``I would bet they would make Rick Miller chief executive in the
second profitable quarter, once he proves he can turn it.''
   Miller, 48, a veteran of Penn Central Corp. and the consumer
electronics businesses of RCA Corp. and General Electric Co., on
Wednesday was named president and chief operating officer of Lowell,
Mass.-based Wang.
   Wang portrayed him as a turnaround specialist who could help the
minicomputer company recover from last year's $424 million loss and
the defection of some nervous customers.
   Miller never has worked for a computer company, but An Wang, the
company's 69-year-old founder and chairman, praised him in a
statement that indicated Wang plans to give him a large degree of
independence.
   ``I have great confidence in the ability of Rick Miller to assume
total control of the operations of Wang Laboratories,'' Wang said.
``He will have my full support and that of the board of directors in
resolving the company's current situation and restoring it to
profitability.''
   Miller replaces Frederick Wang, the son and former heir apparent
of the founder, who resigned Aug. 8 as the company's financial
troubles mounted. Harry H.S. Chou served as president in the interim.
   Wang stock rose 25 cents to close at $6.25 a share Wednesday on
the American Stock Exchange.
   Miller spent 12 years at Penn Central, during which the former
railroad company emerged from Bankruptcy Court reorganization as an
electronics and defense concern. He went to work for RCA in 1982. He
combined and restructured the consumer electronics operations of the
merged General Electric and RCA before their sale last year to
France's Thomson SA.
   John Welch, GE's chairman, released a statement Wednesday
praising Miller. ``Rick Miller is an outstanding leader. He has very
high standards.'' Welch said Miller has ``dealt successfully with
difficult situations in the past at Penn Central, RCA and GE.''
   In an interview in New York, Miller said he wants Wang staffers
to ``know where we're going, restore their dignity and give them
pride in the company's turnaround and accomplishments.''
   Miller also said the company likely would raise new money by
issuing more stock or debt, or both, and said several people were
interested in providing capital.
   There are no plans to sell Wang, he said.
   Following its loss of $424 million in the fiscal year ended June
30, Wang predicted more red ink in the first half of its current
fiscal year. It briefly suspended payments on some of its debt, but
resumed them this week after reaching a new agreement with its bank
lenders.
   Miller said his top priority is to reassure customers, some of
whom have been reluctant to buy from Wang because of concerns about
whether it will survive.
   A survey of 100 customers by Computerworld, a weekly newspaper,
found that 22 percent had been prompted to switch some buying to
other companies because of concerns about Wang's financial stability.
   That is a dangerously high percentage for a company that is
seeking to increase its revenue, said Jeff Goverman, an analyst at
SoundView Financial Group in Stamford, Conn.
   Analysts said before Miller's appointment that the new president
would have to have good relations with the founder, and Miller said
that is the case.
   Miller said, ``I could not be happier with the ease of
communication and the good relationship that has developed'' with An
Wang. ``There is mutual respect and the beginning of trust.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890824-0215 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 0239EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Drexel-Milken Bjt   08-24 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drexel-Milken, Bjt,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sources: Prosecutors May Allow Drexel to Pay Milken</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. is reminding its
employees not to do business with its indicted former junk bond
chief, Michael Milken.
   Separately, sources said Wednesday that federal prosecutors are
reconsidering their agreement with Drexel that bars the investment
house from paying Milken his 1988 compensation of more than $100
million.
   Drexel this week issued a three-sentence memo to all workers
saying they cannot advise corporate clients if they also are being
advised by Milken, who has resigned from Drexel and set up a
financial consulting firm.
   ``While employees of Drexel Burnham may have purely social
contact with them, business matters that do or could involve Drexel
Burnham are not to be discussed,'' read the memo signed by Drexel
Chief Executive Frederick Joseph.
   Under a separate settlement with the Securities and Exchange
Commission, Drexel and its employees are barred from doing business
with Milken and his brother, Lowell, who also is charged by the
government.
   The Milkens were not party to the firm's SEC settlement, which is
to take effect after Drexel enters its criminal plea.
   Drexel spokesman Steven Anreder said the memo was issued because
the firm is ``determined to live within the spirit of the (SEC)
agreement in the absence of its finalization.''
   Drexel was barred from paying Milken as part of its formal
settlement of criminal securities fraud charges.
   The withholding of pay has been controversial because Milken has
not been charged with committing any wrongdoing during 1988. Milken
has challenged the provision in U.S. District Court in Manhattan.
   Sources familiar with the case, who asked not to be identified,
said prosecutors have not made a final decision on whether to let
Drexel pay Milken his compensation, which court documents place at
well over $100 million.
   But they indicated a reversal may be made because legal experts
have criticized the provision as potentially unconstitutional and
the government may not want to start its case against Milken before
U.S. District Judge Kimba Wood on the wrong foot.
   They said ending the lengthy delay of Drexel's plea in the case
was not a factor in reconsidering the payment provision, but the
move could help to speed resolution of the drawn-out case.
   Spokesmen for Drexel and Milken declined to comment.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney John Carroll said, ``When and if we make
a decision with regard to any matters in these cases, we will tell
them to Judge Wood before we tell them to anyone else.''
   Milken was charged in March in a 98-count indictment with
racketeering and fraud related to securities transactions. He
pleaded innocent and is scheduled to go to trial in March.
   A U.S. District Court hearing is scheduled for Sept. 6 on
Milken's arguments that the pay provision deprived him of
constitutional due process.
   The government has indicated Milken's compensation was ordered
withheld on grounds it was improper for Drexel to settle criminal
charges while it was paying millions to the employee allegedly
responsible for illegal activity.
   Drexel agreed in December to pay $650 million and plead guilty to
six felonies for violating securities laws, charges that stemmed
from the Ivan Boesky insider trading case. The plea has been held up
by a series of legal issues related to Milken, the last of which was
his challenge of the pay requirement.
</TEXT>
