<FIRST>r f PM-Time-Warner     08-24 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time-Warner,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time Warner To Exchange Securities for Remaining Warner Stock</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Warner Inc. and Warner Communications Inc.
announced that Warner shareholders would receive a package of
securities for their stock when the two media giants complete their
$14 billion merger.
   The companies said Wednesday that each of Warner's 86.8 million
shares still outstanding would be exchanged for securities valued at
$70, comprising two series of Time Warner preferred stock and common
stock of BHC Inc., a subsidiary of Chris-Craft Industries Inc.
   Time Inc. acquired approximately 100 million other Warner shares
at $70 a share in a cash tender offer that expired July 24. At that
point the company changed its name to Time Warner Inc.
   The package announced Wednesday _ known as the back end of the
merger _ means Time Warner's debt will not be further ballooned by
the cost of acquiring Warner. Shareholders and analysts had been
concerned about the amount of debt Time Warner would have following
the merger.
   Edward Adler, a Time Warner spokesman, said Time Warner would
incur $12 billion in debt in the acquisition, and with nearly $1.6
billion in already outstanding debt would have a total of $13.6
billion in liabilities.
   Fred Anschel, an analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc., said the
fact that no cash was involved in the back end was a plus for Time
Warner.
   Time Warner stock gained $2.12{ to close at $141.75 a share in
New York Stock Exchange composite trading.
   However, there appeared to be some confusion among Warner
investors about the breakdown of the preferred stock, and Warner
stock slipped $1.62{ to $65.37{ a share.
   The preferred stock can be converted to common stock in Time
Warner in the future, but the two series carry different terms for
their conversion and different dividends.
   Stock in BHC was included in the back end as a result of a
settlement between Warner and Chris-Craft. The settlement was part
of Warner's attempt to sever its ties with Chris-Craft, Warner's
largest shareholder.
   Analysts were still studying the details of the back end late
Wednesday. Ken Noble, an analyst with PaineWebber Inc., said that at
first glance the terms appeared good for current Warner shareholders.
   Time Warner said it expected paperwork and approvals for the back
end to be completed in the fourth quarter. At that time, the merger
will be completed and Warner Communications will cease to exist.
   Time Warner will be the world's largest communications concern.
   Time Inc. and Warner Communications announced plans to merge in a
stock-swap in March. On June 6, 2{ weeks before shareholders were to
vote on the deal, Paramount Communications Inc. announced a hostile
tender offer for Time.
   To preserve their merger, Time and Warner amended their agreement
to provide for Time's $14 billion tender offer for Warner.
   Paramount's $12 billion bid collapsed after the Delaware Supreme
Court upheld a lower court ruling that Paramount had no right to
interfere with Time's long-range plans.
   The ruling allowed the Time-Warner deal to go through and it also
was seen as upholding the rights of companies to arrange friendly
mergers without fear of having their plans upset by hostile suitors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
