<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     08-24 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Up Sharply, Tokyo Shares Decline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose sharply today against the
Japanese yen while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange declined.
   The dollar closed at 143.60 yen, up 1.25 yen from Wednesday's
close of 142.35 yen. After opening at 143.45 yen, it ranged between
143.37 and 143.83 yen. Over the previous three trading days, the
dollar had fallen 1.17 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which lost 221.07 points Wednesday, dropped another
106.73 points, or 0.3 percent, closing at 34,786.55.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar gained after news
reports that a key official in the cabinet of new Prime Minister
Toshiki Kaifu would resign over a sex scandal.
   Chief Cabinet Secretary Tokuo Yamashita then apologized for a
past extra-marital affair, but said only that he was ``seriously
considering'' whether to resign.
   Some dealers, meanwhile, said the decline in the yen stemmed more
from dealers selling West German marks to buy dollars than from any
inherent weakness in the yen.
   ``There was no yen-affecting news today,'' said a dealer at Daiwa
Bank.
   Kazuhiro Nomura, a trader with New Japan Securities, said most
investors were waiting on the sidelines during much of the stock
exchange's morning session.
   ``In the afternoon, there was some buying by institutional
investors and index-related purchases by foreign traders, but
overall today's market was weak,'' he said.
   Nomura said no issues attracted particular buyer interest during
the day.
   Trading was thin, with only 380 million shares changing hands.
</TEXT>
