<DOCNO> AP890824-0222 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 0834EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-AutoSales     08-24 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Sales,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fear of 1990 Price Increases Spur Car Sales</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Car sales by the eight major U.S.-based automakers
rose 5.4 percent in mid-August while light truck sales fell 2.1
percent, indicating that some buyers may be rushing to showrooms to
beat 1990 price increases.
   Overall, car and truck sales continued running behind last year's
pace by 3.3 percent, the companies said in sales reports Wednesday.
   ``The two big leading (economic) indicators, that being
unemployment and interest rates, don't seem to have softened,'' said
analyst Paul Kleinaitis of Duff &amp; Phelps of Chicago.
   ``So given that, and given the fact that price increases are due
for the Big Three, maybe buyers were accelerated into purchasing now
rather than in the new model year,'' he said.
   General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. have
announced average car price increases of 3.4 percent, 4.8 percent
and 5 percent, respectively.
   ``I think the uptick we had in July (sales) was partly an
increase in consumer awareness of a price increase,'' said analyst
Mary Anne Sudol of Fitch Investors Service Inc. in New York City.
   ``But the incentives got richer and the combinations make some
deals too good to resist for some people,'' she said. ``Right now,
we're borrowing sales from the fourth quarter.''
   On Wednesday, the automakers reported combined car and truck
sales averaging 34,290 a day during the Aug. 11-20 period this year,
up 2.6 percent from a rate of 33,409 during the same time last year.
   ``The numbers look good to me, compared to what we've been
conditioned to expect,'' Kleinaitis said.
   Through last Sunday, companies said, 1989 vehicle sales averaged
37,908 a day, down 3.3 percent from the 39,222 vehicle-a-day rate
during the same period last year.
   GM said its mid-August car sales were off 0.7 percent compared
with last year and for the year to date, its car sales were down 8.3
percent. GM's truck sales were up 4.3 percent in mid-August and up
1.9 percent for the year to date.
   Ford said its car sales were up 2.8 percent during the second
10-day period of August but were down 1.4 percent for the year.
Ford's light truck sales were down 10.7 percent in mid-August and
down 3 percent for the year to date.
   Chrysler said its car sales during the period were up 6 percent
from last year and down 13.3 percent for the year. The company's
light truck sales fell 1.2 percent for the period and 0.2 percent
for the year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
