<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Higher Crop Estimates Force Down Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures were mostly lower this
morning on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Analysts say a survey this week of the Midwest corn crop has
added several million bushels to the Agriculture Department's
estimated crop yield. That news is pushing corn prices lower.
   Soybean prices were pushed lower by rains and a National Weather
Service 6- to 10-day forecast that calls for more precipitation.
Soybean prices are also being pressured by a lack of demand.
   In addition, the continued high exodus of grain from reserve
stocks is adding to supplies,'' said Rich Feltes, an analyst with
Refco Inc. in Chicago.
   Wheat prices were mixed at the start of trading, with support
coming from anticipated orders from Egypt and other nations.
   In early trading, wheat was 1{ cents lower to { cent higher with
the contract for delivery in September at $3.92\ a bushel; corn was
} cent to 2\ cents lower with September at $2.34 a bushel; oats were
1 cent to 1\ cents lower with September at $1.38 cents a bushel;
soybeans were 4 cents lower to 4{ cents higher with September at
$5.94 cents a bushel.
   Livestock futures were mostly lower and pork futures mostly
higher in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .05 cent to .17 cent lower with September at 74
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent lower o .08 cent higher
with August at 84.25 cents a pound; hogs were .08 cent to .30 cent
higher with October at 41.60 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.05 cent lower to .30 cent higher with August at 27.47 cents a pound.
   Livestock and pork futures settled higher at the close of trading
Wednesday.
</TEXT>
