<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 1251EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Holiday-Bass 1stLd-Writethru   08-24 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Holiday-Bass, 1st Ld-Writethru,0534</SECOND>
<HEAD>Holiday Inns Sold to Bass PLC</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after the 6th graf with analyst's comment; picks
up 7th graf, Last year ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holiday Corp. said today it will sell its
Holiday Inn hotel system to Bass PLC for $2.23 billion and create a
subsidiary to operate the company's gaming operations and three
newer hotel brands.
   Holiday Chairman Michael Rose said the company decided to sell
the Holiday Inn system because ``it became increasingly clear to us
that a separation of Holiday Inns from Holiday Corp.'s other brands
was the most effective positioning of the brands in the 1990s and
beyond.''
   Holiday's other hotels include Embassy Suites, Hampton Inn and
Homewood Suites. Rose said these chains ``had reached levels of
development that will make them increasingly competitive with
Holiday Inns.''
   Bass, a British brewer and hotel operators, will acquire 55 owned
or leased properties, as well as franchise agreements, joint venture
agreements and management contracts that cover about 1,400 Holiday
Inn hotels in North America.
   The agreement calls for Bass to merge a new U.S. subsidiary with
Holiday, converting each share of Holiday stock into about .25 share
of Bass stock. Holiday will retire or assume about $2.1 billion in
debt.
   Holiday stock shot up $7.25 to $84.25 a share at midday on the
New York Stock Exchange today. On Wednesday, the company's stock
soared $7.87{ in anticipation of today's announcement.
   Analysts were pleased with the move. Marvin Roffman, a market
analyst with Janney Montgomery Scott Inc. of Philadelphia, said
Holiday Corp. got a top price for the Holiday Inn chain.
   The deal also ``clearly focuses (Holiday Corp.) in the
high-growth segments of the hotel business and makes it much more of
a gaming company,'' Roffman said.
   Last year, Bass bought the rights to franchise Holiday Inn hotels
outside North America. As the result of that and other purchases it
already owns 14 Holiday Inn hotels in the southeast United States
and is a major franchisee in Canada.
   Bass, with annual sales approaching $6 billion, has more than
7,300 pubs and other food and drink outlets in the United Kingdom.
It brews Bass, Carling Black Label and other beers and has annual
sales approaching $6 billion.
   Holiday has sold off a number of assets in recent years as part
of a recapitalization plan. In February, Holiday Corp. five hotels
to a limited partnership comprising overseas investors or their U.S.
subsidiaries.
   In May, Holiday formed a partnership with a Japanese company to
develop hotels in the United States.
   The spun-off company to operate the three newer hotel chains and
Holiday's Harrah's casinos in Nevada and New Jersey will be run by
Holiday's present senior management group in Memphis and will be
named at a later date.
   ``The spin-off company, formed around Harrah's and these rapidly
growing brands, will be given a new name that reflects the dynamism,
prospective growth and commitment to excellence that will
characterize it,'' Rose said.
   The transactions announced today must be approved by stockholders
from both companies, as well as Nevada and New Jersey gaming
officials.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890824-0231 </DOCNO>
