<DOCNO> AP890824-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 1518EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Britain-Bass Bjt   08-24 0492</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Bass, Bjt,0509</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Britain's Biggest Brewer To Operate World's Largest Hotel Chain
^By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bass PLC's proposed $2.23 billion acquisition of
the Holiday Inn hotel system from Holiday Corp. would make Britain's
biggest brewer the operator of the world's largest hotel chain.
   The deal, which would give Bass control of some 1,600 Holiday
Inns, marks an attempt by the London-based company to diversify away
from brewing and to expand geographically, analysts said Thursday.
   Bass has been criticized in recent years for having its profits
too heavily concentrated in beer and pubs in Britain. Analysts say
the company's Bass, Carling Black Label and Tennent's beers and the
7,000 pubs it owns in Britain represent about 68 percent of its
operating profits.
   Rupert Symington, an analyst with Nomura Securities in London,
noted that ``Bass is almost completely a brewery and pub company. It
has recognized a need to diversify out of its core business of beer
and pubs.''
   With the Holiday Inn purchase, Symington said hotels will
represent 25 percent of Bass's operating profits, compared with 10
percent currently.
   While the acquisition initially might depress Bass' stock price,
analysts called it a good strategic move for long-term development.
   ``It's very difficult when you're No. 1 of the British market
with 22 percent of the market, to grow and get a bigger market
share,'' said one analyst who asked not to be identified.
   Under terms of the deal, Bass will acquire 55 owned or leased
properties, as well as franchise agreements, joint venture
agreements and management contracts that cover about 1,400 Holiday
Inn hotels in North America.
   Last year, Bass bought the rights to franchise Holiday Inn hotels
outside North America, covering about 200 of them.
   Bass said the acquisition gives it ``considerable opportunity for
profit growth'' by allowing it to capitalize on its vast expertise
in ownership and management of international hotels.
   So far the company's diversification into hotels has been
successful. Symington noted that Bass's 66 Crest hotels in Britain
and its European Holiday Inns are performing well.
   Last March, Bass bought the Commonwealth Hospitality Ltd. hotel
chain in Canada from Scotts Hospitality Inc. of Toronto for $222
million, giving it an additional 38 hotels.
   Bass Chairman Ian Prosser said the acquisition ``represents a
substantial move forward in the Bass strategy of becoming
international in each of its core businesses.''
   But one analyst noted that Bass is ``a very U.K.-based company.
Even after this acquisition, three-fourths of its profit comes from
the U.K.''
   Over the years Bass also has marketed soft drinks under Britvic
and other brand names, and operated bingo and snooker halls, betting
shops and a travel agency with mixed results, Symington said.
   On the London Stock Exchange, Bass rose 8 cents to close at
$17.97 a share.
   Bass, which employs 85,000 people, reported profits of $504
million, or $1.37 a share, on revenue of $5.8 billion in the year
ended September 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890824-0235 </DOCNO>
