<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 2145EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-RobinsAppeal     08-24 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Robins Appeal,0673</SECOND>
<HEAD>Claimants Who Challenged Robins Plan to Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Implementation of A.H. Robins Co.'s
reorganization plan will be delayed until at least November while
claimants who challenged the plan appeal its approval to the U.S.
Supreme Court, claimants said Thursday.
   ``We're going to the Supreme Court,'' said Rosemary
Menard-Sanford, one of thousands of women who claimed they were
injured by the Dalkon Shield birth-control device marketed by the
company in the early 1970s.
   More than 94 percent of the claimants voted in favor of the
reorganization plan, confirmed by U.S. District Judge Robert R.
Merhige Jr. But about 900 women had rejected the plan, which was
upheld in June by the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals along with a
related class-action suit against Aetna Casualty and Surety Co.
   Had no further appeals been sought, the trust would have been
funded and the plan consummated Sept. 28, Robins spokesman Roscoe
Puckett said Thursday.
   ``Robins recognizes that it is the appellants' right to seek
further review of the plan by the Supreme Court,'' Puckett said.
``However, the company believes that the overwhelming majority of
Dalkon Shield claimants who voted to accept the plan will share its
deep disappointment and frustration that there will be further
indeterminant delays in implementation of the plan.
   ``The appellants' decision, which will continue to cost claimants
roughly half a million dollars daily in lost interest income, is
particularly disappointing in light of the fact that five judges
already have considered the reorganization plan and judged it
proper.''
   Robins, a large pharmaceutical company based in Richmond, sought
protection under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy laws in August
1985.
   Included in the reorganization plan are a $2.3 billion fund to
compensate claimants injured by the Dalkon Shield; $350 million in
insurance from Aetna, the products liability insurer for the device;
and the absorption of Robins by American Home Products Corp. of New
York in an exchange of stock worth $700 million to Robins
shareholders.
   Suits against Robins officers and directors and the Richmond law
firm that supervised most of the Dalkon Shield litigation before the
bankruptcy action are barred.
   In the petition to be filed Sept. 14, three women represented by
Washington lawyer Alan B. Morrison said they have decided not to
pursue their contention that the approval of the plan was flawed.
   Instead, the women said, they will focus on provisions of the
plan that bar suits against other defendants, which would allow
Robins and American Home Products to complete their merger if they
wish.
   ``We believe that the amount of money set aside in the Dalkon
Shield Claimants' Trust established by the Robins' reorganization
plan is inadequate, as it will not provide full compensation for
Dalkon Shield victims, particularly those with clearly meritorious
claims and serious injuries,'' said Denver lawyer Douglas E. Bragg,
who represents about 100 claimants.
   The amount needed to resolve the claims is closer to $4.2 billion
to $7 billion, Bragg said.
   He said that since the trust might not have enough money to
resolve all claims, claimants must be free to pursue Aetna, Robins
officers and directors and the company's attorneys, who he said are
liable because they conspired with Robins to cover up the dangers of
the Dalkon Shield.
   The companies last month rejected a merger that would have
allowed suits against other defendants. The companies have said
suits against the other potential defendants would result in claims
for indemnity against the trust. Defending those claims would
distract the trustees and reduce the amount of money available to
pay claims, the companies contend.
   About 118,000 claims still are pending and would be resolved
through procedures to be developed by trustees of the claimants'
trust.
   E. Claiborne Robins, patriarch of the pharmaceutical company, and
his son, Robins President E. Claiborne Robins Jr., have agreed to
pay $5 million each to the trust fund, which also will get $75
million from Aetna.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
