<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rains Send Prices Lower in Dull Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Futures prices of grain and soybeans closed mixed
in quiet trading Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Overnight rains in the Midwest and the National Weather Service's
6- to 10-day forecast, which calls for additional precipitation in
major crop states, weighed on the market.
   Also putting a brake on corn prices were reports that a survey of
the Iowa corn crop placed the per-acre yield at higher levels than
predicted by the U.S. Department of Agriculture, said Jerry Gidel,
an analyst with LIT America Inc. in Chicago.
   There had been reports that a lack of rain earlier this month
caused a decline in the quality of crops in parts of the Midwest,
including Iowa.
   Soybean prices were pressured by the weather forecasts and lack
of demand.
   Wheat prices were mixed at the start of trading, with support
coming from anticipated orders from Egypt and other nations. The
failure of the orders to materialize during trading did not prevent
wheat prices from finishing higher.
   At the close of trading, wheat was a { cent to 2} cents higher
with the contract for delivery in September at $3.93} a bushel; corn
was 1} cents to 3 cents lower with September at $2.34 a bushel; oats
were 1\ cents to 1{ cents lower with September at $1.38 a bushel;
soybeans were a 1} cents lower to a \ cent higher with September at
$5.95{ a bushel.
