<FIRST>u f AM-MoneyFunds     08-24 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Money Funds,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rise to New Record of $343.22 Billion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report
are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended Wednesday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 463 money market mutual
funds rose by $2.68 billion in the latest week to hit a new record
of $343.22 billion, the Investment Company Institute said Thursday.
   The rise in the seven-day period ended Wednesday marked the
eighth straight week for a new all-time high in fund assets, the
Washington-based mutual trade group reported.
   The previous record set the week ended Aug. 16 totaled $340.54
billion, revised slightly upward from the $340.51 billion originally
reported by the institute.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 227 general purpose funds rose $1.04 billion to $109.78
billion, assets of 95 broker-dealer funds increased $1.59 billion to
$147.85 billion, and assets of 141 institutional funds rose by $51.0
million to $85.58 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds fell in
the week ended Tuesday to 8.31 percent from 8.33 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield fell to 8.38 percent from 8.45 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was 40
days, unchanged from a week earlier, Donoghue's said.
   The newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of 100 leading
commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and savings banks in
the nation's 10 largest markets showed the effective annual yield
available on money market accounts fell to 6.45 percent as of
Wednesday from 6.46 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super NOW
accounts, was 5.11 percent, unchanged from the previous week.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 8.25
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, unchanged from the
previous week. Yields were 8.26 percent on 1-year CDs, up from 8.25
percent; 8.19 percent on 2{-year CDs, up from 8.17 percent; and 8.18
percent on 5-year CDs, up from 8.17 percent.
</TEXT>
