<SECOND>AM-Newspage Stocks,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dow Industrial Average Sets New Record High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dow Jones industrial average surged 56.53
points a new closing high Thursday, shattering the record set almost
exactly two years earlier and symbolically marking a recovery from
the Black Monday crash.
   The index of 30 blue chip industrial stocks _ which to many
people symbolizes the stock market _ finished at 2,734.64, topping
the previous record close of 2,722.42 of Aug. 25, 1987.
   With Thursday's session, the Dow became the last of the widely
recognized market indicators to recover all the ground it lost in
the crash of 1987 that culminated with a record 508 point loss on
Oct. 19.
   Wall Street has been rallying in recent months largely due to a
decline in interest rates, which investors see as an encouraging
sign that the Federal Reserve is controlling inflation without
causing an economic recession.
   Widespread speculation in takeover stocks also has helped boost
prices.
   The Dow industrials actually had flirted with a new high in
several sessions earlier this month before pulling back each time at
the close.
   ``It was sort of a bugaboo for a lot of people,'' said Robert
Seijas, a market maker at the New York Stock Exchange. ``Just
getting through it removes a lot of the fear.''
   On Thursday, interest rates declined slightly in erratic trading
while several other takeover developments emerged, including Holiday
Corp.'s agreement to sell its Holiday Inn hotel chain to Bass PLC
for $2.23 billion.
   Big-name stocks also got a boost at midday from a wave of buying
by professional traders engaged in computerized strategies involving
stock index options and futures.
</TEXT>
