<FIRST>u f AM-Australia-PilotsStrike     08-24 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Australia-Pilots Strike,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Australia's Domestic Airline Industry Shut Down By Pilots' Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Australia's domestic airline industry
shut down Thursday as carriers began dismissing pilots for not
working to contract and all 1,600 pilots retaliated by resigning en
masse.
   The pilots began striking last Friday over a demand for a 30
percent wage increase which the labor government has called
unacceptable because of a wages and incomes policy limiting
increases to 3 percent.
   Pilots refused to work beyond the hours of 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.
   Most international airlines, meanwhile, agreed to provide seats
for domestic passengers for the Australian segments of international
flights.
   At least eight international carriers, including Continental
Airlines of the United States, have agreed to carry domestic
passengers on the domestic segments of their routes. The others are
Thai International, Singapore Airlines, Olympic Airways of Greece,
Garuda of Indonesia, Malaysian Airways, Cathay Pacific of Hong Kong
and British Airways.
   The Australian government also was considering providing
emergency services with the help of the Air Force. An Air Force
Boeing 747 was expected to take to the air on Friday.
   Pilots for Qantas Airways, Australia's international flag
carrier, refused to act as strike-breakers and said they would not
cooperate except to pick up domestic passengers for compassionate
reasons.
   The two domestic airlines, Australian Airlines and Ansett, began
issuing writs against individual pilots seeking unspecified damages
to cover lost profits.
   The pilots are seeking a wage hike that would boost an average
annual salary to 100,000 U.S. dollars.
   Tourism officials said the dispute could cost the country
millions of dollars in lost revenue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
