<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     08-24 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Finishes Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede BC-LONDON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished mostly higher in quiet
worldwide trading Thursday.
   Gold prices declined. On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold
bullion for current delivery lost $1.30 to close at $364.50 a troy
ounce. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a late bid for gold
of $362.40 an ounce, down from $364.15 late Wednesday.
   Traders said the dollar held within a very narrow range
throughout the day and volume was very thin.
   After a brief selloff on unconfirmed rumors that the Federal
Reserve and the Bank of Japan might be moving to lower interest
rates, the dollar staged a ``minor comeback,'' said Curtis Perkins,
a trader at Chemical New York Capital Markets Group.
   The underlying sentiment toward the U.S. currency remains fairly
bullish, traders said. ``It's been a very slow move up, slow and
steady with corrections all the way, but we're always solidifying
the move up,'' noted Stephen Flanagan, a vice president at
Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co.
   Flanagan said the West German Bundesbank's announcement that it
was not altering its monetary policy helped support the dollar.
Several other European central banks followed by saying they also
planned no immediate changes in interest rates.
   Earlier in the week traders began bracing themselves for a hike
in European interest rates, which would pressure the dollar by
making the returns on foreign investments more attractive.
   In the absence of any meaningful news, traders are looking to
next week's release of U.S. economic indicators to influence the
market.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar rose a sharp 1.25 Japanese yen to close at 143.60 yen.
Later in London, it was quoted at 143.29 yen. In New York, the
dollar closed at 143.21 yen, up from 143.20 yen late Wednesday.
   In London, the dollar gained against the British pound. It cost
$1.5698 to buy one pound, cheaper than $1.5700 late Wednesday. In
New York, one pound cost $1.5720, more expensive than Wednesday's
$1.5715.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Wednesday, included: 1.9565 West German marks, up from 1.9525;
1.6870 Swiss francs, up from 1.6838; 6.5955 French francs, up from
6.5875; 1,402.50 Italian lire, up from 1,398.88, and 1.1748 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.1769.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Wednesday,
included: 1.9585 West German marks, up from 1.9555; 1.6880 Swiss
francs, up from 1.6870; 6.6060 French francs, up from 6.5965; 2.2095
Dutch guilders, up from 2.2000; 1,406.75 Italian lire, up from
1,399.50, and 1.1765 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1727.
   Gold fell in London to a late bid price of $362.75 a troy ounce,
down from late Wednesday's $364.25. In Zurich, Switzerland, gold
closed at a bid $362.00, down from $363.85 late Wednesday. Earlier
in Hong Kong, gold fell $2.48 to close at a bid $364.75.
   Silver prices were mixed. On New York's Comex, silver for current
delivery rose to $5.166 a troy ounce from $5.164 on Wednesay. In
London, the metal traded at a late bid price of $5.17 a troy ounce,
down from $5.19.
</TEXT>
