<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     08-24 0827</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0859</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coffee Prices Plunge on Brazilian Announcement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Coffee futures prices fell sharply Thursday on New York's Coffee,
Sugar &amp; Cocoa Exchange on news that Brazil will not re-introduce its
coffee retention program.
   On other markets, copper was up sharply, sugar prices plunged,
grain and sopybean futures were mostly lower, livestock and pork
futures were down and precious metals were mixed.
   Coffee prices settled 4.22 cents to 4.75 cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at 79 cents a pound.
   Esther Eskenasy, an analyst for Cargill Investors Services in New
York, described the selloff of coffee futures, the first in five
sessions, as panic selling.
   ``The market dropped like a stone from the opening, and didn't
get support until it reached 80 cents,'' she said.
   Ms. Eskenasy attributed the decline to an announcement late
Wednesday by Brazilian Coffee Institute President Jorio Dauster that
the institute has no plans to begin storing three 60-kilogram bags
of coffee for every bag exported.
   Dauster said the policy was dropped when the International Coffee
Organization abolished export quotas in July.
   The organization will meet again on Sept. 25 when it is expected
to again address export quotas. Ms. Exkenasy said some countries are
pressing for quotas because of hurting economies.
   Copper futures continued their upward spiral as production
problems continue to influence the market.
   ``Every producing company has some kind of problem,'' said Fred
Demler, an analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York,
adding that the problems will not be resolved soon.
   In addition to a paralyzing strike in Peru, a strike continues at
the Highland Valley mines in British Columbia, Canada. Mexico's
Cananea mine is expected to be closed as long as three months
following a declaration of bankruptcy. And the Bougainville mine in
Papua, New Guinea remains closed because of terrorist activities by
landowners.
   ``Demand in the United States and Japan remains strong at a time
of declining stocks, at a time of year when they usually increase
because of slack demand,'' Demler said.
   Copper prices were 2.60 cents to 2.90 cents higher with August at
$1.305 a pound.
   An expected rise in European sugar production sent sugar futures
plummeting on the Coffee, Sugar and Cocoa Exchange.
   A report prepared by a West German statistician indicates that
European sugar production will increase by more than 1 million
metric tons from 30.9 million metric tons in 1988-1989.
   The report also predicted the Soviet Union will reduce its sugar
imports.
   Sugar settled .20 cent to .30 cent lower with October at 13.90
cents a pound.
   Grain and soybean futures were mixed in quiet trading on the
Chicago Board of Trade.
   Overnight rains in the Midwest and the National Weather Service's
6- to 10-day forecast, which calls for additional precipitation in
major crop states, weighed on the market.
   Also putting a brake on corn prices were reports that a survey of
the Iowa corn crop placed the per-acre yield at higher levels than
predicted by the U.S. Department of Agriculture, said Jerry Gidel,
an analyst with LIT America Inc. in Chicago.
   Wheat prices were mixed at the start of trading, with support
coming from anticipated orders from Egypt and other nations.
   Wheat was \ cent to 3 cents higher with the contract for delivery
in September at $3.93} a bushel; corn was 1} cents to 3 cents lower
with September at $2.34\ a bushel; oats were a { cent to 1{ cents
lower with September at $1.38 a bushel; soybeans were a 2\ cents
lower to a \ cent higher with September at $5.95} a bushel.
   Oil futures were mostly lower in quiet trading on the New York
Mercantile Exchange in the wake of a Department of Energy report of
an 8.9 million barrel buildup of crude oil stocks.
   West Texas Intermediate crude was 10 cents to 20 cents lower with
October at $18.61 a barrel; heating oil was .08 cent to .29 cent
lower with September at 51.70 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was
.01 cent to .29 cent lower with September at 54.15 cents a gallon.
   Precious metals prices were lower on New York's Commodities
Exchange on slack interest due to a stronger-than-expected economy.
   Gold settled $1.20 to $1.30 lower with August at $364.50 a troy
ounce; silver was 1 cent to 2 cents lower with August at $5.175 a
troy ounce.
   Pork futures were slightly higher on gains in spot-market prices,
and livestock futures were lower due to concerns over plentiful
supplies in light trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .12 cent to .38 cent lower with September at
73.80 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .27 cent lower
with August at 84.10 cents a pound; live hogs were .05 cent lower to
.25 cent higher with October at 41.62 cents a pound; pork bellies
were .02 cent lower to 1.80 cents higher with August at 28.97 cents
a pound.
</TEXT>
