<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     08-24 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Close Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices closed mostly lower in
moderate trading Thursday, pressured by new government data that
showed a bigger surplus of oil than earlier reported.
   The Department of Energy, in its weekly inventory report, said
supplies of crude oil and heating oil in storage were several
million barrels higher than those reported by the American Petroleum
Institute on Tuesday.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the October contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude, fell 19
cents to finish at $18.61 a barrel, after an 11-cent gain in
Wednesday's session.
   Refined products traded on the exchange ended mixed, with the
September and October gasoline contracts closing higher. The
September contract for unleaded gasoline rose 0.22 cent to finish at
54.15 cents a gallon and the October contract advanced 0.3 cent to
51.98 cents a gallon. Contracts for later delivery declined.
   Heating oil for September delivery fell 0.21 cent to settle at
51.70 cents a gallon and prices of other contract months also sank.
   Energy brokers said buying by major refiners, who had not been
heavy traders lately, boosted the two front-month gasoline
contracts. The majors were buying the last of the low-vapor summer
gasoline mandated by the Environmental Protection Agency, brokers
said.
   The EPA required refiners to make gasoline with a lower
evaporation tendency during the summer months in an effort to reduce
auto emissions. The restrictions expire on Sept. 15.
   Futures prices reacted early to the DOE statistics, analysts said.
   ``The report started things off on a bad note,'' said Evan Baron,
senior account executive with Elders Futures Inc.
   The report for the week ended Aug. 18 showed that crude supplies
rose 8.9 million barrels to 340.6 million barrels, compared with a
4.4 million-barrel rise to 335.2 million reported by the API.
Heating oil inventories increased to 118 million barrels, a 1.5
million-barrel rise, according to the DOE statistics, compared with
a 1.1 million-barrel-rise to 115.6 million shown in the API report.
   Traders said the DOE report could be a catalyst for weaker prices
over the next few days. Crude prices have zigzagged but remained
relatively strong despite reports that the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries is producing more oil than the global market can
absorb.
</TEXT>
