<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 1920EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet-Record     08-24 0516</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street-Record,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dow Jones Average Breaks Record Two Years After Last Peak</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   History repeated itself and then some Thursday on
Wall Street, where the Dow Jones industrial average had a record
close just one day short of the second anniversary of its previous
all-time high.
   The record appeared to mark Wall Street's complete recovery from
the nightmare of Black Monday _ Oct. 19, 1987 _ when the average
fell a record 508 points in a single session.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks set its record in
suitably dramatic fashion, rocketing 56.53 points higher in the
second biggest gain of the year.
   Wall Street's best-known average closed at 2,734.64, topping the
record of 2,722.42 set on Aug. 25, 1987.
   As often happens, the market made one of its biggest moves on a
day when nothing in particular happened in the financial world
outside the floor of the New York Stock Exchange.
   ``The stock market just came out of nowhere. It's a real
surprise,'' said Robert Brusca, chief economist of Nikko Securities
Co. International Inc., the New York arm of a Japanese brokerage
firm.
   Separating the new record from the last one was the biggest
one-day crash in Wall Street history.
   Measured from its bottom at the close of Black Monday to its new
top, stock prices have gone up more than 50 percent.
   ``While nobody's paid much attention to it, it's two of the
strongest years, back to back, that we've had,'' said Lawrence R.
Helfand, managing director for retail sales at Rodman &amp; Renshaw Inc.
in Chicago.
   Analysts generally believe the stock market is healthier now than
it was two years ago, when speculation inflated a bubble that burst
in the autumn of '87. Stock prices are lower in comparison to
company profits than they were at their last peak.
   The stock market has been helped by a healthy dollar, relatively
low interest rates and optimism that the economy will manage to
steer a middle course between recession and high inflation.
   Still, market watchers said there was no economic news Thursday
to put the Dow industrials over the top. The bond market finished
just slightly above even, while the dollar edged barely higher.
   ``The market's going up just on its own. When you call around,
there's no reason. It just went up,'' Brusca said.
   While nobody knows where the market will go from here, some
traders said the latest rally could draw more money that had been
sitting on the sidelines in short-term investments.
   ``The worst thing that can happen to an institutional money
manager is to sit there with a pile of cash and watch the market
take off with out him. It's a buying panic,'' Helfand said.
   In a healthy sign, volume on the floor of the Big Board was the
heaviest in more than two months at 225.52 million shares.
   ``I think it's terrific. I remain very optimistic that the market
can make further advances,'' said Lawrence Kudlow, chief economist
at Bear, Stearns &amp; Co.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
