<FIRST>u f AM-Texaco-Pollution     08-24 0328</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Texaco-Pollution,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Rules That Texaco Polluted River</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has ruled that Texaco
Inc. polluted the Delaware River over the course of four years by
discharging about 10,000 gallons a day of cooling water that
contained excess amounts of iron.
   The summary judgment, issued Monday by U.S. District Judge Jane
Roth, is a victory for the Natural Resources Defense Council, which
filed suit after both the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency and
the Delaware Department of Natural Resources and Environmental
Control found NRDC's complaint too minor to warrant fines or
penalties, a Delaware environmental official said.
   NRDC alleged that Texaco polluted the river from 1984 to 1988 by
dumping into the Delaware cooling water from a refinery containing
iron levels that exceeded regulatory limits.
   Between 400 million to 500 million gallons of water were
discharged daily, with about 10,000 gallons of that containing
excessive amounts of iron, said Gerard L. Esposito, director of the
state division of water resources.
   Since the suit was brought, the Delaware environmental agency
issued a new permit for Texaco that takes into account the higher
iron discharges, Esposito said.
   The court has not entered any judgment on liability and the
company has not decided if it will appeal, said John Ambler,
Texaco's senior coordinator of public and government affairs.
   Ambler denied the company was at fault.
   He said Texaco contends that the discharges at question ``were
due to sampling errors and some acts of God. Storms upset the waste
water treatment process.''
   Ambler said that the 390 samples found to be in violation were
out of ``tens of thousands'' and were ``only slightly above
permitted levels.''
   ``Since 1985, the (refinery's) waste water treatment plant has
been in over 99 percent compliance,'' he said.
   Texaco's refinery, located in Delaware City about 12 miles south
of Wilmington, refines gasoline, chemical feedstocks, petroleum coke
for utilities and gases for fuel, Ambler said. Texaco is based in
White Plains, N.Y.
</TEXT>
