<FIRST>u f AM-Continental     08-24 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Continental,0339</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lorenzo Considering Sale of Continental</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Air Corp. may consider selling part of its
Continental Airlines subsidiary, Chairman Frank Lorenzo said
Thursday.
   The surprise announcement comes a week after a Boston investment
firm disclosed that it owns 12 percent of Houston-based Texas Air,
the nation's largest airline company. Texas Air owns both
Continental and strikebound Eastern Airlines.
   Texas Air said it has retained Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. as an
investment adviser to discuss any transaction.
   In a statement released late Thursday, Texas Air said: ``In
answer to a question at a company management conference today, ...
Lorenzo said that the company may consider sale of a minority or
controlling position of its Continental Airlines unit and that it
has had discussions with parties who have expressed an interest in
Continental.''
   Art Kent, a spokesman at Continental's Houston headquarters,
declined to comment further on the statement.
   Last week, Loomis, Sayles &amp; Co., a Boston portfolio management
company, said its 12 percent stake in Texas Air was held for
investment because it believed the company would show a profit in
1990.
   Miami-based Eastern is in the midst of Chapter 11 bankruptcy
reorganization. The carrier filed for protection on March 9, five
days after its Machinists, pilots and flight attendants went on
strike. Since then, it has been rebuilding as a smaller airline
using non-union workers.
   Lorenzo followed a similar path with Continental in 1983.
   ``While there are some arguments in favor of seeing Continental
emerge with new ownership, such as giving the company access to
stronger financial or marketplace resources, there are also a number
of compelling reasons why a sale of the company may not be
advisable,'' Lorenzo said in Thursday's statement.
   One of the principal reasons against selling is that the carrier
is emerging from a period of consolidations with other airlines as a
stronger company and shows potential for improved financial results,
he said.
</TEXT>
