<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-NewsCorp     08-24 0301</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-News Corp,0312</SECOND>
<HEAD>News Corp. Earnings More Than Triple On Gains From Publication Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   News Corp. said Thursday its fourth-quarter
earnings more than tripled on gains from the sale of several of its
publications.
   The communications and entertainment company controlled by
publisher Rupert Murdoch said it earned $559.8 million during the
quarter ended June 30, up from $128.1 million a year earlier.
   Earnings per American Depositary Receipt (ADR) rose to $3.34 from
82 cents. ADRs are shares of foreign companies that are traded in
the United States. Each News Corp. ADR, traded on the New York Stock
Exchange, is equivalent to two of the company's common shares.
   News Corp. said it had $413.9 million in one-time gains from the
sale of its travel publications and Elle magazine during the fourth
quarter.
   Without those gains, the company said it would have earned $145.9
million, or 93 cents per ADR, during the quarter. That represents a
10 percent increase from the year-earlier period.
   News Corp. said its revenue rose to $1.84 billion from $1.21
billion in the final quarter a year earlier.
   The company said its international newspaper publishing
operations performed well, and its film and television operations in
the United States _ including 20th Century Fox and Fox Broadcasting
Co. _ were strong during the quarter.
   The company also said its earnings benefited from the acquisition
earlier in the fiscal year of Triangle Publications, the publisher
of TV Guide and other magazines.
   Fox Broadcasting had what News Corp. called ``a dramatic
turnaround,'' and nearly broke even for the year.
   For the entire fiscal year, News Corp. said it earned $944.6
million, or $5.72 per ADR, up from $341.3 million, or $2.20 per ADR,
the year before.
   Full-year revenue totaled $6.4 billion, up from $4.35 billion in
1988.
</TEXT>
