<FIRST>u f AM-NutraSweetExpansion     08-24 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NutraSweet Expansion,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>NutraSweet Plans to Double Production Capacity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NutraSweet Co. announced plans Thursday to double
the production capacity for its artificial sweetener products, which
are marketed in more than 70 countries.
   The company, based in Deerfield, Ill., said its growth over the
past year has made it necessary to expand operations around the
world to meet future demand.
   ``In response to strong consumer demand in both U.S. and
international markets, we will virtually double our global capacity
over the next two years,'' NutraSweet Chairman Robert Shapiro said
in a statement.
   The subsidiary of Monsanto Co. manufactures and markets
NutraSweet worldwide and Equal tabletop sweetener in the United
States.
   By early 1990, the company plans to enlarge its U.S. plants and
open a facility currently under construction in Sao Paulo, Brazil,
officials said.
   During that same period, a partner company in Japan will also
increase its capacity.
   The sweetener is produced at facilities in University Park, Ill.,
and Augusta, Ga. The company also sells aspartame manufactured in a
European partnership with Ajinomoto Co. of Japan.
   NutraSweet spokesman Jim Prescot said the company intends to add
a new manufacturing facility at its Augusta, Ga., plant in 1991 and
also will invest in manufacturing sites in Europe.
   The low-calorie sweetener and popular sugar substitute, also
known as aspartame, is used in 3,000 products around the world,
including diet soft drinks, puddings and frozen desserts.
</TEXT>
