<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 2227EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-Squibb-BristolMyers     08-24 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Squibb-Bristol Myers,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Squibb Says Officials Probing Possible Insider Trading Violations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Squibb Corp. officials say federal
investigators are probing possible insider trading violations
connected with Squibb's proposed merger with Bristol-Myers Co.
   A subpoena issued Tuesday to Dow Jones &amp; Co. said the U.S.
attorney in Manhattan is looking into allegations of mail and wire
fraud stemming from the proposed $11.4 billion merger of the two
pharmaceutical giants, according to a report in The Central New
Jersey Home News of New Brunswick.
   Squibb has been contacted by the Justice Department, the
Securities and Exchange Commission and the New York Stock Exchange,
said John Skule, spokesman for Princeton-based Squibb. He said
company attorneys characterized the inquiries as routine data
gathering in the wake of a major merger announcement.
   Squibb officials did not disclose when they were contacted, who
was interviewed or what information was being sought.
   A spokeswoman for Bristol-Myers, reading from a statement, said
the New York company is cooperating fully with the SEC and the stock
exchange, but made no mention of Justice Department inquiries. The
company, said the spokeswoman, is not aware of any indication of
wrongdoing in the merger. She declined to comment further.
   Dow Jones, which publishes The Wall Street Journal, was ordered
to turn over copies of news reports on Squibb issued July 25 to July
27 _ the day the merger was announced _ and to verify the times when
the items were issued.
   On July 26, Dow Jones' Professional Investor Report noted Wall
Street speculation about a major pharmaceutical industry takeover,
but quoted analysts who discounted the speculation.
   The subpoena also ordered a Dow Jones official to appear before a
grand jury Friday at the U.S. District Court in New York.
   A Dow Jones spokesman, Charlie Stabler, said the company would
not provide the materials requested because they are available in
the public domain.
   Officials of the three agencies refused to confirm or deny their
was an investigation.
   Squibb's stock rose from $24.75 a share to $112.50 on July 27,
the day the merger was announced. The deal was disclosed before the
markets opened that day.
   Under the terms of the merger, expected to be finalized in
October, Squibb shareholders will receive 2.4 shares of
Bristol-Myers stock for each share of Squibb. The new company,
Bristol-Myers Squibb Co., will become the world's second-largest
pharmaceutical house, after Merck &amp; Co. of Rahway.
   In the three days prior to the announcement, Squibb shares rose
nearly $5 per share on active trading as Wall Street observers
speculated that a buyout of Squibb was in the works. Rumors focused
on Glaxo, a British drug giant.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
