<DOCNO> AP890824-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-24-89 2250EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-PrimeBoard     08-24 0342</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Prime Board,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>J.H. Whitney Partners Take Seats On New Prime Board</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Computer Inc.'s board of directors resigned
Thursday to make way for nominees backed by J.H. Whitney &amp; Co., a
New York venture capital firm that stepped in as the computer
company was battling a hostile takeover.
   The resignations were part of a $1 billion-plus buyout that puts
J.H. Whitney in control of the Natick-based minicomputer maker,
which has suffered major losses during its 10-month battle against
MAI Basic Four Inc. of Tustin, Calif.
   After Prime board members were re-elected at the annual meeting
Thursday, all but one stepped down after electing four Whitney
nominees to the board. Incumbent director John S. Dulaney was to
remain on the board until Whitney completes its tender offer next
week, officials said.
   The new board immediately elected James F. McDonald as Prime's
new president. He succeeds Anthony L. Craig, who has held the post
since November and chose to resign after Whitney completes its
tender offer.
   New board members include Whitney partners Russell E. Planitzer,
Don E. Ackerman and Peter M. Castleman. Also named was George C.
Sheinberg, a vice president at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Resigning from the board were David J. Dunn, Frank P. Brunetta,
Anthony L. Craig, John E. Nolan, Jr., John E. Sheehan and Harold A.
Strickland.
   Whitney has tendered a $20-a-share offer for 49.5 million shares
of Prime common stock, which the company accepted a week ago. The
firm also offered to exchange notes with a face value of $22 a share
for the remaining 21 percent of Prime's shares.
   Securities analysts said those notes would trade at a discount.
They estimated the total value of the deal at $17 to $18.50 a share,
or $1.06 billion to $1.16 billion.
   Prime netted a profit of $19 million on sales of $1.6 billion in
1988. But in the last three quarters it recorded over $38 million in
losses, which it attributed to the cost of defending itself against
the takeover and slow sales of minicomputers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
